ref={{sfnref|Paytress|1995}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Pettigrew|first=Jason|year=1991|title=Godflesh: the Power of Positive Paradoxes|magazine=Alternative Press|volume=5|number=36|pages=22\u201323|ref={{sfnref|Pettigrew|1991}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Pettigrew|first=Jason|year=1996|title=Watch Yourself and Watch What You Say|magazine=Alternative Press|number=92|pages=44\u201351|ref={{sfnref|Pettigrew|1996}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|date=20 August 1988|title=Detonation Angels|magazine=Melody Maker|pages=28\u201330|ref={{sfnref|Reynolds|1988}}}}\n* {{Cite news|last=Serba|first=John|date=22 July 2001|title= Operatic Vocals, Industrial Rhythms Mix For a Sound Distinctly ... German|work=[[The Grand Rapids Press]]|page=B6|ref={{sfnref|Serba|2001}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last1=Stud|first1=B.|last2=Stud|first2=T|date=20 June 1987|title=Heaven Up Here|magazine=Melody Maker|pages=26\u201327|ref={{sfnref|Stud & Stud|1987}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|title=The Ministry of Noise|date=March 1989|magazine=Modern Keyboard|pages=49\u201350|ref={{sfnref|The Ministry of Noise|1989}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Dave|year=1994|title=Industrial Revolution|location=Los Angeles, CA|publisher=Cleopatra|ref={{sfnref|Thompson|1994}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Vale|first1=V.|authorlink=V. Vale|last2=Juno|first2=A.|year=1983|title=[[RE/Search #6-#7: Industrial Culture Handbook]]|location=San Francisco, CA|publisher=RE/SEARCH PUBLICATIONS|ref={{Sfnref|Vale & Juno|1983}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Wiederhorn|first=Jon|year=1994|title=Industrious Metal|magazine=Pulse|number=64|pages=64|ref={{sfnref|Wiederhorn|1994}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Yates|first=Catherine|year=2001|title=Souls of a New Machine|magazine=Kerrang!|number=871|pages=18\u201320|ref={{sfnref|Yates|2001}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{heavymetal}}\n{{Alternative metal}}\n{{industrial music-footer}}\n{{Goth subculture}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Industrial metal| ]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal genres]]\n[[Category:Electronic music genres]]\n[[Category:Industrial music]]\n[[Category:Fusion music genres]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox music genre\n| name = Industrial metal\n|bgcolor             =  #BB0022\n|color               = white\n| stylistic_origins  = {{hlist|[[Industrial rock]]|[[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]]}}\n|cultural_origins    = Mid-1980s; United States, Germany, and Switzerland\n|instruments         = \n|derivatives         = {{hlist|[[Neue Deutsche h\u00e4rte]]|[[nu metal]]}}\n|fusiongenres        =\n|subgenrelist        =\n|subgenres           =\n|regional_scenes     =\n|other_topics        =\n* [[Alternative metal]]<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/><ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=style|id=alternative-metal-ma0000012328|pure_url=yes}}|title=Alternative Metal|work=Allmusic|publisher=All Media Network|accessdate=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all|quote=The first wave of alternative metal bands fused heavy metal with prog-rock (Jane's Addiction, Primus), garage punk (Soundgarden, Corrosion of Conformity), noise-rock (the Jesus Lizard, Helmet), funk (Faith No More, Living Colour), rap (Faith No More, Biohazard), '''industrial (Ministry, Nine Inch Nails)''', psychedelia (Soundgarden, Monster Magnet), and even world music (later Sepultura)...By the latter half of the '90s, most new alt-metal bands were playing some combination of simplified thrash, rap, '''industrial''', hardcore punk, and grunge.}}</ref>\n* [[avant-garde metal]]\n* [[NWOAHM]]\n* [[thrash metal]]\n}}\n\n'''Industrial metal''' is the fusion of [[heavy metal music]] and [[industrial music]], typically employing repeating metal guitar [[riffs]], [[sampling (music)|sampling]], synthesizer or [[music sequencer|sequencer]] lines, and distorted vocals.<ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web|url= {{Allmusic|class=style|id=industrial-metal-ma0000012276|pure_url=yes}}|title= Industrial Metal|work=[[Allmusic]]|publisher=[[All Media Network]]|accessdate=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Prominent industrial metal acts include [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]], [[Godflesh]], [[KMFDM]] and [[Nine Inch Nails]].{{sfn|Di Perna A|1995|p=69}}<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Rough Guide to Heavy Metal|last=Berelian|first=Essi|publisher=Rough Guides|year=2005|isbn=1-84353-415-0|location=London|pages=131, 225\u2013227, 252\u2013254}}</ref>\n\nIndustrial metal developed in the late 1980s, as industrial and metal began to fuse into a common genre.{{sfn|Di Perna A|1995|p=69}}  Industrial metal did well in the early 1990s, particularly in North America,{{sfn|Wiederhorn|1994|p=64}} with the success of groups such as [[Nine Inch Nails]]. The industrial metal movement began to fade in the latter half of the 1990s.<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Wolf-R\u00fcdiger M\u00fchlmann|title=DIVISION ALPHA \u2014 Fazium One|url=https://www.rockhard.de/megazine/reviewarchiv/review-anzeigen.html?tx_rxsearch_pi1%5Breview%5D=4092|magazine=Rock Hard|issue=155|year=1999|language=de|accessdate=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909191051/https://www.rockhard.de/megazine/reviewarchiv/review-anzeigen.html?tx_rxsearch_pi1%5Breview%5D=4092|archivedate=2017-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Early innovators===\nThough electric guitars had been used by industrial artists since the early days of the genre,{{sfn|Di Perna A|1995|p=69}} archetypal industrial groups such as [[Throbbing Gristle]] displayed a strong anti-rock stance.{{Sfn|Paytress|1995|pp=92, 94}} British [[post-punk]] band [[Killing Joke]] pioneered the crossing over between styles,{{sfn|Chantler|2002|p=54}} and was an influence on major acts associated with industrial metal such as [[Ministry (band)|Ministry]], [[Godflesh]], and [[Nine Inch Nails]].<ref name=\"decibel july 2007\">{{Cite magazine |last=Bennett, J. |date=July 2007 |title=Killing Joke |url=http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/jul2007/killingjoke.aspx |magazine=Decibel Magazine |issue=33 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080315022956/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/jul2007/killingjoke.aspx |archive-date=2008-03-15 |access-date=2017-09-09 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Another pioneer industrial rock group, [[Big Black]], also impacted some later groups.{{sfn|Chantler|2002|p=54}}<ref name=guardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jul/18/electronicmusic|title=Till deaf us do part|author=Chick, Stevie|date=2008-07-18|work=The Guardian|accessdate=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909185843/https://www.theguardian.com/music/2008/jul/18/electronicmusic|archivedate=2017-09-09}}</ref>\n\nBy the late 1980s industrial and heavy metal began to fuse into a common genre,{{sfn|Di Perna A|1995|p=69}} with Godflesh's [[Godflesh (EP)|self-titled EP]]<ref name=\"godflesh88\">{{Cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=godflesh-mw0000204753|pure_url=yes}} |title=Godflesh - Godflesh |last=Walters |first=Martin |website=AllMusic |publisher=All Media Network |access-date=2017-09-15 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and Ministry's ''[[The Land of Rape and Honey]]'' at the forefront. Godflesh was founded by former [[Napalm Death]] guitarist [[Justin Broadrick]].<ref name=\"decibel march 2007\">{{Cite magazine |last=Bartkewicz, Anthony |date=March 2007 |title=Justin Broadrick |url=http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/mar2007/justinbroadrick.aspx |magazine=Decibel Magazine |issue=29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080223185218/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/mar2007/justinbroadrick.aspx |archive-date=2008-02-23 |access-date=2017-09-09 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> Drawing from a wide array of influences\u2014[[power electronics (music)|power electronics]] forefathers [[Whitehouse (band)|Whitehouse]],{{sfn|Kaye|1992|p=16}} [[noise rock]] band [[Swans (band)|Swans]],<ref>{{cite newspaper|url=http://www.metrospirit.com/index.php?ShowArticle_ID=11012410074046204&cat=1993101070588705 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090210144406/http://www.metrospirit.com/index.php?ShowArticle_ID=11012410074046204&cat=1993101070588705 |url-status=dead |archive-date=10 February 2009 |title=Justin Broadrick: Existing through risk |author=Ruffin, Josh |date=23 October 2007 |newspaper=Metro Spirit|issue=19.13 |accessdate=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all}}</ref> [[ambient music]] creator [[Brian Eno]]<ref name=\"decibel march 2007\" /> and fellow [[Birmingham]] hard rockers [[Black Sabbath]]{{sfn|Pettigrew|1991|p=22}}\u2014the Godflesh sound was once described as \"''[[Pornography (album)|Pornography]]''-era [[The Cure|Cure]] on [[Quaaludes]]\".{{sfn|Thompson|1994|p=44}} Though not a top-seller,{{sfn|Mudrian|2004|p=186}} Godflesh nonetheless became an influential act, their name mentioned by [[Korn]],{{sfn|Yates|2001|p=19}} [[Metallica]],{{sfn|Alexander|1995|p=52}} [[Danzig (band)|Danzig]],<ref>{{cite magazine|url= http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/jan2007/glenndanzig.aspx|title= Glenn Danzig|author= Bennett, J.|date=January 2007|magazine= Decibel Magazine|issue=27|accessdate=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080223185159/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/features/jan2007/glenndanzig.aspx |archivedate = 2008-02-23}}</ref> [[Faith No More]],{{sfn|M\u00f6rat|1990|p=14}} and [[Fear Factory]].{{sfn|Yates|2001|p=19}}\n\nMinistry emerged from the scene surrounding [[Wax Trax! Records]], a Chicago label dedicated to industrial music.{{sfn|Blush|2001|p=223}} Ministry's initial foray into guitar rock happened during a recording session of ''The Land of Rape and Honey'' on [[Southern Studios]], in London.{{sfn|Gill|1996|p=88}} The band's frontman, the Cuban-born [[Al Jourgensen]], explained this transition:{{sfn|The Ministry of Noise|1989|p=49}}\n\n{{Quote |quote=Rediscovering the guitar on this record was almost like the first day I got my [[Fairlight CMI|Fairlight]]. The possibilities just seemed endless on something that had seemed so limiting before. That's really funny. I started out as a guitarist, but I hadn't really touched a guitar in five years. Then I heard that first [[Audio feedback|feedback]] come out of the [[Marshall Amplification|Marshall]] [[Guitar amplifier|stack]] and all of a sudden it was like there was a whole new parameter within guitar playing itself \u2013 especially in combination with sounds that you get out of a [[Electronic keyboard|keyboard]].}}\n[[File:Rev cocks.jpg|thumb|right|Al Jourgensen (center) with [[Revolting Cocks]]]]\nJourgensen seemed particularly fond of [[thrash metal]]. After the release of ''Land'', he recruited guitarist [[Mike Scaccia]] from Texas thrashers [[Rigor Mortis (band)|Rigor Mortis]].<ref name=\"AllMusic_Scaccia\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=mn0000955452|pure_url=yes}}|author=Whitney Z. Gomes|title=Mike Scaccia|work=AllMusic|publisher=All Media Network|accessdate=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On one occasion, Jourgensen told the press that [[Sepultura]] was his favorite band.{{sfn|Barcinski|1992|p=27}} He also expressed the desire to produce a Metallica album.{{sfn|Gitter|1990|p=77}} Jourgensen's interest in [[Electronic dance music|dance-oriented electronic music]] did not entirely fade, however; he also formed the side-project [[Revolting Cocks]], a more [[electronic body music]]-inflected collaboration with Richard 23 of [[Front 242]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/revolting-cocks-mn0000888100/biography|title=Revolting Cocks \u2014 Biography|author=Jeffries, David|work=Allmusic|publisher=All Media Network|accessdate=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729194242/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/revolting-cocks-mn0000888100/biography|archivedate=2017-07-29}}</ref>\n\nGerman band [[KMFDM]] was another seminal industrial metal group. Although not a metal fan, KMFDM leader [[Sascha Konietzko]]'s \"infatuation with ripping off metal [[Lick (music)|licks]]\" stemmed from his experiments with [[E-MU Systems|E-mu]]'s [[E-mu Emax|Emax]] [[Sampler (musical instrument)|sampler]] in late 1986. He told ''[[Guitar World]]'' that,{{sfn|Di Perna A|1995|p=69}}\n{{quote|It was just interesting to use it as a kind of [[white noise]] reinforcement for our music. All of a sudden heavy metal was free from all those [[tempo]] changes and boring attitudes it always had. What I always hated most about heavy metal was that the best riffs came only once and were never repeated. So the fascination, actually, was to sample a great riff, [[Music loop|loop]] it, and play it over and over again.}}\n\nA Swiss trio, [[The Young Gods]], brushed with the style on their second album, ''[[L'Eau Rouge]]'' (1989). Prior to its release, singer Franz Treichler declared:{{sfn|Reynolds|1988|p=28}}\n\n{{quote|We just wanted to hear guitars. We missed the attack of '[[Envoy\u00e9!|Envoy\u00e9]]'. That's what we want to hear right now, pure power. A metal sound that isn't revivalist, isn't biker style, [[speed metal]] style, ''any'' style, just WHAP!}}\n\nCanadian thrash metal band Malhavoc became another early pioneer of the genre when they began to mix thrash metal with industrial music in the late 1980s<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/artist/79297-Malhavoc|title=Malhavoc|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2017-09-27|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928010206/https://www.discogs.com/artist/79297-Malhavoc|archivedate=2017-09-28}}</ref>\n\n[[Pigface]], formed by [[Martin Atkins]] and including Ministry drummer [[Bill Rieflin]], emerged as an industrial metal collective of sorts, participating with many figures from the [[noise rock]] and industrial worlds.<ref name=\"Pigface Allmusic\">{{Cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=pigface-mn0000340462/biography|pure_url=yes}} |title=Pigface \u2014 Biography |last=Prato |first=Greg |last2=Erlewine |first2=Stephen Thomas |authorlink2=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |website=AllMusic |publisher=All Media Network |access-date=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Nine Inch Nails, the \"one-man-band\" formed by [[Trent Reznor]], brought the genre to mainstream audiences with albums such as the [[Grammy]]-winning ''[[Broken (Nine Inch Nails EP)|Broken]]''<ref name=\"ningrammy\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards/winners-nominees/214 |title=Winners: Best Metal Performance |website=grammy.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070312025815/http://www.grammy.com/GRAMMY_Awards/Winners/Results.aspx?title=&winner=nine%20inch%20nails&year=0&genreID=0&hp=1 |archive-date=12 March 2007 |url-status=dead |access-date=2017-09-09 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and the best-selling ''[[The Downward Spiral]]'', accompanied by their groundbreaking performance at [[Woodstock '94]]. The [[rivethead]] subculture also developed at this time,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.re-constriction.com |title= Re-Constriction |publisher= Cargoland! |accessdate= 11 September 2007 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070930021047/http://www.re-constriction.com/ |archivedate= 30 September 2007 }}</ref> along with the so-called \"coldwave\" subgenre, which encompassed [[Chemlab]], [[16 Volt]], and [[Acumen Nation]].<ref>Ilker Y\u00fccel, interview with Jared Louche, ReGen Magazine, 20 January 2008. {{cite web|url=http://www.regenmag.com/Interviews-214-Chemlab.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080509070142/http://www.regenmag.com/Interviews-214-Chemlab.html |archivedate=2008-05-09 }} Access date: 28 December 2008.</ref> Some [[electro-industrial]] groups adopted industrial metal techniques in this period, including [[Skinny Puppy]] (on their ''[[Rabies (Skinny Puppy album)|Rabies]]'', co-produced by Jourgensen),<ref name=\"Allmusic Rabies\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/rabies-mw0000654322 |title=Rabies \u2014 Overview |last=DiGravina |first=Tim |website=Allmusic |publisher=All Media Network |access-date=2017-09-09 |df=mdy-all |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829042637/http://www.allmusic.com/album/rabies-mw0000654322 |archivedate=2017-08-29 }}</ref> and [[Front Line Assembly]].<ref>{{Cite magazine |url=http://www.lastsigh.com/interviews99/fla98.htm |title=Front Line Assembly \u2013 Bill Leeb \u2013 An Interview |last=Semczuk |first=Karine |date=31 October 1998 |publisher=Last Sigh Magazine |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010710184010/http://www.lastsigh.com/interviews99/fla98.htm |archive-date=2001-07-10 |access-date=2017-09-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nBritish band [[Pitchshifter]], formed in 1989 by brothers [[JS Clayden|Jon]] and Mark Clayden, also started as an industrial metal band.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicmight.com/artist/united+kingdom/nottinghamshire/nottingham/pitchshifter |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203005613/http://www.musicmight.com/artist/united+kingdom/nottinghamshire/nottingham/pitchshifter |archivedate=2013-12-03 }}</ref> The band later included elements of [[drum and bass]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/pitchshifter-mn0000851240/biography |title=Pitchshifter \u2014 Biography |last=Swihart |first=Stanton |website=allmusic |access-date=2017-09-09 |df=mdy-all |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909192725/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/pitchshifter-mn0000851240/biography |archivedate=2017-09-09 }}</ref> Frontman JS mentions:<ref name=\"psi\">{{cite magazine|last=Young|first=Craig|title=earpollution profiles \u2013 pitchshifter [page 2]|issue=0|volume=1|url=http://www.earpollution.com/issuezero/profiles/pitchshifter2.html|magazine=Earpollution|access-date=2017-09-09|df=mdy-all|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170909190438/http://www.earpollution.com/issuezero/profiles/pitchshifter2.html|archivedate=2017-09-09}}</ref>\n{{quote|[...]In the early days we were inspired by bands like [[Head of David]] and [[Swans (band)|Swans]] and the like... coming out of punk into the weird, angry, total noise, kind of pre-industrial music. It gets called industrial but I don't know if it really is.}}\n\n===Industrial thrash and death metal===\nIndustrial metal's popularity led a number of successful [[thrash metal]] groups, including [[Megadeth]], [[Sepultura]], and [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], to request remixes by \"industrial\" artists.{{sfn|Arnopp A|1993|p=41}} Some musicians emerging from the [[death metal]] scene, such as [[Fear Factory]], [[Nailbomb]], [[Autokrator (metal band)|Autokrator]] and [[Meathook Seed]], also began to experiment with industrial. Fear Factory, from Los Angeles,<ref name=\"AM FF\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/fear-factory-mn0000167320/biography |title=Fear Factory \u2014 Biography |last=Huey |first=Steve |website=AllMusic |publisher=All Media Network |access-date=2017-09-15 |df=mdy-all |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107051807/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/fear-factory-mn0000167320/biography |archivedate=2016-01-07 }}</ref> were initially influenced by the [[Earache Records|Earache]] roster (namely [[Godflesh]], [[Napalm Death]] and [[Bolt Thrower]]).<ref>{{cite AV media|people= Cordero, Amber (director)|date=2001-12-18|df=mdy-all|url=|title= Fear Factory: Digital Connectivity|medium = motion picture|location = United States of America|publisher= Roadrunner Records}}</ref> The German band [[Oomph!]] after their second album [[Sperm (album)|Sperm]] started to play industrial metal combined with elements of [[death metal]] and [[groove metal]] until the album [[Plastik]]. Sepultura singer [[Max Cavalera]]'s [[Nailbomb]], a collaboration with [[Alex Newport]], also practiced a combination of extreme metal and industrial production techniques.<ref>{{cite web|author=Jeff Maki|work=Live-Metal.net|year=2007|url=http://www.live-metal.net/revisited_nailbomb.html |title=Revisited - Nailbomb - Point Blank|access-date=2017-09-13|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081225084617/http://www.live-metal.net/revisited_nailbomb.html |archivedate=2008-12-25 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> A lesser-known example of industrial death metal is Meathook Seed, made up of members of Napalm Death and the Florida death metal group [[Obituary (band)|Obituary]]. An industrial music fan, Obituary guitarist Trevor Peres suggested [[drum machines]] for ''[[The End Complete]]'',{{sfn|Arnopp B|1993|p=44}} Obituary's most successful album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=16769|title=It's Official: CANNIBAL CORPSE Are The Top-Selling Death Metal Band Of The SoundScan Era|date=2003-11-17|publisher=BLABBERMOUTH.NET|accessdate=2017-09-13|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080602230201/http://www.roadrunnerrecords.com/blabbermouth.net/news.aspx?mode=Article&newsitemID=16769|archivedate=2 June 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref> The other band members' refusal led him to form [[Meathook Seed]].{{sfn|Arnopp B|1993|p=44}}\n\n===Industrial black metal===\n\nIn the early years of the 21st century, groups from the [[black metal]] scene began to incorporate elements of industrial music. [[Mysticum]], formed in 1991,<ref>Marty Rytkonen, Mysticum interview, ''Worm Gear'' No. 8, {{cite web |url=http://www.fmp666.com/moonlight/mysticum2.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924014037/http://www.fmp666.com/moonlight/mysticum2.html |archivedate=2015-09-24 }} Access date: 11 January 2009.</ref> was the first of these groups.<ref name=lom>Roel F., Interview with Treachery, ''Lords of Metal'' issue 87, December 2008. [http://www.lordsofmetal.nl/showinterview.php?id=2438&lang=en] Access date: 3 December 2008.</ref> [[D\u00f8dheimsgard|DHG]] (D\u00f8dheimsgard), [[Thorns (band)|Thorns]] from Norway and [[Blut Aus Nord]], [[N.K.V.D (metal band)|N.K.V.D.]] and [[Blacklodge]] from France, have been acclaimed for their incorporation of industrial elements.<ref>Chris Dick, \"Blut Aus Nord\", ''Decibel'', December 2006. {{cite web|url=http://www.decibelmagazine.com/upfront/dec2006/blutausnord.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070205141318/http://www.decibelmagazine.com/upfront/dec2006/blutausnord.aspx |archivedate=2007-02-05 }} Access date: 22 July 2008.</ref> Other industrial black metal musicians include [[Samael (band)|Samael]],<ref>Samael, metal-archives.com, 3 September 2011. {{cite web |url=http://www.metal-archives.com/bands/Samael/31 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-07-30 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725053714/http://www.metal-archives.com/bands/Samael/31 |archivedate=2016-07-25 }} Access date: 10 September 2011.</ref> [[The Axis of Perdition]],<ref>Matt Mooring, Deleted Scenes from the Transition Hospital review, Metalreview.com, 28 March 2005. {{cite web|url=http://www.metalreview.com/Reviews/1561/The-Axis-Of-Perdition-Deleted-Scenes-From-The-Transition-Hospital.aspx |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227105037/http://www.metalreview.com/Reviews/1561/The-Axis-Of-Perdition-Deleted-Scenes-From-The-Transition-Hospital.aspx |archivedate=2012-02-27 }} Access date: 4 January 2009.</ref> [[Aborym]],<ref>Gothtronic. {{cite web |url=http://www.gothtronic.com/?page=23&band=777 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-25 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100207214210/http://gothtronic.com/?page=23&band=777 |archivedate=2010-02-07 }} Access date: 4 January 2009.</ref> and [[...And Oceans]].<ref>''Globaldomination'', 26 September 2007. {{cite web|url=http://www.globaldomination.se/reviews/and-oceans-amgod |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-01-25 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091111013457/http://www.globaldomination.se/reviews/and-oceans-amgod |archivedate=2009-11-11 }} Access date: 4 January 2009.</ref> In addition, [[The Kovenant]],<ref>Antti J. Ravelin, Nexus Polaris review, Allmusic. [{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r343514|pure_url=yes}}] Access date: 11 January 2009.</ref> [[Mortiis]] and [[Ulver]] emerged from the Norwegian black metal scene, but later chose to experiment with industrial music.<ref>Stefanos Zachariadis, Blood Inside review, Metal Invader, 3 May 2005. {{cite web|url=http://www.metal-invader.com/db/reviews-1914.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-06-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927230459/http://www.metal-invader.com/db/reviews-1914.html |archivedate=2007-09-27 }} Access date: 9 January 2009.</ref><ref>Mark Hensch, Some Kind of Heroin review, ''Thrashpit''. {{cite web |url=http://www.rocknworld.com/thrashpit/reviews/07/Mortiis-SomeKindofHeroinMH.shtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218111610/http://www.rocknworld.com/thrashpit/reviews/07/Mortiis-SomeKindofHeroinMH.shtml |archivedate=2014-12-18 }} Access date: 9 January 2009.</ref>\n\n=== Progressive industrial metal ===\nSeveral artists with their roots in [[progressive metal|progressive]] music, though not often associated with industrial metal scene, also incorporated industrial textures into their music. Later-era [[King Crimson]], whose [[2000s (decade)|2000s]] albums were referred as \"industrial art metal\"<ref>Langdon Hickman, ''A Beginner\u2019s Guide to the epic music of King Crimson''. {{cite web |url=https://www.treblezine.com/beginners-guide-king-crimson/|title=Archived copy |accessdate=2019-09-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190624153819/https://www.treblezine.com/beginners-guide-king-crimson/ |archivedate=2019-06-24 }} Access date: 15 September 2019.</ref>, and [[OSI (band)|OSI]] can be named as examples of progressive industrial metal. Several acts associated with extreme metal subgenres also mix progressive and [[avant-garde metal]] with industrial, those include the [[Hungary|Hungarian]] experimental metal act [[Thy Catafalque]]<ref>Thy Catafalque \u2013 Geometria Review {{cite web |url=https://www.angrymetalguy.com/thy-catafalque-geometria-review/|title=Archived copy |accessdate=2019-09-15 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612134949/http://www.angrymetalguy.com/thy-catafalque-geometria-review/|archivedate=2018-06-12 }} Access date: 15 September 2019.</ref>, [[Blut aus Nord]] and [[Norway|Norwegian]] band [[Shining (Norwegian band)|Shining]] with their critically acclaimed ''[[Blackjazz]]'' album, which blended progressive rock<ref>{{Cite web|title=Blackjazz review|url=http://www.popmatters.com/pm/review/119585-shining-blackjazz/|first=Adrien|last=Begrand|date=3 February 2010|accessdate=30 April 2010|work=PopMatters|publisher=PopMatters Media}}</ref>, black metal, [[free jazz]] and industrial.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Blackjazz review|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1709437|pure_url=yes}}|first=Phil|last=Freeman|accessdate=30 April 2010|work=Allmusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref> [[Canada|Canadian]] artist [[Devin Townsend]], the founder of industrial [[thrash metal]]<ref>{{Allmusic |class=album |id=city-mw0000616904 |accessdate=August 22, 2011 }}</ref> band [[Strapping Young Lad]], later fused industrial with progressive metal during his prolific solo career.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ocean Machine: Biomech review|url=http://www.metalstorm.net/pub/review.php?review_id=5211|date=|accessdate=|work=|publisher=MetalStorm}}</ref>\n\n===Commercial rise===\n{{Main|Industrial rock sales and awards}}\n[[File:NIN2009torontoVFEST.png|thumb|300px|[[Nine Inch Nails]] in concert, 2009]]\n[[File:Rammstein Live at Madison Square Garden.jpg|thumb|300px|Rammstein Live at Madison Square Garden.]]\nIndustrial metal blossomed in the early 1990s, particularly in North America,{{sfn|Wiederhorn|1994|p=64}} where it would eventually sell close to 35 million units.<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php \n |title=Search Certification Database \n |publisher=Canadian Recording Industry Association (CRIA) \n |accessdate=27 June 2008 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100501065534/http://www.cria.ca/cert_db_search.php \n |archivedate=1 May 2010 \n}}</ref><ref name=riaa>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH \n |title=GOLD AND PLATINUM \u2013 Searchable Database \n |publisher=RIAA \n |accessdate=12 December 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626050454/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH \n |archivedate=26 June 2007 \n}}</ref> It first became a commercial force in 1992 when Nine Inch Nails' ''[[Broken (Nine Inch Nails EP)|Broken]]'' and Ministry's ''[[Psalm 69: The Way to Succeed and the Way to Suck Eggs|Psalm 69]]'' went [[Music recording sales certification|platinum]] in America, though the latter took three years to reach that status.<ref name=\"riaa\"/> Both groups were nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance|Best Metal Performance]] in the 1992 [[Grammy Awards]], with Nine Inch Nails winning.<ref name=\"ningrammy\" /> Two years later, Nine Inch Nails released ''[[The Downward Spiral]]'', which debuted at No. 2,<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/charts/1994-03-26/billboard-200|title= Top Music Charts \u2013 Hot 100 \u2013 Billboard 200 \u2013 Music Genre Sales|publisher= Billboard Music Charts|accessdate= 5 January 2008|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130508150323/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1994-03-26/billboard-200|archivedate= 8 May 2013}}</ref> and would eventually go quadruple-platinum.<ref name=\"riaa\"/> This record is considered by ''[[AllMusic]]'' as \"one of the bleakest multi-platinum albums ever\".<ref name= allnin>{{cite web|url= {{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p5033|pure_url=yes}}|title= (((Nine Inch Nails > Biography)))|author= Huey, Steve|website= allmusic|accessdate=9 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n{{Quote|text=Overall, popular heavy rock music has changed to become more \"industrialized\". This robbed the industrial hardcore movement of any hopes of establishing a new identity of its own. The style is dead (or at least dying); the elements of the style continue on in new musical settings.<br />{{Nb10}}\u2013 David A. Locher, Professor of Sociology, [[Missouri State University]], 1998<ref>{{cite book|editor=Jonathan S. Epstein|author=David A. Locher|chapter=The Industrial Identity Crisis: The Failure of a Newly Forming Subculture to Identify Itself|title=Youth Culture: Identity in a Postmodern World|url=https://archive.org/details/youthcultureiden00epst/page/100|url-access=registration|publisher=Wiley-Blackwell Publishers|year=1998|pages=[https://archive.org/details/youthcultureiden00epst/page/100 100\u2013117]|isbn=1-55786-851-4|via=the Internet Archive}}</ref>{{rp|115}}}}\n\nFollowing Nine Inch Nails' success, [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]], led by a prot\u00e9g\u00e9 of Reznor's,<ref>Staff. (10 May 2000) [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431688/20000510/marilyn_manson.jhtml Manson, Reznor mend fences] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081001122313/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1431688/20000510/marilyn_manson.jhtml |date=2008-10-01 }} MTV. Retrieved 1 March 2009.</ref> came to prominence.<ref name=\"Stephen Thomas Erlewine\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/antichrist-superstar-mw0000188724|title=''Antichrist Superstar'' review|author=Stephen Thomas Erlewine|website=Allmusic|accessdate=1 March 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525142511/http://www.allmusic.com/album/antichrist-superstar-mw0000188724|archivedate=25 May 2016}}</ref> The group's live performance and its transgressive appeal was often more commented on than their music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/marilyn-manson-mn0000825251/biography|title=Marilyn Manson \u2014 Biography|author=Jason Ankeny|website=Allmusic|accessdate=1 March 2009|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426172735/http://www.allmusic.com/artist/marilyn-manson-mn0000825251/biography|archivedate=26 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIndustrial metal reached its commercial zenith in the latter half of the 1990s \u2013 according to the [[RIAA]] databases, its top-selling artists sold around 17.5 million units combined.<ref name=\"riaa\"/><ref name= indgroups>Groups such as Fear Factory, [[Filter (band)|Filter]], [[Marilyn Manson (band)|Marilyn Manson]], Ministry, Nine Inch Nails, [[Orgy (band)|Orgy]], [[Rammstein]], [[Stabbing Westward]], [[Static-X]] and [[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]], plus [[Rob Zombie]]'s solo career.</ref> Records by major industrial metal artists routinely debuted on the top spots of the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart: [[Rob Zombie]]'s ''[[Hellbilly Deluxe]]'' (No. 5),<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/charts/1998-09-12/billboard-200|title= Top Music Charts \u2013 Hot 100 \u2013 Billboard 200 \u2013 Music Genre Sales|publisher= Billboard Music Charts|accessdate= 2 January 2008|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130508160520/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1998-09-12/billboard-200|archivedate= 8 May 2013}}</ref> Marilyn Manson's ''[[Antichrist Superstar]]'' (No. 3),<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=antichrist-superstar-r241643/charts-awards|pure_url=yes}} Antichrist Superstar Allmusic Billboard charts & awards]. Allmusic.com. Retrieved 30 November 2010.</ref> and Nine Inch Nails' ''[[The Fragile (Nine Inch Nails album)|The Fragile]]'' (No. 1).<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/charts/1999-10-09/billboard-200|title= Top Music Charts \u2013 Hot 100 \u2013 Billboard 200 \u2013 Music Genre Sales|publisher= Billboard Music Charts|accessdate= 2 January 2008|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130508141952/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1999-10-09/billboard-200|archivedate= 8 May 2013}}</ref> A number of industrial metal albums performed well on Billboard's ''[[Top Heatseekers|Heatseekers]]'' chart: [[Filter (band)|Filter]]'s ''[[Short Bus (album)|Short Bus]]'' (No. 3),<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=294&cfgn=Albums&cfn=Heatseekers&ci=3020133&cdi=6938407&cid=05%2F13%2F1995|title= Top Music Charts \u2013 Hot 100 \u2013 Billboard 200 \u2013 Music Genre Sales|publisher= Billboard Music Charts|accessdate=5 January 2008}}</ref> [[Stabbing Westward]]'s ''[[Wither Blister Burn & Peel|Wither Blister Burn + Peel]]'' (No. 1),<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttp://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=294&cfgn=Albums&cfn=Heatseekers&ci=3022498&cdi=7026482&cid=02%2F10%2F1996|title= Top Music Charts \u2013 Hot 100 \u2013 Billboard 200 \u2013 Music Genre Sales|publisher= Billboard Music Charts|accessdate=5 January 2008}}</ref> [[Rammstein]]'s ''[[Sehnsucht (Rammstein album)|Sehnsucht]]'' (No. 2),<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttp://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=294&cfgn=Albums&cfn=Heatseekers&ci=3030569&cdi=7317884&cid=05%2F02%2F1998|title= Top Music Charts \u2013 Hot 100 \u2013 Billboard 200 \u2013 Music Genre Sales|publisher= Billboard Music Charts|accessdate=5 January 2008}}</ref> [[Orgy (band)|Orgy]]'s ''[[Candyass]]'' (No. 1),<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=294&cfgn=Albums&cfn=Heatseekers&ci=3031649&cdi=7355790&cid=09%2F05%2F1998|title= Top Music Charts \u2013 Hot 100 \u2013 Billboard 200 \u2013 Music Genre Sales|publisher= Billboard Music Charts|accessdate=5 January 2008}}</ref> and [[Static-X]]'s ''[[Wisconsin Death Trip (album)|Wisconsin Death Trip]]'' (No. 1).<ref>{{cite web |url=\nhttp://www.billboard.com/bbcom/esearch/chart_display.jsp?cfi=294&cfgn=Albums&cfn=Heatseekers&ci=3035445&cdi=7492857&cid=09%2F25%2F1999|title= Top Music Charts \u2013 Hot 100 \u2013 Billboard 200 \u2013 Music Genre Sales|publisher= Billboard Music Charts|accessdate=5 January 2008}}</ref>\n\nDuring this era, [[Trent Reznor]] was chosen by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' as one of the most influential Americans of 1997.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,986206,00.html|title= Time's 25 most influential americans|date= 21 April 1997|work= TIME|accessdate= 14 December 2007|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080107103639/http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,986206,00.html|archivedate= 7 January 2008}}</ref> The genre's popularity was such that established [[glam metal]] groups, including [[Guns N' Roses]] and [[M\u00f6tley Cr\u00fce]], began to dabble in the style.<ref>New GNR.com [http://www.newgnr.com/band/finck.html] Access date: 4 August 2008.</ref><ref>Dave De Sylvia, ''Generation Swine'' review, [http://www.sputnikmusic.com/album.php?albumid=2790] Access date: 4 August 2008.</ref> Figures from the [[hip hop]] scene also began to seek out collaborations with and remixes from industrial metal musicians.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1427395/19980115/puff_daddy.jhtml|title= Puffy Remixed By Reznor, Deftones, Mascis|date= 15 January 1998|publisher= MTV|accessdate= 21 October 2007|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20081222051737/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1427395/19980115/puff_daddy.jhtml|archivedate= 22 December 2008}}</ref><ref>Nin Chan, ''Rap Reviews'', 25 January 2005 {{cite web |url=http://www.rapreviews.com/archive/BTTL_badblood.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-08-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120819175039/http://www.rapreviews.com/archive/BTTL_badblood.html |archivedate=2012-08-19 }} Access date: 22 July 2008</ref><ref>Dave Maher, Pitchforkmedia news, 16 February 2007 {{cite web|url=http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/41220-el-p-reveals-lp-tracklist-single-with-trent-reznor |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-02-09 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090228121305/http://www.pitchforkmedia.com/article/news/41220-el-p-reveals-lp-tracklist-single-with-trent-reznor |archivedate=2009-02-28 }} Access date: 22 July 2008</ref>\n\nWhen industrial metal climbed the charts of the late 1990s, its sudden popularity was met with negative reactions from the early innovators of [[industrial music]]. [[Peter Christopherson]] told ''[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]'' that he no longer felt any kinship with the industrial scene: \"this is not me, this is not what I'm about\".<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.thewire.co.uk/web/unpublished/coil.html|title= Time Out of Joint|author= Keenan, David|date= 21 July 1998|publisher= THE WIRE \u2013 ADVENTURES IN MODERN MUSIC|accessdate= 8 September 2007|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200608/http://www.thewire.co.uk/web/unpublished/coil.html|archivedate= 27 September 2007}}</ref> [[Lustmord]], a prominent early industrial musician,<ref>John Bush, Lustmord, Allmusic bio. [{{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p19048|pure_url=yes}}] Access date: 21 February 2009.</ref> declared that \"Ministry just doesn't interest [him]\" and \"[he has] no time for all this [[rock and roll]] shit they're doing now.\"{{sfn|Fergunson|1993|p=55}} [[Skinny Puppy]] frontman [[Nivek Ogre]] dismissed Nine Inch Nails as \"[[cock rock]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reinspired.wordpress.com/2010/04/17/memory-lane-skinny-puppy/|title=Memory Lane: Skinny Puppy|date=17 April 2010|website=wordpress.com|accessdate=2 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171013225544/https://reinspired.wordpress.com/2010/04/17/memory-lane-skinny-puppy/|archivedate=13 October 2017}}</ref> but have since patched things up and have even performed on stage together.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ninwiki.com/Skinny_Puppy|title=Skinny Puppy - NinWiki|website=www.ninwiki.com|accessdate=2 May 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011204702/http://www.ninwiki.com/Skinny_Puppy|archivedate=11 October 2014}}</ref>\n\nIndustrial metal suffered a critical backlash at the turn of the millennium. In an April 2000 review for the ''[[Chicago Sun Times]]'', [[Jim DeRogatis]] dismissed Nine Inch Nails' new music as a \"generic brand of industrial thrash\" and accused Ministry of repeating an act that \"was old by 1992\".<ref name=\"jdr2000\">{{cite web|url= http://www.theninhotline.net/archives/articles/xrevw131.shtml|title= Nine Inch Nails stuck in the '90s|author= DeRogatis, Jim|work= Chicago Sun Times|date= April 2000|accessdate= 24 August 2007|url-status= dead|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20070930154709/http://www.theninhotline.net/archives/articles/xrevw131.shtml|archivedate= 30 September 2007}} Archived at [http://www.theninhotline.net The NIN Hotline] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516050555/http://www.theninhotline.net/ |date=2008-05-16 }}.</ref> Although ''The Fragile'' reached the top spot of the ''Billboard'' 200<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.billboard.com/charts/1999-10-09/billboard-200|title= Top Music Charts \u2013 Hot 100 \u2013 Billboard 200 \u2013 Music Genre Sales|publisher= Billboard Music Charts|accessdate= 9 May 2008|url-status= live|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130508141952/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1999-10-09/billboard-200|archivedate= 8 May 2013}}</ref> and went on to earn [[Music recording sales certification|double platinum]] status,<ref name=\"riaa\"/> DeRogatis considered it a \"flop\" nonetheless.<ref name=\"jdr2000\"/>\nAround this time, veteran industrial metal artists (Ministry,{{sfn|Pettigrew|1996|p=46}} Godflesh,{{sfn|Martin|2004|p=25}} and [[White Zombie (band)|White Zombie]]{{sfn|Di Perna B|1995|p=35}}) began to repudiate the industrial label. Sales remained high throughout 2000\u20132005; at least 10 million records were sold during that time frame.<ref name=\"riaa\"/><ref name=\"indgroups\"/> Many groups began to take influence from hip hop and [[electronic music]], in addition to industrial metal. As a result, acts like [[Powerman 5000]] are often described as industrial metal as well as [[nu metal]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Michael|last=Mehle|title=Industrial Strength Powerman 5000'S `Action Rockers' Keep the Message Light In A Cacophony of Power Chords|work=[[Rocky Mountain News]]|date=April 25, 1997|page=20D|quote=Powerman 5000 can be called a lot of things ... industrial metal ... with a bit of hip-hop, a touch of funk and an awful lot of energy....}}{{Subscription required|via=HighBeam}}</ref>\n\n==Film and video==\nSeveral industrial metal groups have produced eye-catching videos. These include Godflesh's collaboration with [[Andres Serrano]],<ref>Jay W. Babcock, \"In Godflesh We Trust\", RIP Magazine, December 2006. {{cite web |url=http://www.godflesh.com/articles/article5.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120628102221/http://www.godflesh.com/articles/article5.html |archivedate=2012-06-28 }} Access date: 4 January 2009.</ref> [[Aidan Hughes]]'s graphics for KMFDM,<ref>Aidan Hughes, Interview by Liberation Iannillo, ''Trigger Magazine'', 5 August 2005. {{cite web |url=http://www.triggermagazine.com/archives/2005/08/aidan_hughes.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080821120122/http://www.triggermagazine.com/archives/2005/08/aidan_hughes.html |archivedate=2008-08-21 }} Access date: 4 January 2009.</ref> Nine Inch Nails' work with [[Mark Romanek]],<ref>Ed Gonzalez, ''Slant Magazine'', 5 September 2005. {{cite web |url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/dvd_review.asp?ID=746 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-24 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090904062438/http://www.slantmagazine.com/dvd/dvd_review.asp?ID=746 |archivedate=2009-09-04 }} Access date: 4 January 2009.</ref> [[Rob Zombie]]'s visual work for White Zombie (for which he received the [[MTV Video Music Awards|MTV Video Music Award]] for Best Hard Rock Video),<ref name=jorgl>Stephen Jorgl, \"Rob Zombie on Making Films and Records\", ''Audiohead.net'', 2006. {{cite web |url=http://www.audiohead.net/interviews/robzombie/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-03-24 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130725090705/http://www.audiohead.net/interviews/robzombie/ |archivedate=2013-07-25 }} Access date: 4 January 2009.</ref> and Marilyn Manson's output with [[Richard Kern]]<ref>Kurt B. Reighley, ''Marilyn Manson'', chapter 6, Macmillan, 1998, p. 73.</ref> and [[Floria Sigismondi]].<ref>Mark Dillon, \"Gothic Goddess\", ''American Cinematographer'', August 1998, p. 60-70. {{cite web|url=http://www.floriasigismondi.com/reviews/review00.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-01-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041209135432/http://www.floriasigismondi.com/reviews/review00.html |archivedate=2004-12-09 }} Access date: 4 January 2009.</ref> NIN later collaborated with [[Bill Viola]] for live accompaniment.<ref>Bill Viola artist biography. {{cite web |url=http://www.billviola.com/biograph.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208013450/http://www.billviola.com/biograph.htm |archivedate=2014-12-08 }} Access date: 4 January 2009.</ref> Trent Reznor also produced the soundtracks for the films ''[[Natural Born Killers]]'' and ''[[Lost Highway (film)|Lost Highway]]'', and served as \"musical consultant\" for ''[[Man on Fire (2004 film)|Man on Fire]]''.<ref>David Browne, \"'Killer' Riffs,\" ''Entertainment Weekly'', 23 September 1994. {{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,303796,00.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-01-10 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090421103818/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,303796,00.html |archivedate=2009-04-21 }} Access date: 10 January 2009.</ref><ref>\"Death to Hootie!: Trent Reznor Makes a Case for Danger,\" ''Rolling Stone'', 6 March 1997.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0328107/fullcredits |title=Man on Fire (2004) \u2013 Full cast and crew |publisher=Imdb.com |accessdate=27 October 2008 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090401021048/http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0328107/fullcredits |archivedate=1 April 2009 }}</ref> Rob Zombie has directed three films.<ref name=jorgl/> In 2009, Marilyn Manson was in the process of directing ''[[Phantasmagoria: The Visions of Lewis Carroll]]''. The movie has since languished in [[development hell]].<ref>Wax, Alyse. ''Marilyn Manson Freaks Us Out at the Scream Awards'', FEARnet, 20 October 2008 at [http://www.fearnet.com/news/b13425_we_chat_with_marilyn_manson_scream.html FEARnet.com] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220021040/http://www.fearnet.com/news/b13425_we_chat_with_marilyn_manson_scream.html |date=2008-12-20 }}. Last Retrieved 22 October 2008.</ref> Other films that have included prominent contributions from industrial metal artists include ''[[The Crow (1994 film)|The Crow]]'', ''[[Johnny Mnemonic (film)|Johnny Mnemonic]]'', ''[[Spawn (1997 film)|Spawn]]'', ''[[The Matrix]]'', ''[[Blair Witch (film)|Blair Witch]]'' and ''[[A.I. Artificial Intelligence]]''.<ref>Charles Aaron, Entertainment Weekly, 1 April 1994. {{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,301635,00.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218111832/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,301635,00.html |archivedate=2014-12-18 }} Access date: 10 January 2009.</ref>{{sfn|Collins|2005|p=166}}<ref name=okeefe/><ref>Marc Weingarten, Entertainment Weekly, 7 May 1999. {{cite web |url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273304,00.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-18 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141218115456/http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,273304,00.html |archivedate=2014-12-18 }} Access date: 9 January 2009.</ref><ref>David Basham, MTV News, 19 April 2001. {{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1442976/20010419/ministry.jhtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-02-21 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041210130517/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1442976/20010419/ministry.jhtml |archivedate=2004-12-10 }} Access date: 9 January 2009.</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\nIts emphasis on transgressive themes has made a few industrial metal groups vulnerable to attack from [[Conservatism in the United States#Social conservatism and tradition|American social conservatives]]. For example, Sen. [[Bob Dole]], then head of the Republican Party, sharply criticized [[Time Warner]] after a meeting between [[Michael J. Fuchs]] (head of the Warner Music Group), [[William Bennett]], and [[C. Delores Tucker]], at which Tucker and Bennett demanded that Fuchs read lyrics from NIN's \"[[The Downward Spiral|Big Man with a Gun]]\".<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Larry Leibstein with Thomas Rosenstiel|title=The Right Takes a Media Giant to Political Task|url=http://www.newsweek.com/right-takes-media-giant-political-task-183552|work=Newsweek|date=June 12, 1995|page=30}}</ref> A year later, Bennett, Tucker, and [[Joseph Lieberman]] launched a similar campaign against [[MCA Records]] for their distribution of Marilyn Manson's music.<ref name=\"blame\">{{cite web|url=https://groups.google.com/group/alt.music.marilyn-manson/msg/5f8b2fa591032024|title=Google Groups|author=|date=|website=groups.google.com|accessdate=2 May 2018}}</ref> Many of his concerts were cancelled by authorities after this uproar.<ref name=okeefe>Paula O' Keefe, \"The History of Marilyn Manson, 1997 Update Part 2 of 2\", at [http://www.spookhouse.net/update2.html Spookhouse.net] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091120015819/http://www.spookhouse.net/update2.html |date=2009-11-20 }} Access date: 10 January 2009.</ref> In addition, [[Dennis Cooper]] cited Ministry's video for \"[[Just One Fix]]\", which featured footage of [[William S. Burroughs]], as an early example of [[heroin chic]].<ref>{{cite magazine|authorlink=Dennis Cooper|last=Cooper|first=Dennis|title=Junkie See, Junkie Do.|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|date=March 1995|pages=55, 106\u2013107|volume=10|issue=12|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f7SFGOzAxGQC&pg=PA55#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=January 27, 2019|via=Google Books}}</ref>{{rp|106\u2013107}} Some initial reports claimed that [[Columbine High School massacre|Columbine High School shooters]] [[Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold]] were Marilyn Manson fans.<ref>Cullen, Dave. [http://www.salon.com/news/feature/1999/09/23/columbine/index.html Inside the Columbine High investigation] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090126133759/http://www.salon.com/news/feature/1999/09/23/columbine/index.html |date=2009-01-26 }}. ''Salon News'', 23 September 1999.</ref> In fact, they preferred KMFDM and Rammstein.<ref name=\"cullen\">{{cite news | url=http://www.slate.com/id/2099203/sidebar/2099208/ | work=[[Slate magazine|Slate]] | title=The Depressive and the Psychopath | first=Dave | last=Cullen | date=20 April 2004 | accessdate=24 August 2008 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080615143737/http://www.slate.com/id/2099203/sidebar/2099208/ <!--Added by H3llBot--> | archivedate=15 June 2008}}</ref> [[Asa Coon]], another school shooter, was a Manson fan.<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20071011/ap_on_re_us/school_shooting School Shooting]  {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071021073827/http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20071011/ap_on_re_us/school_shooting |date=October 21, 2007 }}</ref>\nManson, a former journalist, published a detailed response to the controversy following the Columbine shootings in an article published in ''[[Rolling Stone]]''. It concluded:<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Marilyn Manson|title=Columbine: Whose Fault Is It?|magazine=Rolling Stone|issue=815|date=June 24, 1999|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/columbine-whose-fault-is-it-19990624|access-date=April 10, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120721192522/http://www.rollingstone.com/culture/news/columbine-whose-fault-is-it-19990624|archivedate=July 21, 2012}}</ref>\n{{quote|I think that the [[National Rifle Association]] is far too powerful to take on, so most people choose ''[[Doom (1993 video game)|Doom]]'', ''[[The Basketball Diaries (film)|The Basketball Diaries]]'' or yours truly. This kind of controversy does not help me sell records or tickets, and I wouldn't want it to. I'm a controversial artist, one who dares to have an opinion and bothers to create music and videos that challenge people's ideas in a world that is watered-down and hollow. In my work I examine the America we live in, and I've always tried to show people that the devil we blame our atrocities on is really just each one of us. [...]}}\nSascha Konietzko reported that KMFDM was \"sick and appalled\" by the shootings, issuing a statement the following day saying:<ref>{{cite AV media | people=Konietzko, Sascha (speaker) | date=September 2008 | title=KMFDM \u2013 Sascha Konietzko om skolemassakrene | url=http://www1.nrk.no/nett-tv/klipp/418313 | format=asf | medium=Streaming audio | publisher=NRK \u2013 Norsk Rikskringkasting | location=Oslo, Norway | accessdate=13 October 2008 | time=1:51, 4:05 | url-status=live | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081221015844/http://www1.nrk.no/nett-tv/klipp/418313 | archivedate=21 December 2008 }}</ref>\n{{quote|First and foremost, KMFDM would like to express their deep and heartfelt sympathy for the parents, families and friends of the murdered and injured children in Littleton. We are sick and appalled, as is the rest of the nation, by what took place in Colorado yesterday.\n\nKMFDM are an art form \u2013 not a political party. From the beginning, our music has been a statement against war, oppression, fascism and violence against others. While some of the former band members are German as reported in the media, none of us condone any Nazi beliefs whatsoever.}}\n\nRammstein stated that they \"have no lyrical content or political beliefs that could have possibly influenced such behavior\".<ref>\"KMFDM And Rammstein Speak Out About Columbine,\" MTV News, 23 April 1999. {{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1427256/04231999/kmfdm.jhtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090409005154/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1427256/04231999/kmfdm.jhtml |archivedate=2009-04-09 }} Access date: 27 February 2009.</ref> Rammstein have also been controversial for their use of Nazi imagery, including footage shot by [[Leni Riefenstahl]] for ''[[Olympia (1938 film)|Olympia]]'' in their video for \"[[Stripped (song)#Rammstein cover|Stripped]]\".<ref name=london>London Records press release, \"Nazis? Hell No!\" [http://www.btinternet.com/~rammstein_online/articles_nazis.html] Access date: 27 February 2009. {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081227181355/http://www.btinternet.com/~rammstein_online/articles_nazis.html |date=December 27, 2008 }}</ref> [[Alec Empire]], a German [[digital hardcore]] musician, declared that \"[Rammstein is] successful for all the wrong reasons. I think they're not a fascist band at all, but I think in Germany there's a lot of misunderstanding and that's why they sell records and I think that's dangerous.\"<ref>\"Atari Teenage Riot's Alec Empire Questions Rammstein's Sincerity.\" MTV News, 9 November 1998. {{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1425050/19981109/story.jhtml |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-03-20 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010904165432/http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1425050/19981109/story.jhtml |archivedate=2001-09-04 }} Access date: 27 February 2009.</ref> In response to the controversy, Rammstein stated that \"We are not Nazis, Neo-Nazis, or any other kind of Nazi. We are against racism, bigotry or any other type of discrimination.\"<ref name=london/> The band went on to create the song \"[[Links 2-3-4]]\", released in 2001, which responded to the Nazi allegations by insinuating that they reside left on the [[political spectrum]].{{sfn|Serba|2001|p=B6}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Rock music}}\n* [[List of industrial metal bands]]\n* [[Heavy metal music]]\n* [[List of industrial music festivals]]\n* [[List of heavy metal festivals]]\n* [[Neue Deutsche H\u00e4rte]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin|3}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Alexander|first=Phil|date=|year=1995|title=Alien Soundtracks!|url=|magazine=Kerrang!|pages=52\u201353|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|ref={{SfnRef|Alexander|1995}}|number=528}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Arnopp|first=Jason|date=|year=1993|title=De-Construction!|url=|magazine=Kerrang!|pages=41|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|ref={{SfnRef|Arnopp A|1993}}|number=462}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Arnopp|first=Jason|date=|year=1993|title=Industrial Metal: A User's Guide|url=|magazine=Kerrang!|pages=44|doi=|pmid=|access-date=|ref={{SfnRef|Arnopp B|1993}}|number=462}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Barcinski|first=Andr\u00e9|year=1992|title=M\u00e1quina Mort\u00edfera|magazine=Bizz|number=79|pages=24\u201329|ref={{SfnRef|Barcinski|1992}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Blush|first=Steven|authorlink1=Steven Blush|year=2001|title=[[American Hardcore: A Tribal History]]|location=Los Angeles, CA|publisher=[[Feral House]]|ref={{SfnRef|Blush|2001}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Chantler|first=Chris|year=2002|title=Splitting Heirs|magazine=Terrorizer|number=96|pages=54\u201355|ref={{SfnRef|Chantler|2002}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Collins|first=Karen|year=2005|title=Dead Channel Surfing: the Commonalities between Cyberpunk Literature and Industrial Music|magazine=Popular Music|volume=24|number=2|pages=165\u2013178|ref={{sfnref|Collins|2005}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Di Perna|first=Alan|year=1995|title=Jackhammer of the Gods|magazine=Guitar World|volume=15|number=6|pages=54\u201359, 61\u201362, 67, 69, 71|ref={{sfnref|Di Perna A|1995}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Di Perna|first=Alan|year=1995|title=White Zombie: Zombies Gave Me Lunch!|magazine=Guitar World|volume=15|number=6|pages=33, 35\u201326, 38, 40, 46, 170, 172|ref={{Sfnref|Di Perna B|1995}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Fergunson|first=Paul|year=1993|title=Terror Against Terror: Lustmord's Dancefloor Coup|magazine=Industrial Nation|number=7|pages=53\u201357|ref={{sfnref|Fergunson|1993}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Gill|first=Chris|year=1996|title=Swine Before Pearls: Wallowing In the Muck with Ministry's Al Jourgensen|magazine=Guitar Player|volume=30|number=3|pages=84\u201389|ref={{sfnref|Gill|1996}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last1=Gill|first=C.|last2=Rotondi|first2=J.|year=1996|title=Heady Metal|magazine=Guitar Player|volume=30|number=3|pages=74\u201382|ref={{sfnref|Gill & Rotondi|1996}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Gitter|first=Mike|title=Ministry: Sole Survivors|magazine=Thrasher|date=January 1990|pages=76\u201377, 100|ref={{sfnref|Gitter|1990}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Kaye|first=Don|year=1992|title=Flesh Eaters|magazine=Kerrang!|number=388|pages=16\u201317|ref={{sfnref|Kaye|1992}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Martin|first=Jim|year=2004|title=Sadness Will Prevail|magazine=Terrorizer!|number=123|pages=24\u201325|ref={{sfnref|Martin|2004}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|author=M\u00f6rat|year=1990|title=Flesh for Fantasy|magazine=Kerrang!|number=320|pages=14\u201315|ref={{sfnref|M\u00f6rat|1990}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Mudrian|first=Albert|year=2004|title=Choosing Death: the Improbable History of Death Metal and Grindcore|location=Los Angeles, CA|publisher=Feral House|ref={{sfnref|Mudrian|2004}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Paytress|first=Mark |year=1995|title=Industrial Music|magazine=Record Collector|number=185|pages=92\u201399|ref={{sfnref|Paytress|1995}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Pettigrew|first=Jason|year=1991|title=Godflesh: the Power of Positive Paradoxes|magazine=Alternative Press|volume=5|number=36|pages=22\u201323|ref={{sfnref|Pettigrew|1991}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Pettigrew|first=Jason|year=1996|title=Watch Yourself and Watch What You Say|magazine=Alternative Press|number=92|pages=44\u201351|ref={{sfnref|Pettigrew|1996}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Reynolds|first=Simon|date=20 August 1988|title=Detonation Angels|magazine=Melody Maker|pages=28\u201330|ref={{sfnref|Reynolds|1988}}}}\n* {{Cite news|last=Serba|first=John|date=22 July 2001|title= Operatic Vocals, Industrial Rhythms Mix For a Sound Distinctly ... German|work=[[The Grand Rapids Press]]|page=B6|ref={{sfnref|Serba|2001}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last1=Stud|first1=B.|last2=Stud|first2=T|date=20 June 1987|title=Heaven Up Here|magazine=Melody Maker|pages=26\u201327|ref={{sfnref|Stud & Stud|1987}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|title=The Ministry of Noise|date=March 1989|magazine=Modern Keyboard|pages=49\u201350|ref={{sfnref|The Ministry of Noise|1989}}}}\n* {{cite book|last=Thompson|first=Dave|year=1994|title=Industrial Revolution|location=Los Angeles, CA|publisher=Cleopatra|ref={{sfnref|Thompson|1994}}}}\n* {{cite book|last1=Vale|first1=V.|authorlink=V. Vale|last2=Juno|first2=A.|year=1983|title=[[RE/Search #6-#7: Industrial Culture Handbook]]|location=San Francisco, CA|publisher=RE/SEARCH PUBLICATIONS|ref={{Sfnref|Vale & Juno|1983}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Wiederhorn|first=Jon|year=1994|title=Industrious Metal|magazine=Pulse|number=64|pages=64|ref={{sfnref|Wiederhorn|1994}}}}\n* {{cite magazine|last=Yates|first=Catherine|year=2001|title=Souls of a New Machine|magazine=Kerrang!|number=871|pages=18\u201320|ref={{sfnref|Yates|2001}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{heavymetal}}\n{{Alternative metal}}\n{{industrial music-footer}}\n{{Goth subculture}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n[[Category:Industrial metal| ]]\n[[Category:Heavy metal genres]]\n[[Category:Electronic music genres]]\n[[Category:Industrial music]]\n[[Category:Fusion music genres]]\n", "name_user": "Kaltenmeyer", "label": "safe", "comment": "moved punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Industrial_metal"}
{"title_page": "C. L. Max Nikias", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = C. L. Max Nikias.jpg\n| alt = C.L. Max Nikias (cropped)\n| order = 11th\n| office = President of the University of Southern California\n| term_start = August 3, 2010\n| term_end = August 7, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Steven Sample]]\n| successor = [[Carol Folt]]\n| birth_name = Chrysostomos Loizos Nikias\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|09|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Komi Kebir]], [[Cyprus]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[National Technical University of Athens]], [[University at Buffalo]]\n| residence = \n| profession = [[Electrical engineering]], Higher education, [[Academic administration]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Niki|1977}}\n| children = 2 daughters\n}}\n\n'''Chrysostomos Loizos \"Max\" Nikias''' ({{lang-el|\u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03cc\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u039b\u03bf\u0390\u03b6\u03bf\u03c2 \u039d\u03b9\u03ba\u03af\u03b1\u03c2}}; born September 30, 1952) is a Cypriot-American academic, and served as the 11th [[University of Southern California]] president, a position he held from August 3, 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uscnews.usc.edu/university/c_l_max_nikias_named_11th_president_of_usc.html|title=C. L. Max Nikias Named 11th President of USC|date=March 11, 2010|publisher=USC News|accessdate=September 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923014604/http://uscnews.usc.edu/university/c_l_max_nikias_named_11th_president_of_usc.html|archive-date=September 23, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> to August 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boardoftrustees.usc.edu/message-from-board-of-trustees-chairman-rick-j-caruso-august-7-2018/|title=Message from Board of Trustees Chairman Rick J. Caruso (August 7, 2018) - Board of Trustees - USC|website=boardoftrustees.usc.edu|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He holds the Malcolm R. Currie Chair in Technology and the Humanities and is president [[emeritus]] of the university.<ref name=\"transition\">{{cite web |url=http://universityofsoutherncalifornia.createsend1.com/t/ViewEmail/j/C9A2A4FDE384E2D72540EF23F30FEDED|title=Nikias transitions to president emeritus|date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He had been at USC since 1991, as a professor, director of national research centers, [[dean (education)|dean]], [[provost (education)|provost]], and president. He also served as chair of the College Football Playoff (CFP) Board of Managers (2015-2018) as chair of the board of the Keck Medical Center at USC (2009-2018), as member of the board of directors of the Alfred Mann Institute for Biomedical Engineering (2001-2018), and as a member of the Board of Trustees of the Chadwick School, an independent school in Palos Verdes Peninsula, Calif. (2001-2010).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/25606/Nikias-Named-New-USC-Provost/|title=Nikias Named New USC Provost|date=March 24, 2005}}</ref> He is currently a tenured professor in electrical engineering with a secondary appointment in classics, and the director of the USC Institute for Technology Enabled Higher Education.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu/biography/cv/executive-summary/|title=C. L. Max Nikias Curriculum Vitate|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, 200 tenured USC professors (out of 4,604 university faculty)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://about.usc.edu/facts/|title=USC Facts and Figures|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> demanded Nikias's resignation for how his administration dealt with nearly 300 incidents of sexual assault and sexual misconduct allegations over 27 years against a longtime student health center gynecologist, [[George Tyndall]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-of-usc-professors-call-for-presidents-ouster-1527024102|title=Hundreds of USC Professors Call for President's Ouster|last=Korn|first=Melissa|date=May 22, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 23, 2018 |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/us/usc-faculty-president-nikias.html |title=200 Professors Call for Ouster of U.S.C. President, Citing Lack of 'Moral Authority'|date=May 22, 2018|work=The New York Times |access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/17/us/USC-gynecologist-young-women.html|title='Just the Grossest Thing': Women Recall Interactions With U.S.C. Doctor|date=May 17, 2018|work=The New York Times |access-date=May 23, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He and the board of trustees agreed to an orderly transition to a new president on May 25, 2018, and he stepped down on August 7, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/05/29/usc-president-will-step-down|title=USC president will step down|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/25/us/usc-nikias-tyndall.html|title=U.S.C. President Agrees to Step Down Over Scandal Involving Gynecologist|date=May 25, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 6, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Following this, Nikias was named president emeritus and a life trustee of the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://alumni.usc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/BoTChair-Communication-080718.pdf |title=BoT Chair Communication 080718 |publisher=University of Southern California |year=2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> The U.S. Department of Education's Office for Civil Right's independent investigation concluded with a report published in February 2020 and did not implicate Nikias in any wrongdoing. The report stated that Nikias had no knowledge of \"the possibility of physical misconduct\" by the student health center gynecologist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=48|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> As soon as Nikias was made aware of the gynecologist situation, the report stated that \"he had identified the matter to be of such significance that he directed the general council to brief the University's Board of Trustees\" in March of 2018; and on May 15, 2018, he informed all USC students and alumni worldwide about the matter in advance of the Los Angeles Times article.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=4-5|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNikias was born on the Mediterranean island of [[Cyprus]].<ref name=\"Nikias profile\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/mar/12/local/la-me-usc-biobox12-2010mar12|title=Profile of USC's next president|date=March 12, 2010 |work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 21, 2010}}</ref> There, he graduated with honors from the Famagusta Gymnasium, a school that emphasizes sciences, history, and Greco-Roman classics. He married his wife, Niki, in 1977,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter03/eng-3.html|title=The Climb of His Life|year=2003|publisher=Trojan Family Magazine|accessdate=April 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002131741/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter03/eng-3.html#|archive-date=October 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the couple have two daughters, Georgiana and Maria.<ref name=\"Nikias profile\"/> He received a degree in electrical and mechanical engineering from the [[National Technical University of Athens]] in 1977, and has an academic interest in Athenian drama and democracy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/bio/|title=C. L. Max Nikias Biography|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=April 23, 2013}}</ref> Nikias earned a master's degree in 1980 and a Ph.D in 1982 in electrical engineering at the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo]].<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Nikias |first= Chrysostomos Loizos|date= 1982|title= A new class of robust spectral estimation algorithms based on minimum covariance recursion error and their application in cardiac data analysis |degree=Ph.D. |publisher= State University of New York at Buffalo |url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=910320|access-date=August 21, 2016}}</ref> His predecessor as USC president, [[Steven Sample]], was likewise an electrical engineer, and served as president of SUNY-Buffalo from 1982 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.usc.edu/presidentemeritus/|title=About USC \u2013 President Emeritus|accessdate=September 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002132554/http://about.usc.edu/presidentemeritus/|archive-date=October 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Associate Dean and Center Director in the USC Viterbi School of Engineering (1991\u20132001)===\nNikias served as founding director of the school's Integrated Media Systems Center (IMSC) from 1996 to 2001. He led the engineering school's effort to secure the center in an intense national competition conducted by the National Science Foundation that included 116 other proposals. Nikias also served as associate dean of the engineering school from 1992 to 2001. While his research work ranged from signal processing and biomedical engineering to digital communications and military radar and sonar, he is best known for his understanding of multimedia's defining place in the future of the internet and the IMSC.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/5020/Engineering-Max-Nikias-succeeds-Len-Silverman-as-dean/|title=Engineering: Max Nikias succeeds Len Silverman as dean|date=May 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Dean of the USC Viterbi School of Engineering (2001\u20132005)===\nFrom 2001 to 2005, Nikias served as dean of the [[USC Viterbi School of Engineering]], solidifying its position as a top-tier engineering school. He directed the expansion of the school's biomedical engineering enterprise and developed its distance-learning program into one of the largest in the country at that time. He oversaw the development of the school's Tutor Hall of Engineering. He also established key partnerships with corporations, among them [[Pratt & Whitney]], [[Airbus]], [[Boeing]], [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]], and [[Northrop Grumman]], and led a fundraising campaign that brought in more than $250 million, capped by a $52 million school-naming gift from [[Andrew Viterbi|Andrew and Erna Viterbi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://viterbi.usc.edu/about/viterbi/viterbi_press_release.htm|title=Cell phone pioneer endows Viterbi School of Engineering |publisher=viterbi.usc.edu|accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> Nikias was instrumental in supporting the Information Sciences Institute in the USC Viterbi School, and in working with faculty across the university to establish two National Science Foundation (NSF) Engineering Research Centers (ERC), as well as the Department of Homeland Security's first Research Center of Excellence at USC.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/25606/Nikias-Named-New-USC-Provost/|title=Nikias Named New USC Provost|date=March 24, 2005}}</ref>\n\n===USC provost (2005\u20132010)===\nFrom June 2005 to August 2010, Nikias served as USC's provost and chief academic officer. He was instrumental in bringing USC trustee [[Steven Spielberg|Steven Spielberg's]] [[USC Shoah Foundation Institute for Visual History and Education|Shoah Foundation Institute]] and its vast video archive of 55,000 testimonies of [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] survivors to USC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/uscnews/stories/11601.html|title=USC College to House Shoah Foundation|date=September 10, 2005|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=April 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126115711/http://www.usc.edu/uscnews/stories/11601.html|archive-date=November 26, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nikias also established the university's Edward R. Roybal Institute on Aging, Stevens Center for Innovation, [http://china.usc.edu U.S.-China Institute],<ref>[http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=204 Nikias announcement] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714163127/http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=204# |date=July 14, 2014 }} of the creation of the USC U.S.-China Institute; [http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=61 Nikias introductory remarks] at inaugural USC U.S.-China Institute conference.</ref> and Levan Institute for Humanities and Ethics. He launched [https://web.archive.org/web/20100620185435/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/ Visions and Voices], USC's campus-wide arts and humanities initiative, as well as a grant program to advance scholarship in the [[humanities]] and [[social science]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/about.php|title=Visions and Voices: The Arts and Humanities Initiative|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=September 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826150957/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/about.php#|archive-date=August 26, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nikias spearheaded the integration of the [[Keck School of Medicine of USC]]'s faculty practice plans, oversaw the transfer of [[Los Angeles County+USC Medical Center|University Hospital]] and [[USC Norris Comprehensive Cancer Center|USC Norris Cancer Hospital]] from [[Tenet Healthcare Corporation]] to the university, and recruited a new leadership team for USC's medical enterprise.\n\n===USC president (2010\u20132018)===\nAs president, Nikias wrote frequently about a range of nationally significant topics, including the value of\u2014and access to\u2014higher education;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://agenda.weforum.org/2015/01/what-will-the-future-of-education-look-like/|title=What will the future of education look like?|date=January 24, 2015|publisher=World Economic Forum|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/why-elite-universities-should-admit-more-community-college-grads/2014/10/23/b4dda968-4986-11e4-a046-120a8a855cca_story.html|title=Why elite universities should admit more community college grads|date=October 23, 2014 |work=Washington Post|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> the future of online education;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/online-education-revolution-hype-reality/|title=Online Education Revolution \u2013 Hype and Reality|date=October 15, 2013|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=June 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618203420/http://www.president.usc.edu/online-education-revolution-hype-reality/|archive-date=June 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> the continued importance of the arts and humanities; the art of leadership through the classics; and the role of elite research universities, particularly as economic drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/all-roads-lead-to-southern-california-2012/|title=All Roads Lead to Southern California|date=March 21, 2012|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=June 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618203423/http://www.president.usc.edu/all-roads-lead-to-southern-california-2012/|archive-date=June 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Nikias announced a $6 billion fundraising campaign, which\u2014at the time of its launch\u2014was the largest in the history of higher education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/28/local/la-me-usc-funds-20110828|title=USC to pursue record-breaking donation total|date=August 28, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In six and a half years, USC's campaign surpassed the $6 billion mark\u201418 months ahead of schedule\u2014bringing to the university, on the average, $900 million per year. The fundraising campaign raised a total of $7 billion in eight years.<ref>{{cite web|title=USC Is Raising Money So Fast, It Just Moved the Goalpost|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/usc-is-raising-money-so-fast-it-just-moved-the-goalpost-1487190600|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> ''The Chronicle of Higher Education'' has called Nikias a \"prodigious fundraiser.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/As-Its-Popular-President/64532/|title=As Its Popular President Retires, USC Eyes An Encore |date=March 7, 2010|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=April 5, 2012|last1=Keller |first1=Josh }}</ref> During Nikias' tenure, USC consistently ranked among the top five universities, along with Stanford and Harvard, in cash charitable donations.\n\nNikias brought the nation's largest literary festival, the [[Los Angeles Times Festival of Books|''Los Angeles Times'' Festival of Books]], to USC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/23/local/la-me-0923-book-festival-20100923|title=Times Festival of Books will move to USC|date=September 23, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In addition, under his leadership, the university embarked on a major capital construction initiative that already includes Wallis Annenberg Hall for [[USC Annenberg School for Communication and Journalism|journalism]], the [[USC Michelson Center for Convergent Bioscience]], Dauterive Hall for social sciences, Fertitta Hall for business, the Kaufman International Dance Center, the McKay Center for athletics, Uytengsu Aquatics Center, the Engemann Student Health Center, a new [[USC School of Cinematic Arts|Cinematic Arts]] building, and the University Club at Stoops, as well as the Soto Building, Currie Residential Hall,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/103561/uscs-health-sciences-campus-getting-major-revamp/|title=Health Sciences Campus getting major revamp|date=July 5, 2016}}</ref> and Norris Consultation Center on the [[Campus of the University of Southern California#Health Sciences Campus|Health Sciences Campus]], and beautification projects for both of USC's campuses. The most prominent project, though, is the USC Village, a 1.3 million square-foot center of student residential colleges, that opened in 2017, entirely reimagining the university's landscape.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-usc-village-20140915-story.html|title=USC unveiling plans for $650-million housing, retail complex|date=September 15, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of his efforts to renew USC's [[USC Trojans|athletic heritage]], ''The New York Times'' selected Nikias as one of a small number of national figures \"who make sports' little corner of the world a better place.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/25/sports/25anderson.html?_r=0|title=Moments to Savor from the Sports World|date=November 24, 2010 |work=The New York Times|accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure as president, USC rose in both ranking and reputation. Nikias introduced a number of strategic initiatives, and was focused on faculty recruitment and the expansion of the medical enterprise; broadening USC's international presence; improving the diversity and quality of the student body; improving the university's infrastructure, including the development of the USC Village; and bringing to closure the university's fundraising campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu/legacy/usc-a-journey-of-transformation/|title=USC: A Journey of Transformation|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Los Angeles Times'', Nikias played \"a central role in university's meteoric rise in academic stature.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-usc-year-disruption-culture-20181223-story.html|title=Rocked by scandal, USC must heal its divisions and repair a broken culture|date=December 23, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref> In 2016, ''The Wall Street Journal''/ Times Higher Education's rankings placed USC at No. 17 among 1,061 colleges and universities. Only three universities west of Chicago ranked in the top 20: USC, Stanford, and Caltech.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/graphics/college-rankings-2016/|title=2016 U.S. College Rankings|date=September 27, 2016|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nNikias is recognized internationally for his research on digital signal processing, digital media systems, and [[biomedicine]]. The U.S. Department of Defense has adopted a number of his innovations and patents in sonar, radar, and communication systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ee.usc.edu/faculty_staff/faculty_directory/nikias.htm|title=USC Ming Hsieh Department of Electrical Engineering: Chrysostomos L. Nikias|publisher=ee.usc.edu|accessdate=September 20, 2010}}</ref> He has authored more than 275 journal articles and conference papers, three textbooks, and eight patents, and has mentored more than 30 Ph.D. and postdoctoral scholars. Three of his publications received best papers awards.\n\n== Transition ==\nIn May 2018, Nikias and the USC board of trustees agreed to an orderly transition to a new president, following a sex abuse scandal regarding USC's student health center's gynecologist and questions{{From whom?|date=August 2018}} about how the university handled it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/05/29/usc-president-will-step-down |title=USC president will step down|publisher=|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOver 200 tenured USC professors (out of 4,604 university faculty) called for the resignation of Nikias, saying that he had \"lost the moral authority to lead.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-of-usc-professors-call-for-presidents-ouster-1527024102|title=Hundreds of USC Professors Call for President's Ouster|last=Korn|first=Melissa|date=May 22, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 22, 2018 |language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-usc-faculty-petition-nikias-20180522-story.html|title=200 USC professors demand Nikias step down; trustees express 'full confidence' in president |last=Hamilton |first=Harriet Ryan, Sarah Parvini, Matt|website=latimes.com|access-date=May 22, 2018|date=May 22, 2018 }}</ref> There were concerns over how the university dealt with sexual misconduct allegations against a longtime student health center gynecologist George Tyndall.<ref name=\"LAT 2018-12-12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-usc-business-school-dean-trustees-20181212-story.html|title=USC trustees back president's ouster of business school dean over handling of harassment cases|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first1=Harriet |last1=Ryan|first2=Matt|last2=Hamilton|date=December 13, 2018|access-date=December 16, 2018}}</ref> The allegations are that for decades over three different university administrations, Tyndall conducted improper pelvic exams on female students, especially students from [[China]], many of whom were seeing a gynecologist for the first time, and made sexually and racially inappropriate comments.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/17/us/USC-gynecologist-young-women.html|title='Just the Grossest Thing': Women Recall Interactions With U.S.C. Doctor|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/3011851/secret-files-dr-george-tyndall-gynaecologist-usc|title=Secret files on doctor who 'preyed on young Asian students'|date=2019-05-26|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> \n\nIn a letter to USC's Board of Trustees, a group of faculty members wrote that they had come together to \"express our outrage and disappointment over the mounting evidence of President Nikias' failure to protect our students, our staff, and our colleagues from repeated and pervasive sexual harassment and misconduct.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ktla.com/2018/05/22/faculty-members-call-for-usc-president-to-step-down-in-wake-of-gynecologist-scandal/ |title=Faculty Members Call for USC President to Step Down in Wake of Gynecologist Scandal|date=May 22, 2018|work=KTLA|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> According to USC Trustees, however, the internal investigation of the Tyndall matter did not reveal \"moral failing in university leadership... it occurred because non-academic offices such as human resources did not advance with the rest of the university.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-usc-year-disruption-culture-20181223-story.html|title=Rocked by scandal, USC must heal its divisions and repair a broken culture|date=December 23, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref> In a letter to the USC community, Nikias expressed sympathy and compassion for the students and acknowledged the university community's distress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studenthealthresources.usc.edu/message-from-president-nikias-to-the-usc-community-may-18-2018/|title=Message from President Nikias to the USC Community|date=May 18, 2018}}</ref> Before agreeing to step down as president, he presented an in-depth plan for changing the campus culture, revisiting the university's core values, and restructuring the university's operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://actionplan.usc.edu/|title=USC Action Plan|date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter Nikias stepped down in August 2018, Rick Caruso, chair of the USC board of trustees, said: \"As he has always done, Max is taking this action in what he believes to be in the best interest of the university following controversies that have arisen from the unfortunate and unacceptable acts of others. From our investigations, which are not yet completed, we have found absolutely no wrong doing on Max's part.\"<ref name=\"transition\"/>\n\nIn February 2020, following its independent investigation, the U.S. Department of Education's Office for Civil Rights published its report. It did not implicate Nikias in any wrongdoing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The report stated that Nikias had no knowledge of \"the possibility of physical misconduct\" by the student health center gynecologist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=48|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref> As soon as Nikias was made aware of the gynecologist situation, the report stated that he had identified the matter \"to be of such significance that he directed the general counsel to brief the university's Board of Trustees\" in March of 2018;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=5|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref> and on May 15, 2018, he informed all USC students and alumni worldwide about the matter in advance of the ''Los Angeles Times'' article.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=4-5|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNikias subsequently became President Emeritus and a Life Trustee of the university, as well as director of the USC Institute for Technology Enabled Higher Education.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu/biography/|title=C. L. Max Nikias biography|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nNikias is a member of the [[National Academy of Engineering]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nae.edu/MembersSection/Directory20412/31047.aspx|title=Dr. Chrysostomos L. Nikias|website=NAE Website|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amacad.org/content/news/pressReleases.aspx?pr=206|title=American Academy of Arts and Sciences Inducts 233rd Class of Members|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences |accessdate=August 19, 2015}}</ref> a charter fellow of the [[National Academy of Inventors]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academyofinventors.org/search-fellows.asp?Cursor=2&QueryItem=%25&GO=N&qSort=%25 |title=Search Fellows - National Academy of Inventors|website=www.academyofinventors.org|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> an associate member of the [[Academy of Athens (modern)|Academy of Athens]], a life fellow of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]], and a fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows|title=Archived copy|accessdate=July 20, 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727124856/http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows |archivedate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> He was named a Fellow of the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) in 1991 when he was 38. Fewer than 2 percent of IEEE's 350,000 members have been named Fellow, and only 5 percent of those achieved that honor by age 38.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/5020/Engineering-Max-Nikias-succeeds-Len-Silverman-as-dean/|title=Engineering: Max Nikias succeeds Len Silverman as dean|date=May 30, 2001}}</ref>\n \nAmong numerous other honors, he has received the IEEE Simon Ramo Medal,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ieee.org/about/awards/bios/ramo_recipients.html|title=IEEE Simon Ramo Medal Recipients|website=www.ieee.org |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> an Academic Leadership Award from Carnegie Corporation of New York,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-ln-usc-award-20150924-story.html|title=USC President C. L. Max Nikias gets national award with $500,000 for campus|work=Los Angeles Times|date=September 24, 2015}}</ref> the Ellis Island Medal of Honor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neco.org/medal-of-honor/2016-medalists|title=2016 Ellis Island Medal of Honor Recipients|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608220224/http://www.neco.org/medal-of-honor/2016-medalists|archivedate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> the Woodrow Wilson Center's Award for Public Service,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.usc.edu/82758/usc-president-nikias-receives-woodrow-wilson-award-for-public-service/|title=USC President Nikias receives Woodrow Wilson Award for Public Service - USC News|website=news.usc.edu|accessdate=June 2, 2018|date=June 14, 2015}}</ref> UNICEF's Spirit of Compassion Award, as well as the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo's]] Distinguished Alumni Award and Clifford C. Furnas Memorial Award.<ref>{{cite web  |url=http://www.buffalo.edu/UBT/UBT-archives/volume26number3/alumni_news/achievementawards.html |title=UB Today: Alumni News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928060405/http://www.buffalo.edu/UBT/UBT-archives/volume26number3/alumni_news/achievementawards.html |archive-date=September 28, 2017 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He also received honorary doctorates from [[Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://huc.edu/news/article/2011/cl-max-nikias-phd-president-university-of-southern-california-brreceived-honorary-doctor-of-humane-letters-from-brhebrew-union-college-jewish-institute-of-religion|title=C.L. Max Nikias, Ph.D., President, University of Southern California, :Received Honorary Doctor of Humane Letters from :Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> his alma mater, the [[National Technical University of Athens]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/82238/nikiases-wrap-up-europe-trip-with-warm-reception-in-athens/|title=Nikiases wrap up Europe trip with warm reception in Athens - USC News|website=news.usc.edu|accessdate=June 2, 2018|date=May 30, 2015}}</ref> the [[University of Cyprus]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kios.ucy.ac.cy/index.php/13-about-us/advisory-board/25-chrysostomos-l-max-nikias.html|title=Chrysostomos L. Max Nikias |publisher=KIOS CoE|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> University of Crete; University of Piraeus; and University of Strathclyde.<ref>{{cite web|title=USC President Nikias receives honorary degree from Scottish university|url=http://news.usc.edu/124374/usc-president-nikias-receives-honorary-degree-from-scottish-university/|website=USC News|date=June 27, 2017}}</ref> Nikias was awarded the Aristeia medal, the Republic of Cyprus' highest honor in the letters, arts, and sciences. In addition, he received the USC Black Alumni Association's Thomas Kilgore Service Award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://viterbi.usc.edu/admission/professionalprograms/usc-forum-india/panelists/c-l-max-nikias.htm |title=Viterbi School of Engineering - C. L. Max Nikias |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031311/https://viterbi.usc.edu/admission/professionalprograms/usc-forum-india/panelists/c-l-max-nikias.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> the Los Angeles Police Museum's Jack Webb Award,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mynewsla.com/education/2014/09/23/usc-president-honored-jack-webb-award/|title=USC President Honored With Jack Webb Award - MyNewsLA.com|date=September 23, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> and earned a commendation for cutting-edge research from the [[Governor of California|governor]] of [[California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccst.us/ccstinfo/board/bios/nikias.php |title=CCST Board Member C. L. Max Nikias|website=www.ccst.us |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> He has also received an Outstanding Teacher Award from the National Technological University, a distance learning university.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/5020/Engineering-Max-Nikias-succeeds-Len-Silverman-as-dean/|title=Engineering: Max Nikias succeeds Len Silverman as dean|date=May 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nNikias lived on the [[Palos Verdes]] Peninsula, an area southwest of Los Angeles, with his wife and two daughters. Following his inauguration as president of USC, he and his family moved to [[San Marino, California|San Marino]], located closer to both USC campuses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/14/local/la-me-adv-nikias-20101014|title=Many see a clean slate in Friday's inauguration of USC president|date=October 14, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref> He and his wife Niki currently live in Manhattan Beach, California.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whitepages.com/address/3009-N-Poinsettia-Ave/Manhattan-Beach-CA/2zz26TJqSGkmJ52Mxp8910|title=Whitepages|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*Nikias, C. L and Shao, M. ''Signal processing with alpha-stable distributions and applications.'' New York: Wiley, c1995. xiii, 168 p. : ill. ; 25&nbsp;cm. {{ISBN|0-471-10647-X}}\n*Nikias, C. L. and Petropulu, A. P. ''Higher-order spectra analysis: a nonlinear signal processing framework.'' Englewood Cliffs, N.J. : PTR Prentice Hall, c1993. xxii, 537 p. : ill. ; 25&nbsp;cm. {{ISBN|0-13-678210-8}}\n*J. G. Proakis, C. Rader, F. Ling, and C. L. Nikias. ''Advanced Signal Processing.'' Macmillan Publishing Company, 1992. {{ISBN|0023968419}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu USC President Emeritus biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Steven B. Sample]]\n| title=11th [[President of the University of Southern California]]\n| years=August 3, 2010 \u2013 August 7, 2018\n| after=[[Wanda Austin]] (interim)\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USC presidents}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nikias, C. L. Max}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the University of Southern California]]\n[[Category:American electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:University of Connecticut faculty]]\n[[Category:Northeastern University faculty]]\n[[Category:National Technical University of Athens alumni]]\n[[Category:University at Buffalo alumni]]\n[[Category:Fellow Members of the IEEE]]\n[[Category:People from Famagusta District]]\n[[Category:Cypriot emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Palos Verdes, California]]\n[[Category:Engineers from California]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| image = C. L. Max Nikias.jpg\n| alt = C.L. Max Nikias (cropped)\n| order = 11th\n| office = President of the University of Southern California\n| term_start = August 3, 2010\n| term_end = August 7, 2018\n| predecessor = [[Steven Sample]]\n| successor = [[Carol Folt]]\n| birth_name = Chrysostomos Loizos Nikias\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|09|30}}\n| birth_place = [[Komi Kebir]], [[Cyprus]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = [[National Technical University of Athens]], [[University at Buffalo]]\n| residence = \n| profession = [[Electrical engineering]], Higher education, [[Academic administration]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|Niki|1977}}\n| children = 2 daughters\n}}\n\n'''Chrysostomos Loizos \"Max\" Nikias''' ({{lang-el|\u03a7\u03c1\u03c5\u03c3\u03cc\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bc\u03bf\u03c2 \u039b\u03bf\u0390\u03b6\u03bf\u03c2 \u039d\u03b9\u03ba\u03af\u03b1\u03c2}}; born September 30, 1952) is a Cypriot-American academic, and served as the 11th [[University of Southern California]] president, a position he held from August 3, 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uscnews.usc.edu/university/c_l_max_nikias_named_11th_president_of_usc.html|title=C. L. Max Nikias Named 11th President of USC|date=March 11, 2010|publisher=USC News|accessdate=September 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100923014604/http://uscnews.usc.edu/university/c_l_max_nikias_named_11th_president_of_usc.html|archive-date=September 23, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> to August 7, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://boardoftrustees.usc.edu/message-from-board-of-trustees-chairman-rick-j-caruso-august-7-2018/|title=Message from Board of Trustees Chairman Rick J. Caruso (August 7, 2018) - Board of Trustees - USC|website=boardoftrustees.usc.edu|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He holds the Malcolm R. Currie Chair in Technology and the Humanities and is president [[emeritus]] of the university.<ref name=\"transition\">{{cite web |url=http://universityofsoutherncalifornia.createsend1.com/t/ViewEmail/j/C9A2A4FDE384E2D72540EF23F30FEDED|title=Nikias transitions to president emeritus|date=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He had been at USC since 1991, as a professor, director of national research centers, [[dean (education)|dean]], [[provost (education)|provost]], and president. He also served as chair of the College Football Playoff (CFP) Board of Managers (2015-2018) as chair of the board of the Keck Medical Center at USC (2009-2018), as member of the board of directors of the Alfred Mann Institute for Biomedical Engineering (2001-2018), and as a member of the Board of Trustees of the Chadwick School, an independent school in Palos Verdes Peninsula, Calif. (2001-2010).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/25606/Nikias-Named-New-USC-Provost/|title=Nikias Named New USC Provost|date=March 24, 2005}}</ref> He is currently a tenured professor in electrical engineering with a secondary appointment in classics, and the director of the USC Institute for Technology Enabled Higher Education.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu/biography/cv/executive-summary/|title=C. L. Max Nikias Curriculum Vitate|access-date=April 8, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, 200 tenured USC professors (out of 4,604 university faculty)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://about.usc.edu/facts/|title=USC Facts and Figures|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref> demanded Nikias's resignation for how his administration dealt with nearly 300 incidents of sexual assault and sexual misconduct allegations over 27 years against a longtime student health center gynecologist, [[George Tyndall]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-of-usc-professors-call-for-presidents-ouster-1527024102|title=Hundreds of USC Professors Call for President's Ouster|last=Korn|first=Melissa|date=May 22, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 23, 2018 |language=en-US |issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/22/us/usc-faculty-president-nikias.html |title=200 Professors Call for Ouster of U.S.C. President, Citing Lack of 'Moral Authority'|date=May 22, 2018|work=The New York Times |access-date=May 23, 2018|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/17/us/USC-gynecologist-young-women.html|title='Just the Grossest Thing': Women Recall Interactions With U.S.C. Doctor|date=May 17, 2018|work=The New York Times |access-date=May 23, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> He and the board of trustees agreed to an orderly transition to a new president on May 25, 2018, and he stepped down on August 7, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/05/29/usc-president-will-step-down|title=USC president will step down|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/25/us/usc-nikias-tyndall.html|title=U.S.C. President Agrees to Step Down Over Scandal Involving Gynecologist|date=May 25, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 6, 2018|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Following this, Nikias was named president emeritus and a life trustee of the university.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://alumni.usc.edu/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/BoTChair-Communication-080718.pdf |title=BoT Chair Communication 080718 |publisher=University of Southern California |year=2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> The U.S. Department of Education's Office for Civil Right's independent investigation concluded with a report published in February 2020 and did not implicate Nikias in any wrongdoing. The report stated that Nikias had no knowledge of \"the possibility of physical misconduct\" by the student health center gynecologist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=48|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> As soon as Nikias was made aware of the gynecologist situation, the report stated that \"he had identified the matter to be of such significance that he directed the general council to brief the University's Board of Trustees\" in March of 2018; and on May 15, 2018, he informed all USC students and alumni worldwide about the matter in advance of the Los Angeles Times article.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=4-5|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nNikias was born on the Mediterranean island of [[Cyprus]].<ref name=\"Nikias profile\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/mar/12/local/la-me-usc-biobox12-2010mar12|title=Profile of USC's next president|date=March 12, 2010 |work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=July 21, 2010}}</ref> There, he graduated with honors from the Famagusta Gymnasium, a school that emphasizes sciences, history, and Greco-Roman classics. He married his wife, Niki, in 1977,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter03/eng-3.html|title=The Climb of His Life|year=2003|publisher=Trojan Family Magazine|accessdate=April 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002131741/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/trojan_family/winter03/eng-3.html#|archive-date=October 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> and the couple have two daughters, Georgiana and Maria.<ref name=\"Nikias profile\"/> He received a degree in electrical and mechanical engineering from the [[National Technical University of Athens]] in 1977, and has an academic interest in Athenian drama and democracy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/bio/|title=C. L. Max Nikias Biography|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=April 23, 2013}}</ref> Nikias earned a master's degree in 1980 and a Ph.D in 1982 in electrical engineering at the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo]].<ref>{{cite thesis |last=Nikias |first= Chrysostomos Loizos|date= 1982|title= A new class of robust spectral estimation algorithms based on minimum covariance recursion error and their application in cardiac data analysis |degree=Ph.D. |publisher= State University of New York at Buffalo |url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=910320|access-date=August 21, 2016}}</ref> His predecessor as USC president, [[Steven Sample]], was likewise an electrical engineer, and served as president of SUNY-Buffalo from 1982 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://about.usc.edu/presidentemeritus/|title=About USC \u2013 President Emeritus|accessdate=September 27, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002132554/http://about.usc.edu/presidentemeritus/|archive-date=October 2, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Associate Dean and Center Director in the USC Viterbi School of Engineering (1991\u20132001)===\nNikias served as founding director of the school's Integrated Media Systems Center (IMSC) from 1996 to 2001. He led the engineering school's effort to secure the center in an intense national competition conducted by the National Science Foundation that included 116 other proposals. Nikias also served as associate dean of the engineering school from 1992 to 2001. While his research work ranged from signal processing and biomedical engineering to digital communications and military radar and sonar, he is best known for his understanding of multimedia's defining place in the future of the internet and the IMSC.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/5020/Engineering-Max-Nikias-succeeds-Len-Silverman-as-dean/|title=Engineering: Max Nikias succeeds Len Silverman as dean|date=May 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\n===Dean of the USC Viterbi School of Engineering (2001\u20132005)===\nFrom 2001 to 2005, Nikias served as dean of the [[USC Viterbi School of Engineering]], solidifying its position as a top-tier engineering school. He directed the expansion of the school's biomedical engineering enterprise and developed its distance-learning program into one of the largest in the country at that time. He oversaw the development of the school's Tutor Hall of Engineering. He also established key partnerships with corporations, among them [[Pratt & Whitney]], [[Airbus]], [[Boeing]], [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]], and [[Northrop Grumman]], and led a fundraising campaign that brought in more than $250 million, capped by a $52 million school-naming gift from [[Andrew Viterbi|Andrew and Erna Viterbi]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://viterbi.usc.edu/about/viterbi/viterbi_press_release.htm|title=Cell phone pioneer endows Viterbi School of Engineering |publisher=viterbi.usc.edu|accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref> Nikias was instrumental in supporting the Information Sciences Institute in the USC Viterbi School, and in working with faculty across the university to establish two National Science Foundation (NSF) Engineering Research Centers (ERC), as well as the Department of Homeland Security's first Research Center of Excellence at USC.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/25606/Nikias-Named-New-USC-Provost/|title=Nikias Named New USC Provost|date=March 24, 2005}}</ref>\n\n===USC provost (2005\u20132010)===\nFrom June 2005 to August 2010, Nikias served as USC's provost and chief academic officer. He was instrumental in bringing USC trustee [[Steven Spielberg|Steven Spielberg's]] [[USC Shoah Foundation Institute for Visual History and Education|Shoah Foundation Institute]] and its vast video archive of 55,000 testimonies of [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] survivors to USC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/uscnews/stories/11601.html|title=USC College to House Shoah Foundation|date=September 10, 2005|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=April 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111126115711/http://www.usc.edu/uscnews/stories/11601.html|archive-date=November 26, 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nikias also established the university's Edward R. Roybal Institute on Aging, Stevens Center for Innovation, [http://china.usc.edu U.S.-China Institute],<ref>[http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=204 Nikias announcement] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714163127/http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=204# |date=July 14, 2014 }} of the creation of the USC U.S.-China Institute; [http://china.usc.edu/ShowArticle.aspx?articleID=61 Nikias introductory remarks] at inaugural USC U.S.-China Institute conference.</ref> and Levan Institute for Humanities and Ethics. He launched [https://web.archive.org/web/20100620185435/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/ Visions and Voices], USC's campus-wide arts and humanities initiative, as well as a grant program to advance scholarship in the [[humanities]] and [[social science]]s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/about.php|title=Visions and Voices: The Arts and Humanities Initiative|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=September 20, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826150957/http://www.usc.edu/dept/pubrel/visionsandvoices/about.php#|archive-date=August 26, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> Nikias spearheaded the integration of the [[Keck School of Medicine of USC]]'s faculty practice plans, oversaw the transfer of [[Los Angeles County+USC Medical Center|University Hospital]] and [[USC Norris Comprehensive Cancer Center|USC Norris Cancer Hospital]] from [[Tenet Healthcare Corporation]] to the university, and recruited a new leadership team for USC's medical enterprise.\n\n===USC president (2010\u20132018)===\nAs president, Nikias wrote frequently about a range of nationally significant topics, including the value of\u2014and access to\u2014higher education;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://agenda.weforum.org/2015/01/what-will-the-future-of-education-look-like/|title=What will the future of education look like?|date=January 24, 2015|publisher=World Economic Forum|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/why-elite-universities-should-admit-more-community-college-grads/2014/10/23/b4dda968-4986-11e4-a046-120a8a855cca_story.html|title=Why elite universities should admit more community college grads|date=October 23, 2014 |work=Washington Post|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> the future of online education;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/online-education-revolution-hype-reality/|title=Online Education Revolution \u2013 Hype and Reality|date=October 15, 2013|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=June 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618203420/http://www.president.usc.edu/online-education-revolution-hype-reality/|archive-date=June 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> the continued importance of the arts and humanities; the art of leadership through the classics; and the role of elite research universities, particularly as economic drivers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.president.usc.edu/all-roads-lead-to-southern-california-2012/|title=All Roads Lead to Southern California|date=March 21, 2012|publisher=usc.edu|accessdate=June 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150618203423/http://www.president.usc.edu/all-roads-lead-to-southern-california-2012/|archive-date=June 18, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Nikias announced a $6 billion fundraising campaign, which\u2014at the time of its launch\u2014was the largest in the history of higher education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/aug/28/local/la-me-usc-funds-20110828|title=USC to pursue record-breaking donation total|date=August 28, 2011|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In six and a half years, USC's campaign surpassed the $6 billion mark\u201418 months ahead of schedule\u2014bringing to the university, on the average, $900 million per year. The fundraising campaign raised a total of $7 billion in eight years.<ref>{{cite web|title=USC Is Raising Money So Fast, It Just Moved the Goalpost|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/usc-is-raising-money-so-fast-it-just-moved-the-goalpost-1487190600|accessdate=May 2, 2017}}</ref> ''The Chronicle of Higher Education'' has called Nikias a \"prodigious fundraiser.\"<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://chronicle.com/article/As-Its-Popular-President/64532/|title=As Its Popular President Retires, USC Eyes An Encore |date=March 7, 2010|journal=The Chronicle of Higher Education|accessdate=April 5, 2012|last1=Keller |first1=Josh }}</ref> During Nikias' tenure, USC consistently ranked among the top five universities, along with Stanford and Harvard, in cash charitable donations.\n\nNikias brought the nation's largest literary festival, the [[Los Angeles Times Festival of Books|''Los Angeles Times'' Festival of Books]], to USC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/sep/23/local/la-me-0923-book-festival-20100923|title=Times Festival of Books will move to USC|date=September 23, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref> In addition, under his leadership, the university embarked on a major capital construction initiative that already includes Wallis Annenberg Hall for [[USC Annenberg School for Communication and Journalism|journalism]], the [[USC Michelson Center for Convergent Bioscience]], Dauterive Hall for social sciences, Fertitta Hall for business, the Kaufman International Dance Center, the McKay Center for athletics, Uytengsu Aquatics Center, the Engemann Student Health Center, a new [[USC School of Cinematic Arts|Cinematic Arts]] building, and the University Club at Stoops, as well as the Soto Building, Currie Residential Hall,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/103561/uscs-health-sciences-campus-getting-major-revamp/|title=Health Sciences Campus getting major revamp|date=July 5, 2016}}</ref> and Norris Consultation Center on the [[Campus of the University of Southern California#Health Sciences Campus|Health Sciences Campus]], and beautification projects for both of USC's campuses. The most prominent project, though, is the USC Village, a 1.3 million square-foot center of student residential colleges, that opened in 2017, entirely reimagining the university's landscape.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-usc-village-20140915-story.html|title=USC unveiling plans for $650-million housing, retail complex|date=September 15, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn recognition of his efforts to renew USC's [[USC Trojans|athletic heritage]], ''The New York Times'' selected Nikias as one of a small number of national figures \"who make sports' little corner of the world a better place.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/25/sports/25anderson.html?_r=0|title=Moments to Savor from the Sports World|date=November 24, 2010 |work=The New York Times|accessdate=April 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure as president, USC rose in both ranking and reputation. Nikias introduced a number of strategic initiatives, and was focused on faculty recruitment and the expansion of the medical enterprise; broadening USC's international presence; improving the diversity and quality of the student body; improving the university's infrastructure, including the development of the USC Village; and bringing to closure the university's fundraising campaign.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu/legacy/usc-a-journey-of-transformation/|title=USC: A Journey of Transformation|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''Los Angeles Times'', Nikias played \"a central role in university's meteoric rise in academic stature.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-usc-year-disruption-culture-20181223-story.html|title=Rocked by scandal, USC must heal its divisions and repair a broken culture|date=December 23, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref> In 2016, ''The Wall Street Journal''/ Times Higher Education's rankings placed USC at No. 17 among 1,061 colleges and universities. Only three universities west of Chicago ranked in the top 20: USC, Stanford, and Caltech.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/graphics/college-rankings-2016/|title=2016 U.S. College Rankings|date=September 27, 2016|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nNikias is recognized internationally for his research on digital signal processing, digital media systems, and [[biomedicine]]. The U.S. Department of Defense has adopted a number of his innovations and patents in sonar, radar, and communication systems.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ee.usc.edu/faculty_staff/faculty_directory/nikias.htm|title=USC Ming Hsieh Department of Electrical Engineering: Chrysostomos L. Nikias|publisher=ee.usc.edu|accessdate=September 20, 2010}}</ref> He has authored more than 275 journal articles and conference papers, three textbooks, and eight patents, and has mentored more than 30 Ph.D. and postdoctoral scholars. Three of his publications received best papers awards.\n\n== Transition ==\nIn May 2018, Nikias and the USC board of trustees agreed to an orderly transition to a new president, following a sex abuse scandal regarding USC's student health center's gynecologist and questions{{From whom?|date=August 2018}} about how the university handled it.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.insidehighered.com/news/2018/05/29/usc-president-will-step-down |title=USC president will step down|publisher=|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOver 200 tenured USC professors (out of 4,604 university faculty) called for the resignation of Nikias, saying that he had \"lost the moral authority to lead.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/hundreds-of-usc-professors-call-for-presidents-ouster-1527024102|title=Hundreds of USC Professors Call for President's Ouster|last=Korn|first=Melissa|date=May 22, 2018|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=May 22, 2018 |language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-usc-faculty-petition-nikias-20180522-story.html|title=200 USC professors demand Nikias step down; trustees express 'full confidence' in president |last=Hamilton |first=Harriet Ryan, Sarah Parvini, Matt|website=latimes.com|access-date=May 22, 2018|date=May 22, 2018 }}</ref> There were concerns over how the university dealt with sexual misconduct allegations against a longtime student health center gynecologist George Tyndall.<ref name=\"LAT 2018-12-12\">{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-usc-business-school-dean-trustees-20181212-story.html|title=USC trustees back president's ouster of business school dean over handling of harassment cases|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first1=Harriet |last1=Ryan|first2=Matt|last2=Hamilton|date=December 13, 2018|access-date=December 16, 2018}}</ref> The allegations are that for decades over three different university administrations, Tyndall conducted improper pelvic exams on female students, especially students from [[China]], many of whom were seeing a gynecologist for the first time, and made sexually and racially inappropriate comments.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/17/us/USC-gynecologist-young-women.html|title='Just the Grossest Thing': Women Recall Interactions With U.S.C. Doctor|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.scmp.com/news/world/united-states-canada/article/3011851/secret-files-dr-george-tyndall-gynaecologist-usc|title=Secret files on doctor who 'preyed on young Asian students'|date=2019-05-26|website=South China Morning Post|language=en|access-date=2019-10-06}}</ref> \n\nIn a letter to USC's Board of Trustees, a group of faculty members wrote that they had come together to \"express our outrage and disappointment over the mounting evidence of President Nikias' failure to protect our students, our staff, and our colleagues from repeated and pervasive sexual harassment and misconduct.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ktla.com/2018/05/22/faculty-members-call-for-usc-president-to-step-down-in-wake-of-gynecologist-scandal/ |title=Faculty Members Call for USC President to Step Down in Wake of Gynecologist Scandal|date=May 22, 2018|work=KTLA|access-date=May 22, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> According to USC Trustees, however, the internal investigation of the Tyndall matter did not reveal \"moral failing in university leadership... it occurred because non-academic offices such as human resources did not advance with the rest of the university.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-usc-year-disruption-culture-20181223-story.html|title=Rocked by scandal, USC must heal its divisions and repair a broken culture|date=December 23, 2018|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=April 21,2020}}</ref> In a letter to the USC community, Nikias expressed sympathy and compassion for the students and acknowledged the university community's distress.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://studenthealthresources.usc.edu/message-from-president-nikias-to-the-usc-community-may-18-2018/|title=Message from President Nikias to the USC Community|date=May 18, 2018}}</ref> Before agreeing to step down as president, he presented an in-depth plan for changing the campus culture, revisiting the university's core values, and restructuring the university's operations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://actionplan.usc.edu/|title=USC Action Plan|date=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter Nikias stepped down in August 2018, Rick Caruso, chair of the USC board of trustees, said: \"As he has always done, Max is taking this action in what he believes to be in the best interest of the university following controversies that have arisen from the unfortunate and unacceptable acts of others. From our investigations, which are not yet completed, we have found absolutely no wrong doing on Max's part.\"<ref name=\"transition\"/>\n\nIn February 2020, following its independent investigation, the U.S. Department of Education's Office for Civil Rights published its report. It did not implicate Nikias in any wrongdoing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> The report stated that Nikias had no knowledge of \"the possibility of physical misconduct\" by the student health center gynecologist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=48|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref> As soon as Nikias was made aware of the gynecologist situation, the report stated that he had identified the matter \"to be of such significance that he directed the general counsel to brief the university's Board of Trustees\" in March of 2018;<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=5|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref> and on May 15, 2018, he informed all USC students and alumni worldwide about the matter in advance of the ''Los Angeles Times'' article.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www2.ed.gov/about/offices/list/ocr/docs/investigations/more/09186908-a.pdf|title=U.S. Department of Education OCR resolution letter|date=February 27, 2020|page=4-5|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nNikias subsequently became President Emeritus and a Life Trustee of the university, as well as director of the USC Institute for Technology Enabled Higher Education.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu/biography/|title=C. L. Max Nikias biography|access-date=April 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honors==\nNikias is a member of the [[National Academy of Engineering]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nae.edu/MembersSection/Directory20412/31047.aspx|title=Dr. Chrysostomos L. Nikias|website=NAE Website|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> a fellow of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.amacad.org/content/news/pressReleases.aspx?pr=206|title=American Academy of Arts and Sciences Inducts 233rd Class of Members|publisher=American Academy of Arts and Sciences |accessdate=August 19, 2015}}</ref> a charter fellow of the [[National Academy of Inventors]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.academyofinventors.org/search-fellows.asp?Cursor=2&QueryItem=%25&GO=N&qSort=%25 |title=Search Fellows - National Academy of Inventors|website=www.academyofinventors.org|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> an associate member of the [[Academy of Athens (modern)|Academy of Athens]], a life fellow of the [[Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers]], and a fellow of the [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows|title=Archived copy|accessdate=July 20, 2014|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140727124856/http://membercentral.aaas.org/fellows |archivedate=July 27, 2014}}</ref> He was named a Fellow of the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) in 1991 when he was 38. Fewer than 2 percent of IEEE's 350,000 members have been named Fellow, and only 5 percent of those achieved that honor by age 38.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/5020/Engineering-Max-Nikias-succeeds-Len-Silverman-as-dean/|title=Engineering: Max Nikias succeeds Len Silverman as dean|date=May 30, 2001}}</ref>\n \nAmong numerous other honors, he has received the IEEE Simon Ramo Medal,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ieee.org/about/awards/bios/ramo_recipients.html|title=IEEE Simon Ramo Medal Recipients|website=www.ieee.org |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> an Academic Leadership Award from Carnegie Corporation of New York,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/local/education/la-me-ln-usc-award-20150924-story.html|title=USC President C. L. Max Nikias gets national award with $500,000 for campus|work=Los Angeles Times|date=September 24, 2015}}</ref> the Ellis Island Medal of Honor,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neco.org/medal-of-honor/2016-medalists|title=2016 Ellis Island Medal of Honor Recipients|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608220224/http://www.neco.org/medal-of-honor/2016-medalists|archivedate=June 8, 2016}}</ref> the Woodrow Wilson Center's Award for Public Service,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.usc.edu/82758/usc-president-nikias-receives-woodrow-wilson-award-for-public-service/|title=USC President Nikias receives Woodrow Wilson Award for Public Service - USC News|website=news.usc.edu|accessdate=June 2, 2018|date=June 14, 2015}}</ref> UNICEF's Spirit of Compassion Award, as well as the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo's]] Distinguished Alumni Award and Clifford C. Furnas Memorial Award.<ref>{{cite web  |url=http://www.buffalo.edu/UBT/UBT-archives/volume26number3/alumni_news/achievementawards.html |title=UB Today: Alumni News |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170928060405/http://www.buffalo.edu/UBT/UBT-archives/volume26number3/alumni_news/achievementawards.html |archive-date=September 28, 2017 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> He also received honorary doctorates from [[Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://huc.edu/news/article/2011/cl-max-nikias-phd-president-university-of-southern-california-brreceived-honorary-doctor-of-humane-letters-from-brhebrew-union-college-jewish-institute-of-religion|title=C.L. Max Nikias, Ph.D., President, University of Southern California, :Received Honorary Doctor of Humane Letters from :Hebrew Union College-Jewish Institute of Religion |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> his alma mater, the [[National Technical University of Athens]];<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/82238/nikiases-wrap-up-europe-trip-with-warm-reception-in-athens/|title=Nikiases wrap up Europe trip with warm reception in Athens - USC News|website=news.usc.edu|accessdate=June 2, 2018|date=May 30, 2015}}</ref> the [[University of Cyprus]];<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kios.ucy.ac.cy/index.php/13-about-us/advisory-board/25-chrysostomos-l-max-nikias.html|title=Chrysostomos L. Max Nikias |publisher=KIOS CoE|accessdate=May 29, 2018}}</ref> University of Crete; University of Piraeus; and University of Strathclyde.<ref>{{cite web|title=USC President Nikias receives honorary degree from Scottish university|url=http://news.usc.edu/124374/usc-president-nikias-receives-honorary-degree-from-scottish-university/|website=USC News|date=June 27, 2017}}</ref> Nikias was awarded the Aristeia medal, the Republic of Cyprus' highest honor in the letters, arts, and sciences. In addition, he received the USC Black Alumni Association's Thomas Kilgore Service Award,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://viterbi.usc.edu/admission/professionalprograms/usc-forum-india/panelists/c-l-max-nikias.htm |title=Viterbi School of Engineering - C. L. Max Nikias |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304031311/https://viterbi.usc.edu/admission/professionalprograms/usc-forum-india/panelists/c-l-max-nikias.htm |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> the Los Angeles Police Museum's Jack Webb Award,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mynewsla.com/education/2014/09/23/usc-president-honored-jack-webb-award/|title=USC President Honored With Jack Webb Award - MyNewsLA.com|date=September 23, 2014|accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> and earned a commendation for cutting-edge research from the [[Governor of California|governor]] of [[California]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccst.us/ccstinfo/board/bios/nikias.php |title=CCST Board Member C. L. Max Nikias|website=www.ccst.us |accessdate=June 2, 2018}}</ref> He has also received an Outstanding Teacher Award from the National Technological University, a distance learning university.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.usc.edu/5020/Engineering-Max-Nikias-succeeds-Len-Silverman-as-dean/|title=Engineering: Max Nikias succeeds Len Silverman as dean|date=May 30, 2001}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nNikias lived on the [[Palos Verdes]] Peninsula, an area southwest of Los Angeles, with his wife and two daughters. Following his inauguration as president of USC, he and his family moved to [[San Marino, California|San Marino]], located closer to both USC campuses.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/oct/14/local/la-me-adv-nikias-20101014|title=Many see a clean slate in Friday's inauguration of USC president|date=October 14, 2010|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=September 27, 2013}}</ref> He and his wife Niki currently live in Manhattan Beach, California.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.whitepages.com/address/3009-N-Poinsettia-Ave/Manhattan-Beach-CA/2zz26TJqSGkmJ52Mxp8910|title=Whitepages|access-date=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n*Nikias, C. L and Shao, M. ''Signal processing with alpha-stable distributions and applications.'' New York: Wiley, c1995. xiii, 168 p. : ill. ; 25&nbsp;cm. {{ISBN|0-471-10647-X}}\n*Nikias, C. L. and Petropulu, A. P. ''Higher-order spectra analysis: a nonlinear signal processing framework.'' Englewood Cliffs, N.J. : PTR Prentice Hall, c1993. xxii, 537 p. : ill. ; 25&nbsp;cm. {{ISBN|0-13-678210-8}}\n*J. G. Proakis, C. Rader, F. Ling, and C. L. Nikias. ''Advanced Signal Processing.'' Macmillan Publishing Company, 1992. {{ISBN|0023968419}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://presidentemeritus.usc.edu USC President Emeritus biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-aca}}\n{{succession box\n| before=[[Steven B. Sample]]\n| title=11th [[President of the University of Southern California]]\n| years=August 3, 2010 \u2013 August 7, 2018\n| after=[[Wanda Austin]] (interim)\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USC presidents}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nikias, C. L. Max}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the University of Southern California]]\n[[Category:American electrical engineers]]\n[[Category:University of Connecticut faculty]]\n[[Category:Northeastern University faculty]]\n[[Category:National Technical University of Athens alumni]]\n[[Category:University at Buffalo alumni]]\n[[Category:Fellow Members of the IEEE]]\n[[Category:People from Famagusta District]]\n[[Category:Cypriot emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Palos Verdes, California]]\n[[Category:Engineers from California]]\n[[Category:Foreign Members of the Russian Academy of Sciences]]\n", "name_user": "Keith D", "label": "safe", "comment": "Space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C._L._Max_Nikias"}
{"title_page": "Fanny Sunesson", "text_new": "[[File:Fanny Sunesson.JPG|thumb|right|Sunesson in 2006]]\n'''Fanny Sunesson,''' born in [[Gothenburg]], [[Sweden]], 9 July 1967, is a professional [[golf]] [[caddie]], who is most noted as being the caddie for [[Nick Faldo]] from 1990 to 1999.\n\n==Career==\nSunesson was born into a golfing family. At age 15, she played golf at amateur standard, and decided to get an insight on the tour by persuading tour player [[Jaime Gonzalez (golfer)|Jaime Gonzalez]] to let her caddie for him in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.jrank.org/pages/1410/Faldo-Nick-Related-Biography-Caddie-Fanny-Sunesson.html |title=Nick Faldo - Related Biography: Caddie Fanny Sunesson |accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe soon began caddying for [[Howard Clark (golfer)|Howard Clark]] during the 1980s before [[Nick Faldo]] asked her to join up with him at the end of 1989.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nFaldo, who had recently undergone major swing surgery with coach [[David Leadbetter (golf instructor)|David Leadbetter]], would win four majors together with Sunesson over a nine-year period. Sunesson decided to part from Faldo in 1999 to caddie for [[Sergio Garc\u00eda|Sergio Garcia]] in what was a short-lived stint of just eight tournaments before being sacked after a run of poor form culminated in Garcia missing the cut in [[The Players Championship]].\n\n===Present day===\nSunesson then had stints with [[Fred Funk]] and [[Notah Begay III]] before being rehired by Nick Faldo. \n\nIt was a coincidence that Sunesson and Faldo both married their respective partners on the same date in July 2001. She serves as a mental coach for [[Martin Kaymer]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nSunesson retired in 2012 to coach and advise full-time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pga.com/news/golf-buzz/fanny-sunesson-retires-caddie |title=Fanny Sunesson retires as caddie |publisher=PGA of America |first=John |last=Holmes |accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgatour.com/tourreport/2012/10/stenson-appreciative-of-former-caddie-fanny.html |title=Stenson discusses Fanny's retirement |publisher=PGA Tour |date=19 October 2013 |first=Bill |last=Cooney |accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Sunesson came out of retirement to serve as Australian golfer [[Adam Scott (golfer)|Adam Scott]]'s caddie for [[The Open Championship]] at Carnoustie and she caddied for fellow Swede [[Henrik Stenson]] at the [[2019 Masters Tournament]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Caddie Hall of Fame inductees]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.golftoday.co.uk/news/yeartodate/news99/faldo13.html ''Golf Today'' report on split with Faldo]\n*[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/article376649.ece ''Sunday Times'' interview]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sunesson, Fanny}}\n[[Category:Caddies]]\n[[Category:Caddie Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from Karlshamn]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Fanny Sunesson.JPG|thumb|right|Sunesson in 2006]]\n'''Fanny Sunesson,''' born in [[Gothenburg]], [[Sweden]] 9 July 1967, is a professional [[golf]] [[caddie]], who is most noted as being the caddie for [[Nick Faldo]] from 1990 to 1999.\n\n==Career==\nSunesson was born into a golfing family. At age 15, she played golf at amateur standard, and decided to get an insight on the tour by persuading tour player [[Jaime Gonzalez (golfer)|Jaime Gonzalez]] to let her caddie for him in 1986.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.jrank.org/pages/1410/Faldo-Nick-Related-Biography-Caddie-Fanny-Sunesson.html |title=Nick Faldo - Related Biography: Caddie Fanny Sunesson |accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nShe soon began caddying for [[Howard Clark (golfer)|Howard Clark]] during the 1980s before [[Nick Faldo]] asked her to join up with him at the end of 1989.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nFaldo, who had recently undergone major swing surgery with coach [[David Leadbetter (golf instructor)|David Leadbetter]], would win four majors together with Sunesson over a nine-year period. Sunesson decided to part from Faldo in 1999 to caddie for [[Sergio Garc\u00eda|Sergio Garcia]] in what was a short-lived stint of just eight tournaments before being sacked after a run of poor form culminated in Garcia missing the cut in [[The Players Championship]].\n\n===Present day===\nSunesson then had stints with [[Fred Funk]] and [[Notah Begay III]] before being rehired by Nick Faldo. \n\nIt was a coincidence that Sunesson and Faldo both married their respective partners on the same date in July 2001. She serves as a mental coach for [[Martin Kaymer]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nSunesson retired in 2012 to coach and advise full-time.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pga.com/news/golf-buzz/fanny-sunesson-retires-caddie |title=Fanny Sunesson retires as caddie |publisher=PGA of America |first=John |last=Holmes |accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pgatour.com/tourreport/2012/10/stenson-appreciative-of-former-caddie-fanny.html |title=Stenson discusses Fanny's retirement |publisher=PGA Tour |date=19 October 2013 |first=Bill |last=Cooney |accessdate=13 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Sunesson came out of retirement to serve as Australian golfer [[Adam Scott (golfer)|Adam Scott]]'s caddie for [[The Open Championship]] at Carnoustie and she caddied for fellow Swede [[Henrik Stenson]] at the [[2019 Masters Tournament]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of Caddie Hall of Fame inductees]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.golftoday.co.uk/news/yeartodate/news99/faldo13.html ''Golf Today'' report on split with Faldo]\n*[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/article376649.ece ''Sunday Times'' interview]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sunesson, Fanny}}\n[[Category:Caddies]]\n[[Category:Caddie Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from Karlshamn]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "EEJB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Editorial", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fanny_Sunesson"}
{"title_page": "WAAKE-UP!", "text_new": "{{short description|Former student and community coalition}}\n'''WAAKE-UP!''' ('''World Awareness and Action Koalition of Equal United Progressives''') was a student and community coalition at the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] (CU-Boulder) active from 1998 to 2001. WAAKE-UP! adopted the motto \"Action without Awareness is ignorant. Awareness without Action is immoral.\" WAAKE-UP! supported many progressive causes, but were best known for the \"[[Sweatshop]] Campaign,\" demanding that [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]] apparel be made in factories supporting fair labor conditions, specifically those endorsed by the [[Worker Rights Consortium]]. The Sweatshop Campaign was not successful, but its goals were later fulfilled by WAAKE-UP!'s successor organizations, 180 at 11 (180 degrees at the 11th hour), CASA (Coalition Against Sweatshop Apparel) and WWJC (World Workers Justice Committee). Like many other progressive organizations in [[Colorado]] their actions were recorded in the Denver Police Spy Files.<ref name=\"ACLUSPY2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aclu-co.org/spyfiles/samplefiles.htm |title=ACLU of Colorado: Spy Files |accessdate=2007-09-18 |author=ACLU of Colorado |date=2006-02-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808135029/http://www.aclu-co.org/spyfiles/samplefiles.htm |archivedate=2007-08-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==The Sweatshop Campaign==\nJuly, 1996 the [[University of Colorado system|University of Colorado]] board of regents adopted the [[Talloires Declaration]] stating that the University must maintain \"institutional neutrality in social and political matters\" unless it is an issue that \"directly affects the university, is detrimental to the achievement of the university's mission and purposes, and/or threatens [[academic freedom]].\"<ref name=\"NEUTRALITY\">{{cite news|author=Oakland L. Childers|title=U. Colorado student group takes on regents' neutrality policy|date=1999-04-06|publisher=University Wire|accessdate=2007-09-22|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-21197490.html}}{{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nApril 1, 1999 CU-Boulder's student union legislative council unanimously passed Council Resolution 106 suggesting CU regents, Chancellor Richard Byyny, and President John Buechner adopt a Basic Commitment to Human Rights, requiring them to take a stand against environmentally irresponsible investments and apparel contracts. The following Monday, April 5, WAAKE-UP! held a press conference asking the University to abandon its institutional neutrality policy for a \"institutional integrity policy.\" WAAKE-UP! members asked the University of Colorado to stop investing in corporations committing human rights violations even if the investments were more lucrative than [[Socially responsible investing|socially responsible alternatives]]. Specifically, WAAKE-UP! members were displeased with the University's investments in corporations like [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]], [[Royal Dutch Shell]], [[Louisiana-Pacific]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Lehman Brothers]] (the parent company of [[Peabody Energy|Peabody Coal]]), [[Texaco]] and [[Unocal]].<ref name=\"NEUTRALITY\"/>\n\nWAAKE-UP! faxed and emailed documentation violations of the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] committed by corporations invested in by the [[University of Colorado system|University of Colorado]] to the regents, Byyny and Buechner, demanding they support Council Resolution 106 by April 12. None of the University officials responded.<ref name=\"NEUTRALITY\"/>\n\nApril 26, 1999, WAAKE-UP! held a rally at the Dalton Trumbo Fountain outside the University Memorial Center on the CU-Boulder campus encouraging the [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]], to dissolve the University's neutrality policy on investments and sign a basic commitment to [[human rights]]. Byyny refused to meet with the protesters. In response, WAAKE-UP! organized a protest on April 28, 1999, blocking traffic at the intersection of Broadway and Regent Drive (located on the edge of the Boulder campus) until Byyny agreed to speak with them. He scheduled an appointment to speak with WAAKE-UP! members on April 30, 1999, at 8 a.m.<ref name=\"CODAILY041999\">{{cite news|author=Oakland L. Childers|title=Group brings U. Colorado-investments protest to the boulevard|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-21355301.html|newspaper=Colorado Daily|date=1999-04-28|accessdate=2010-01-03}}{{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref> WAAKE-UP! continued to organize and grow over the next year.<ref name=\"POSTSDEMANDS\">{{cite news|author=Pamela White |date=2000-03-03 |title=WAAKE-UP! student group posts demands at U. Colorado |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-21 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25241456.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200402/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25241456.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===March 2000===\nMarch 2, 2000, and again on March 15, 2000, WAAKE-UP! presented Chancellor Richard Byyny with a series of demands to ensure ethical apparel licensing was practiced by the University of Colorado. Byyny responded that he would consider adopting them but needed time, more community input, and expressed some specific concerns. Byyny questioned whether one of WAAKE-UP!'s demands, [[equal pay for women]] making [[University of Colorado system|University of Colorado]] apparel, was a [[human right]] or a [[cultural norm]]. According to the [[United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] it is not a cultural norm, Article 23, Section 2 states: \"Everyone, without any discrimination, has the right to equal pay for equal work.\"<ref name=\"POSTSDEMANDS\"/><ref name=\"CODAILY03172000\">{{cite news|author=Pamela White|title=Opinion: Byyny fails CU at WAAKE-UP! talks: Spirit of Norlin dead at CU|date=2000-03-17|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020308001325/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/17|archivedate=2002-03-08}}</ref><ref name=\"MEASURES\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |title=U. Colorado chancellor, students debate anti-sweatshop measures |date=2000-03-16 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25493515.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200506/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25493515.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nMarch 19, 2000, WAAKE-UP! members protested outside of the [[Abercrombie & Fitch]] store on the [[Pearl Street Mall]] in [[Boulder, Colorado]], a few blocks away from the CU-Boulder campus. WAAKE-UP! claimed Abercrombie & Fitch laborers were exploited and worked in [[sweatshop]] conditions.<ref name=\"CODAILY03202000\">{{cite news|title=Colorado Daily Front Page|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/20|newspaper=Colorado Daily|date=2000-03-20|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020308001325/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/20|archivedate=2002-03-08}}</ref>\n\nMarch 21, 2000, CU-Boulder professor [[Ira Chernus]] announced that he had written a resolution in support of WAAKE-UP!'s demands and that it would be voted on during the next Boulder Faculty Assembly. It included creating a Code of Conduct for Ethical Apparel Licensing as well as an Investment Board of Ethics which would be monitored by an Internal Advisory Board for compliance with the Code of Conduct.<ref name=\"CODAILY03222000\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=CU profs may support Code: BFA to consider sweatshop resolution|date=2000-03-17|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]}}</ref> This was in addition to resolutions passed by the Assembly on March 13, 2000, calling for WAAKE-UP!, Byyny, and Vice Chancellor Ronald Stump to continue a good-faith discussion on University of Colorado apparel licensing.<ref name=\"BEER2000A\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/MOTRES/xr1-0300.html |title=BFAX-R-1-0300: Facilitation |accessdate=2010-01-03 |author=Francis A. Beer |author2=Sierra Swearingen |author3=Britt Cartrite |date=2000-03-13 |archivedate=2010-01-03 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUlQw1Z9?url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/MOTRES/xr1-0300.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> The resolutions were forwarded to the Chancellor's office on March 14, 2000.<ref name=\"BEER2000B\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/MOTRES/index.html |title=BFA Motions and Resolutions |accessdate=2010-01-02 |author=Francis A. Beer |author2=Sierra Swearingen |author3=Britt Cartrite |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUlXiCd3?url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/MOTRES/index.html |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"BEER2000C\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/EXCOM/XMINARCH/XARCH00/031300.html |title=BFA Executive Committee Minutes |accessdate=2010-01-03 |author=Francis A. Beer |author2=Sierra Swearingen |author3=Britt Cartrite |date=2000-03-13 |archivedate=2000-09-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000919212421/http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/EXCOM/XMINARCH/XARCH00/031300.html |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===April 2000===\nApril 4, 2000, WAAKE-UP! held a mock trial outside the University Memorial Center by the Dalton Trumbo Fountain with the \"Sweatshop King\", a {{convert|10|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} street theater puppet. University of Colorado police officers, Detective Tim DeLaria and Lt. Michelle Irving monitored the demonstration and took photographs of those participating. Both officers belonged to the Investigations and Community Service Unit of the [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]] Police Department.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000A\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=\"Sweatshop King\" reigns: Cops keep eye on WAAKE-UP! rally, students demand \"no sweat\"|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/5%20sweatr|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-05|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/5%20sweatr|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 5, 2000, WAAKE-UP! demanded that the University of Colorado join the [[Worker Rights Consortium]] by the end of the day on April 6, 2000. Meeting this deadline would have allowed representatives from the University to attend a [[Worker Rights Consortium]] meeting taking place in New York City on April 7, 2000.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000B\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Sweatshop issue gaining momentum: WAAKE-UP! gives CU deadline to join WRC|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/6|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-06|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/6|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 6, 2000, the Boulder Faculty Assembly voted in favor of a resolution supporting WAAKE-UP!'s demands, though it didn't specifically include the requirement that the University of Colorado should join the [[Worker Rights Consortium]]. The resolution was passed on a voice vote with 30 faculty members in attendance, the vast majority voting in favor of it.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000C\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=BFA demands \"no sweat\"|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/7%20daily%20bfa|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-07|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/7%20daily%20bfa|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref> The Assembly claimed that the [[United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] served as a basis for the proposed Code of Conduct. Byyny created an ad hoc group of ten [[University of Colorado Boulder|CU-Boulder]] faculty, staff, and students to investigate WAAKE-UP!'s proposal. Byyny's ad hoc group's first meeting was behind closed doors, against Colorado's [[Open Meeting Law]]<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000C 2\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Habitat for humanity|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-11|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref> WAAKE-UP! was invited to attend the first meeting, but boycotted it in protest. A WAAKE-UP! member was present at all subsequent meetings.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000D\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=WAAKE-UP! will attend: But students are critical of CU administration's \"task group\" meeting|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-11|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Boulder Faculty Assembly had organized three community forums in an effort to get the community input Byyny requested. Byyny never attended any of the forums organized by the Assembly. University of Colorado Vice Chancellor Paul Tabolt, however, attended one of the forums and raised a few questions, but left without giving forum attendees a chance to respond to them.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000C\"/> Tabolt stated [[collective bargaining]] is not a right (an opinion not supported by the [[United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights]]) and that he believed it was fair to pay workers less than what they need to live.<ref>{{cite news|title=Opinion: CU showing its true colors|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/10%20opinion|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-10|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/10%20opinion|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 7, 2000, the University of Colorado Student Union unanimously supported WAAKE-UP!'s demand that the University join the [[Worker Rights Consortium]], passing on a vote of 13\u20130. However, this failed to produce any action from the Office of the Chancellor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Student reps back WRC: Note campus support growing for anti-sweatshop measures; Byyny's task force to meet today|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/10%20ucsu|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-10|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/10%20ucsu|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn the meantime WAAKE-UP! was busy circulating a petition among students demanding that the University of Colorado join the Worker Rights Consortium (gathering over 2000 signatures) and on April 10, 2000, and built a [[shantytown]] in the Norlin Quadrangle on the CU-Boulder campus to draw attention to their campaign and gain visibility during the [[Conference on World Affairs]]. In reference to the conference, WAAKE-UP! members named the shantytown the \"Conference on World Despairs.\" WAAKE-UP! initially created the shantytown without the University's permission, but later obtained \"temporary structure\" permits after it was established. The construction of the shantytown started just hours before the [[Conference on World Affairs]]' opening procession through the Norlin Quadrangle. WAAKE-UP! said the shantytown was meant to symbolize the poor living conditions of sweatshop workers. WAAKE-UP!'s shantytown was reminiscent of a previous one constructed in 1988 outside the Dalton Trumbo Fountain to protest the University of Colorado's investment in the South African [[apartheid]] regime.<ref name=\"HABITAT\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Habitat for humanity|date=2000-04-11|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|accessdate=2007-09-21|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"POPPEN2000\">{{cite news|author=Julie Poppen|title=Students demand CU join consortium: Protesters want CU to be sure sweatshops don't make university-licensed apparel|newspaper=[[Daily Camera]]|date=2000-04-11|accessdate=2007-09-21|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20camera|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20camera|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"STILLSTANDS\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |date=2000-04-12 |title=Anti-sweatshop still stands at U. Colorado despite threats |publisher=University Wire |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25798656.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200412/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25798656.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nWAAKE-UP! members stayed at the [[shantytown]] in shifts during the day and night. During the day they held teach-ins, distributed fliers, and explained the purpose of the shantytown to passersby. Among other topics, WAAKE-UP! members discussed [[Gary Barnett]]'s threats to suspend players covering up [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] logos on their uniforms. Community members and local businesses supported them by supplying food and water.<ref name=\"STILLSTANDS\"/><ref name=\"CAMP\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Camp still stands: Threat of removal doesn't deter activists|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-12|accessdate=2007-09-21|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/12%20daily|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/12%20daily|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"SWOOSH\">{{cite news|author=Ted Dawson and Terje Langeland |title=Colorado football players punished for covering up Nike 'swoosh' |date=2000-04-26 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26204539.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200516/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26204539.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref> At 3 a.m. on April 13, 2000, approximately ten people came by the shantytown and set off fireworks, threw water balloons and distributed flyers that read \"kegs not contraversy (sic).\" WAAKE-UP! members sleeping at the [[shantytown]] said they appreciated the [[nonviolent]] protest methods used by the \"anti-protest protesters.\"<ref name=\"SHANTYTOWN\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Shantytown's future uncertain|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|accessdate=2007-09-21|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14%20shanty|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\nApril 15, 2000 WAAKE-UP! members staying at the shantytown abandoned it due to heavy snow, but later returned.\nApril 17, 2000 more than 150 people attended a rally at WAAKE-UP!'s shantytown focusing on high school education and in solidarity with protests the previous day in [[Washington D.C.]] against the [[International Monetary Fund]] and [[World Bank]].<ref name=\"SNOWFALL\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Snowfall only temporary setback for shantytown|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-17|accessdate=2007-09-21|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/17%20shanty|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/17%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\nApril 13, 2000, WAAKE-UP! began meeting with the ad hoc committee formed by Chancellor Byyny. Though both sides claimed progress was being made, the University administration favored joining the [[Fair Labor Association]] over the [[Worker Rights Consortium]]. WAAKE-UP! were critical of the Fair Labor Association as much of its funding came from organizations it monitored creating a potential [[conflict of interest]].<ref name=\"PROGRESS\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Progress made on students' demands: WAAKE-UP! meets with CU on code of conduct|date=2000-04-14|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"TASKFORCE\">{{cite news|title=Task force discusses sweatshop labor|date=2000-04-14|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Daily Camera]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14%20camera|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14%20camera|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 17, 2000, the ad hoc group put together by Byyny recommended a one-year conditional membership in the Worker Rights Consortium, though it still needed to be approved by a larger ad hoc committee, appointed by the Chancellor, and the Chancellor himself. The committee also recommended they monitor the [[Fair Labor Association]] during that year to decide if it would be worth joining. Additionally, the committee raised some questions as to how the Code of Conduct would apply to contracts [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] had with the CU-Boulder athletics department, which operated somewhat autonomously.<ref name=\"GROUPAPPROVES\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Group approves WRC: CU subcommittee endorses joining consortium for one-year trial, but move still needs Byyny's approval|date=2000-04-18|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/18|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"ADAMS2000\">{{cite news|author=Emma Adams|title=No proposals from CU labor panel|date=2000-04-18|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Daily Camera]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/18%20camera|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/18%20camera|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nBy April 19, 2000 the larger ad hoc committee said it was putting the finishing touches on the Code of Conduct and were getting ready to send it to Byyny to review.<ref name=\"ONEAUTOGRAPH\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=One autograph away: CU's membership in sweatshop watchdog group now hinges on chancellor's signature|date=2000-04-19|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/19|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/19|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref> WAAKE-UP! pressured Byyny to sign it as soon as he possibly could.<ref name=\"NEXTWEEK\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Students press Byynt on WRC: Chancellor unlikely to sign agreement until next week|date=2000-04-20|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/20|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 25, 2000, Chancellor Byyny announced that he would not sign the [[anti-sweatshop]] policy approved by the ad hoc committees. Instead, Byyny made some changes to the existing policy using the committee's recommendations as guidelines.<ref name=\"WHITE2000\">{{cite news|author=Pamela White|title=Byyny ought to resign|date=2000-04-27|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20pamela|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20pamela|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 26, 2000, [[Ralph Nader]] visited the CU-Boulder campus. Nader endorsed WAAKE-UP!'s demands and condemned Byyny's decision not to join the Worker Rights Consortium. Nader speculated that the University's decision might be influenced by an announcement [[Phil Knight]] had recently made, stating that he would retract a thirty million dollar donation to the [[University of Oregon]] after they joined the [[Worker Rights Consortium]].<ref name=\"NADER\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Nader backs WAAKE-UP!|date=2000-04-27|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20nader|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20nader|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nWAAKE-UP! met with Byyny the same day. Byyny gave few specifics about his decision not to follow the committee's recommendations. A WAAKE-UP! member had brought a water gun to the meeting, and showed it to the police officers present. Later in the meeting officer Tim DeLaria attempted to grab the water gun out of the activist's hand, causing it to squirt two other officers. DeLaria attempted to arrest the activist for this, though Police Lt. John Kish reversed DeLaria's decision and let the water-gun carrying activist off with a warning. Professor Ira Chernus had protested the unnecessary show of force during this and previous meetings.<ref name=\"HEAT\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Chancellor takes heat|date=2000-04-27|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20byyny|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20byyny|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\n===May 2000===\nMay 3, 2000, Byyny signed a revised version of the university apparel licensing policy recommended by the executive committee. The revisions were made in a closed door meeting, and public input was not sought on the changes. The revised version required licensees to comply with labor laws and regulations of their governments, and prohibited discrimination, harassment, child labor, [[Unfree labour|forced labor]] and [[Penal labour|prison labor]].<ref name=\"REALCHANGE\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |title=U. Colorado signs apparel policy, activists promise to fight for 'real change' |date=2000-03-04 |publisher=University Wire |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26399077.html |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200432/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26399077.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref> WAAKE-UP! members were disappointed with vague language used in revision and weakened stance on [[women's rights]] and maximum hours allowed in a [[workweek]].<ref name=\"VAGUE\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |title=Anti-sweatshop activists call proposed U. Colorado code too 'vague' |date=2000-05-03 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26374850.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200922/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26374850.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nMay 4, 2000, in response to Byyny's rejection of the committee's licensing recommendations, WAAKE-UP! and Boulder [[Biotic Baking Brigade]] member, Sara Toombs (a.k.a. Agent Moon Pie), [[Pieing|pied]] Chancellor Byyny while he was giving a speech on the CU-Boulder campus.<ref name=\"BBB2001\">{{cite news|url=http://bioticbakingbrigade.org/communique011301.html |title=Just dessets: Sweet confection targeted CU policy on sweatshop labor |accessdate=2010-01-03 |author=Michael A. de Yoanna |date=January 2001 |newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]] |archivedate=2003-04-11 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030411190638/http://bioticbakingbrigade.org/communique011301.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> Toombs was later tried for [[assault]]. Byyny claimed he incurred numerous [[dry cleaning]] bills and that his cheek was slightly bruised as a result of the pieing. Toombs testified at the trial that she baked the organic blueberry pie herself, and that she used her training in [[nonviolent resistance]] techniques as well as the benefit of practice with friends to \"squoosh\" the pie in Byyny's face without harming him. The jury found that she was not guilty of assault but did find her guilty of [[harassment]] and [[Mischief|criminal mischief]]. Toombs was sentenced to six months of unsupervised probation, thirty hours of [[community service]], and was ordered to write Byyny a letter of apology. The verdict was considered a victory by Toombs, her attorneys, and her supporters.<ref name=\"BBB2001\"/>\n\nBefore the trial WAAKE-UP! members staged a \"sui-pied\", a demonstration where they hit themselves in the face with pies to show how harmless it was, outside the Boulder County Justice Center.<ref name=\"BBB2001\"/>\n\n===September 2000===\nSeptember 18, 2000, the University of Colorado confirmed suspicions it had joined the [[Fair Labor Association]] on May 3, 2000. WAAKE-UP! members had only learned of the decision from a discussion with a FLA representative, and were upset that they were not consulted about or informed of the decision.<ref name=\"HOYA2000\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehoya.com/news/092200/news9.htm |title=Students Perceive Move to DLA as 'Betrayal' |accessdate=2007-09-19 |date=2000-09-22 |publisher=[[The Hoya]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929091853/http://www.thehoya.com/news/092200/news9.htm |archivedate=2007-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"FLABETRAYAL\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |title=U. Colorado joins Fair Labor Association; student activists view decision as 'betrayal' |date=2000-09-20 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-32310150.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200847/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-32310150.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref> Following the news, WAAKE-UP! members said they would continue the campaign making three demands on the University: (1) to adopt a strong licensing policy that will eliminate the possibility of doing business with companies that use sweatshop labor, (2) form an internal monitoring board within the University of Colorado that will evaluate whether companies comply with the licensing policy and to investigate and research possible violations, and (3) to join the Worker Rights Consortium (WRC) as an external monitoring agency that will investigate conditions in the factories in which apparel is made. Although it was not in the three demands, WAAKE-UP! also asked that the University relinquish its membership in the [[Fair Labor Association]].<ref name=\"WADLINGE\">{{cite web|url=http://ucsu.colorado.edu/~wadlinge/actnow.html|author=Nina Wadlinger|title=ACTION|accessdate=2007-09-19|date=April 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010428120525/http://ucsu.colorado.edu/~wadlinge/actnow.html|archivedate=2001-04-28}}</ref>\n\n===Continued organizing and victory===\nNovember 15, 2001 former WAAKE-UP! organizer Scott Silber returned to CU-Boulder to give a talk titled ''American Jihad Inc.: Corporate Crusades for the Free Market Faith'' about corporate influence in the post-September 11 world.<ref name=\"WEEKLY2001\">{{cite news|url=http://www.boulderweekly.com/archive/111501/newsspin.html|author=Editorial Staff|title=Scott Silber WAAKEs up CU: Sweat shop activist returns|date=2001-11-15|publisher=[[Boulder Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051122202527/http://www.boulderweekly.com/archive/111501/newsspin.html|archivedate=2005-11-22}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2004 to 2006 the student groups 180 degrees at the 11th hour, CASA (Coalition Against Sweatshop Apparel), and WWJC (World Workers Justice Committee) organized on the [[University of Colorado Boulder|CU-Boulder]] campus, again trying to get the University to join the [[Worker Rights Consortium]], this time petitioning Chancellor Phil Distefano.<ref name=\"WEEKLY2005\">{{cite news|url=http://www.boulderweekly.com/archive/031705/coverstory.html|author=Pamela White|title=The triumphant return of crachers: A pissed-off corporate-crime-fighting chicken comes back to CU to end sweatshop abuses|date=2005-03-17|publisher=[[Boulder Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051122221510/http://www.boulderweekly.com/archive/031705/coverstory.html|archivedate=2005-11-22}}</ref>\n\nMay 5, 2005, the groups held a hunger strike inside Distefano's office, until it was announced that the University would begin the affiliation process. CASA members again went on hunger strike for fifteen days from April 12 to April 27, 2006 until the University accepted the Designated Supplier Program proposed by the United Students Against Sweatshops.<ref name=\"RMR\">{{cite news|url=http://rockymountainresister.org/?q=node/10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009174927/http://rockymountainresister.org/?q=node%2F10|archivedate=2007-10-09|title=24-HR. Hunger Strike, Occupation Ends 6-Year CU Sweatshop Fight|date=2005-05-07|publisher=The Rocky Mountain Resister|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Other causes and campaigns==\n=== Career fair demonstration ===\nWAAKE-UP! members had requested a table at career fairs held on the CU-Boulder campus to inform students about the behavior of corporations trying to recruit them, but had been denied by CU-Boulder administration. In response, on January 31, 2000, WAAKE-UP! held a demonstration during a career fair, accompanied by [[TV Nation]]'s Crackers the Corporate Crime-Fighting Chicken, carrying a banner that read \"Students are NOT products, Teachers are NOT tools, The University is NOT a factory!\"<ref name=\"GEORGEANNEDAILY\">{{cite news|url=http://www.stp.georgiasouthern.edu/George-Anne/arc5/spr00/0131nws.html |author=TMS Campus |title=National News Brief: Students protest at U. of Colo. |date=2000-01-31 |publisher=[[The George-Anne Daily]] |accessdate=2010-01-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909091236/http://www.stp.georgiasouthern.edu/George-Anne/arc5/spr00/0131nws.html |archivedate=2006-09-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"CAREERFAIR\">{{cite news|author=Amanda Hill |title=U. Colorado group protests career fair |date=2000-01-26 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-24764377.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200557/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-24764377.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Die-in to support the U'wa===\nMarch 14, 2000, WAAKE-UP! members staged a [[die-in]] in front of the World Trade Center buildings in [[Denver, Colorado]] to raise awareness about the [[U'wa people|U'wa]]'s struggle against the [[Occidental Petroleum Corporation]]. There were approximate 20 police officers at the protest who dragged the limp protesters away from the scene, at one point dragging a protester's head into a [[street gutter]]. One of the protesters was taken in to custody without being read his [[Miranda Rights]].<ref name=\"HALFHOUR\">{{cite news|author=Leo Griep-Ruiz|title=Opinion: A half hour in downtown Denver|date=2000-03-21|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020308001325/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/20|archivedate=2002-03-08}}</ref>\n\n===A16 solidarity march===\nOn April 15, 2000 WAAKE-UP! organized a march of more than 400 people in Boulder in solidarity with protests of the [[World Bank]] and [[International Monetary Fund]] in [[Washington D.C.]]. The protests were a continuation of those at the [[WTO Ministerial Conference of 1999 protest activity|Ministerial Conference of 1999]] in [[Seattle, Washington]].<ref name=\"INDYMEDIA\">{{cite web|url=http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/850 |title=A15 \u2013 Boulder, CO, Solidarity March |date=2000-04-16 |author=Tammi Laninga |publisher=[[Washington, D.C.|DC]] [[Independent Media Center|Indymedia]] |archivedate=2010-01-03 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUmIkxS8?url=http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/850 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On April 9, 2000, The ''[[Daily Camera]]'' published an article by Ira Chernus in support of the march supporting the protest. Speakers at the protest included Cecilia Zarate-Laun and David Pellow.<ref name=\"LOCALA15\">{{cite news|author =Amanda Hill|title=Local A15 events slated|date=2000-04-11|accessdate=2007-09-27|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20a15|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20a15|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref> The protest was non-violent and there was no hostile contact with the police during it.<ref name=\"MIRRORED\">{{cite news|author =Amanda Hill|title=Protest in Washington D.C. mirrored in Boulder|date=2000-04-17|accessdate=2007-09-27|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/17%20a15daily|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/17%20a15daily|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nSome WAAKE-UP! members, however, went to the April 16 protest in Washington D.C., and came prepared to treat protesters who might be injured. They brought medical supplies and treated people who had been [[pepper spray]]ed.<ref name=\"PLAINSMAN2000\">{{cite news|url=http://www.auburn.edu/student_info/plainsman/archives/042000/042000nprotest.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050507092543/http://www.auburn.edu/student_info/plainsman/archives/042000/042000nprotest.html|archivedate=2005-05-07|title=\"This is what democracy looks like.\" : Protests Erupt in Washington, D.C.|date=2000-04-20|author=Matt Comer|publisher=[[The Auburn Plainsman]]}}</ref>\n\n===Flatirons Crossing protest===\nAugust 11, 2000, WAAKE-UP! members protested the opening of the Flatirons Crossing mall in [[Broomfield, Colorado]]. WAAKE-UP! believed the mall promoted [[consumerism]] and contributed to [[urban sprawl]].<ref name=\"CAMPUSPRESS\">{{cite news|url=http://newmedia.colorado.edu/press/stories/pages/110.html |title=FlatIron Crossing takes shopping to the extreme |date=2000-09-20 |publisher=[[The Campus Press]] |author=Hanh Tran |archivedate=2001-03-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010303165340/http://newmedia.colorado.edu/press/stories/pages/110.html |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===S26 Solidarity March===\nSeptember 25, 2000, WAAKE-UP! members and other activists marched on [[Pearl Street Mall]] in [[Boulder, Colorado]]. The action was in solidarity with protests against the [[International Monetary Fund]] and [[World Bank]] in [[Prague]]. Protesters urged passersby at stores on the Pearl Street Mall such as [[Gap (clothing retailer)|GAP]], [[Banana Republic (clothing retailer)|Banana Republic]], [[Abercrombie & Fitch]], [[Starbucks]], and [[Borders Group|Borders Bookstore]] (under construction at the time) to support local business, chanting \"Take your crap back to the Gap\" and \"Human need, not corporate greed.\" This was a smaller protest compared to one following it in [[Denver, Colorado]] on September 26, 2000.<ref name=\"YOANNA20000925\">{{cite news|url=http://www.colorado.edu/AmStudies/lewis/2010/gap.htm |title=Boulderites unite with Prague protesters: Denver demonstration slated for Tuesday |date=2000-09-25 |newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]] |author=Michael A. de Yoanna |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUr1A3YP?url=http://www.colorado.edu/AmStudies/lewis/2010/gap.htm |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"PARKER\">{{cite news|title=Views mixed on local vs. outside-owned businesses|date=2000-09-25|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|author=Lisa Parker|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/s2k.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040119102934/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/s2k.html|archivedate=2004-01-19}}</ref>\n\n===Buy Nothing Day===\nNovember 23, 2001, WAAKE-UP! members supported the [[Buy Nothing Day]] protests in [[Boulder, Colorado]], organized by CU-Boulder professor Kayann Short, who focused it on how [[consumerism]] affects women.<ref name=\"BND-LIST\">{{cite mailing list|url=http://www.ddh.nl/pipermail/bnd-list/2001/000050.html |title=Why Shop? Week in Colorado |date=2001-11-17 |accessdate=2007-09-19 |mailinglist=Bnd-list |last=Short |first=Kayann |archivedate=2007-10-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020073527/http://www.ddh.nl/pipermail/bnd-list/2001/000050.html |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"ANTICONSUMERISM\">{{cite news|author=Fred Baerkircher |title=U. Colorado instructor launches anti-consumerism campaign |date=2001-11-15 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-48239447.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516201751/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-48239447.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===The People's Summit on Globalization===\nWAAKE-UP! supported the [[People's Summit]] on Globalization, a conference discussing how [[globalization]] affects people around the world. The conference focused specifically on institutions such as the [[World Bank]], [[International Monetary Fund]], and the [[World Trade Organization]]. The conference was held March 8\u201311, 2001, and featured speakers such as [[Paul Hawken]], Chol Soon Rhie, Danny Kennedy, [[Kevin Danaher (activist)|Kevin Danaher]], Ignacio Ibarra, Njoki Njoroge Njehu, Raquel Sancho, [[Amy Goodman]], Julie Davids, Carlos Zorrilla, Michael Morrill, Orrin Williams, [[Ward Churchill]], Evelyn Hu-DeHart, Irungu Houghton, Jason Wallach, and William Begay.<ref name=\"PEOPLESUMMIT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/StudentGroups/summit/ |title=The People's Summit on Globalization and Concurrent Events : \"A conference to educate, empower, and united people striving for justice in the face of corporate globalization\" |date=2001-03-08 |author=The Coalition for Economic Justice |archivedate=2010-01-03 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUmhfpe5?url=http://www.colorado.edu/StudentGroups/summit/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===The Rocky Mountain Rebels===\n'''The Rocky Mountain Rebels''' were a group of [[Radical cheerleading|Radical Cheerleaders]] in WAAKE-UP!. They were present at nearly every WAAKE-UP! demonstration cheering on the protesters.<ref name=\"BECKEREJ\">{{cite web|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~beckerej/Home.html|author=Emily Becker|title=Radical Cheerleaders|accessdate=2007-09-19|year=2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010725092749/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~beckerej/Home.html|archivedate=2001-07-25}}</ref><ref name=\"RADICALRUSH\">{{cite news|author=Lisa Parker |title=U. Colorado Radical Rush week kicks off with film |date=2000-09-13 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-31823277.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200648/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-31823277.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Radical Rush===\nAs an alternative to [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity and sorority]] rushes, WAAKE-UP! members held a \"Radical Rush\" at the beginning of each semester in an attempt to get incoming students acquainted with all of the radical student organizations on campus.<ref name=\"RADICALRUSH\"/><ref name=\"RADICALRUSHSITE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/studentgroups/radicalrush/|title=Radical Rush|accessdate=2007-09-19|year=2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010911041255/http://www.colorado.edu/studentgroups/radicalrush/|archivedate=2001-09-11}}</ref><ref name=\"RADICALRUSH2001\">{{cite news|author=Jessika Fruchter |title=Alternative rush kicks off at U. Colorado |date=2001-09-05 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-46686422.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516201327/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-46686422.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref> The Radical Rush tradition continued after WAAKE-UP! was defunct.<ref name=\"RADICALRUSH2002\">{{cite news|author=Jenny Atchley |title='Radical Rush' week exposes U. Colorado students to activist groups |date=2002-09-03 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-55877917.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200947/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-55877917.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===This Is What Democracy Looks Like===\nNovember 30, 2000, WAAKE-UP! co-sponsored showings of the film ''This Is What Democracy Looks Like'' along with End Sanctions Now!, the Rocky Mountain Independent Media Center, AMP, Art & Revolution, [[Free Speech TV]] and [[KGNU]].<ref name=\"LOOKSLIKE1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisdemocracy.org/n30.html|title=THIS IS WHAT DEMOCRACY LOOKS LIKE|accessdate=2007-09-19|date=November 2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051215090901/http://www.thisisdemocracy.org/n30.html|archivedate=2005-12-15}}</ref><ref name=\"LOOKSLIKE2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisdemocracy.org/7_n30list.html|title=THIS IS WHAT DEMOCRACY LOOKS LIKE|accessdate=2007-09-19|date=November 2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230091833/http://www.thisisdemocracy.org/7_n30list.html|archivedate=2006-12-30}}</ref>\n\n===Unity 2000===\nWAAKE-UP! endorsed Unity 2000, a group of concerned citizens and activists who protested at the [[Republican National Convention]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] on July 30, 2000.<ref name=\"ABOLITION\">{{cite mailing list|url=http://www.xmission.com/pub/lists/abolition-usa/archive/v01.n300 |title=Should political parties be able to endorse Unity 2000? |date=2000-05-10 |accessdate=2007-09-19 |mailinglist=abolition-usa-digest |last=Morrill |first=Michael |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUmotpzR?url=http://www.xmission.com/pub/lists/abolition-usa/archive/v01.n300 |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"GENDERRADIO\">{{cite episode|title=GenderTalk|series=2000 Programs|url=http://www.gendertalk.com/radio/programs/251/gt266.shtml|credits=Hosted by Nancy Nangeroni and Gordene O. MacKenzie. Featuring Daviko Marcel (transman and director of Boston's Transgender Education Network, and partner [name removed by request], on ground breaking research on health care needs for trans persons) and Michael Morrill (organizer of the upcoming \"Unity 2000 March\" in Philadelphia during the Republican National Convention)|station=WMBR|location=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]|airdate=2000-07-10|number=266|archivedate=2015-09-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910035033/http://www.gendertalk.com/radio/programs/251/gt266.shtml}}</ref>\n\n==Presence in the Denver Police spy files==\nThe Colorado [[ACLU]] was able to obtain files collected by the FBI's [[Joint Terrorism Task Force]] while working with local law enforcement in [[Denver, Colorado]] as a result of the Denver Police Spy File litigation. The files show that emails were intercepted from WAAKE-UP!'s email list, specifically about a protest planned for the Aspen Institutes's Summit on Globalization and the Human Condition in July 2000. Tim DeLaria of the CU-Boulder police department intercepted the email and forwarded it to George Kennedy in the Denver Police Department's Intelligence Unit. Kennedy wrote back to Tim DeLaria saying he would forward the email to Tom Fisher of the FBI Joint Terrorism Task Force to contact someone in [[Aspen, Colorado]].<ref name=\"SPYFILESX\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coloradoaclu.org/spyfiles/fbifiles.htm |author=ACLU of Colorado |title=ACLU of Colorado: Spy Files |accessdate=2007-09-19 |date=2006-02-24 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUkeulc8?url=http://www.aclu-co.org/spyfiles/fbifiles.htm |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the exchange about the Aspen Institutes's Summit on Globalization, it also includes an exchange between Tim DeLaria and the Denver Police Department about a march organized by WAAKE-UP! in support of the [[U'wa people|U'wa]].<ref name=\"DELARIA2000\">{{cite mailing list|url=http://www.siliconashes.net/~talbert/emails.pdf |title=Fw: MARCH FOR THE U'wa (fwd) |date=2000-10-06 |accessdate=2010-01-02 |mailinglist=waake-up |last=Delaria |first=Tim |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUn1tJ0M?url=http://www.siliconashes.net/~talbert/emails.pdf |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The WAAKE-UP! email list was one of 24 lists mentioned in a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] request by the Colorado ACLU in relation to the Denver Police Spy files case.<ref name=\"SILVERSTEIN2004\">{{cite journal|title=Re: Request under Freedom of Information Act and Privacy Act |date=2004-12-02 |last=Silverstein |first=Mark |url=https://www.aclu.org/FilesPDFs/foia_co.pdf |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUq2f9Sw?url=http://www.aclu.org/FilesPDFs/foia_co.pdf |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nLinda Gorman of the [[Independence Institute]] wrote two articles decrying WAAKE-UP!.<ref name=\"GORMAN2000A\">{{cite web|title=Linda Gorman|publisher=Independence Institute |date=2000-05-18|url=http://www.i2i.org/main/author.php?author_id=80|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061003124227/http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=288|archivedate=2006-10-03}}</ref> Gorman claimed that policies advocated by WAAKE-UP! would put the working poor making [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]] apparel out of work. Gorman was also very critical of Sara Toombs' choice of fillings for the pie baked to [[Pieing|pie]] Chancellor Byyny; stating that at the time of year when the pie was baked [[blueberries]] were out of season and may have been imported by a corporation exploiting its workers south of the United States border. Gorman suggested Toombs should have made a [[rhubarb]] pie, as rhubarb was in season at the time.<ref name=\"GORMAN2000B\">{{cite web|author=Linda Gorman |title=Against Everything, For What? |publisher=Independence Institute |date=2000-05-03 |accessdate=2007-09-21 |url=http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=284 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021517/http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=284 |archivedate=2007-09-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"GORMAN2000C\">{{cite web|author=Linda Gorman |title=WAAKE-UP! and Feel Better\u2014Throw the Poor Our of Work |publisher=Independence Institute |date=2000-05-18 |accessdate=2007-09-21 |url=http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=288 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061003124227/http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=288 |archivedate=2006-10-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20010420170521/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/doitjust.html WAAKE-UP!'s home page] (archive.org)\n* [https://archive.is/20130415060558/http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/2535 A Video Documentary About WAAKE-UP! by Andrew Dieringer of the Activist Media Project] (DC Indymedia)\n* [https://archive.is/20130415010029/http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/1479 A Video Documentary on WAAKE-UP!'s A16 Solidarity March] (DC Indymedia)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20010819074557/http://ucsu.colorado.edu/~wadlinge/news.html Archive of WAAKE-UP!'s news coverage] (archive.org)\n* [http://www.mail-archive.com/waake-up@lists.colorado.edu/ WAAKE-UP!'s Email List Archives]\n* [http://www.colorado.edu/studentgroups/18011/ 180*11's home page] (colorado.edu)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090114045548/http://www.culaborsolidarity.org/ the Coalition Against Sweatshop Abuse's home page] (archive.org)\n\n[[Category:Anti-globalization protests]]\n[[Category:Anti-globalization organizations]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1998]]\n[[Category:2001 disestablishments in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Student political organizations]]\n", "text_old": "'''WAAKE-UP!''' ('''World Awareness and Action Koalition of Equal United Progressives''') was a student and community coalition at the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] (CU-Boulder) active from 1998 to 2001. WAAKE-UP! adopted the motto \"Action without Awareness is ignorant. Awareness without Action is immoral.\" WAAKE-UP! supported many progressive causes, but were best known for the \"[[Sweatshop]] Campaign,\" demanding that [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]] apparel be made in factories supporting fair labor conditions, specifically those endorsed by the [[Worker Rights Consortium]]. The Sweatshop Campaign was not successful, but its goals were later fulfilled by WAAKE-UP!'s successor organizations, 180 at 11 (180 degrees at the 11th hour), CASA (Coalition Against Sweatshop Apparel) and WWJC (World Workers Justice Committee). Like many other progressive organizations in [[Colorado]] their actions were recorded in the Denver Police Spy Files.<ref name=\"ACLUSPY2006\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aclu-co.org/spyfiles/samplefiles.htm |title=ACLU of Colorado: Spy Files |accessdate=2007-09-18 |author=ACLU of Colorado |date=2006-02-24 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808135029/http://www.aclu-co.org/spyfiles/samplefiles.htm |archivedate=2007-08-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==The Sweatshop Campaign==\nJuly, 1996 the [[University of Colorado system|University of Colorado]] board of regents adopted the [[Talloires Declaration]] stating that the University must maintain \"institutional neutrality in social and political matters\" unless it is an issue that \"directly affects the university, is detrimental to the achievement of the university's mission and purposes, and/or threatens [[academic freedom]].\"<ref name=\"NEUTRALITY\">{{cite news|author=Oakland L. Childers|title=U. Colorado student group takes on regents' neutrality policy|date=1999-04-06|publisher=University Wire|accessdate=2007-09-22|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-21197490.html}}{{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref>\n\nApril 1, 1999 CU-Boulder's student union legislative council unanimously passed Council Resolution 106 suggesting CU regents, Chancellor Richard Byyny, and President John Buechner adopt a Basic Commitment to Human Rights, requiring them to take a stand against environmentally irresponsible investments and apparel contracts. The following Monday, April 5, WAAKE-UP! held a press conference asking the University to abandon its institutional neutrality policy for a \"institutional integrity policy.\" WAAKE-UP! members asked the University of Colorado to stop investing in corporations committing human rights violations even if the investments were more lucrative than [[Socially responsible investing|socially responsible alternatives]]. Specifically, WAAKE-UP! members were displeased with the University's investments in corporations like [[Chevron Corporation|Chevron]], [[Royal Dutch Shell]], [[Louisiana-Pacific]], [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]], [[Lehman Brothers]] (the parent company of [[Peabody Energy|Peabody Coal]]), [[Texaco]] and [[Unocal]].<ref name=\"NEUTRALITY\"/>\n\nWAAKE-UP! faxed and emailed documentation violations of the [[Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] committed by corporations invested in by the [[University of Colorado system|University of Colorado]] to the regents, Byyny and Buechner, demanding they support Council Resolution 106 by April 12. None of the University officials responded.<ref name=\"NEUTRALITY\"/>\n\nApril 26, 1999, WAAKE-UP! held a rally at the Dalton Trumbo Fountain outside the University Memorial Center on the CU-Boulder campus encouraging the [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]], to dissolve the University's neutrality policy on investments and sign a basic commitment to [[human rights]]. Byyny refused to meet with the protesters. In response, WAAKE-UP! organized a protest on April 28, 1999, blocking traffic at the intersection of Broadway and Regent Drive (located on the edge of the Boulder campus) until Byyny agreed to speak with them. He scheduled an appointment to speak with WAAKE-UP! members on April 30, 1999, at 8 a.m.<ref name=\"CODAILY041999\">{{cite news|author=Oakland L. Childers|title=Group brings U. Colorado-investments protest to the boulevard|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-21355301.html|newspaper=Colorado Daily|date=1999-04-28|accessdate=2010-01-03}}{{Dead link|date=April 2016}}</ref> WAAKE-UP! continued to organize and grow over the next year.<ref name=\"POSTSDEMANDS\">{{cite news|author=Pamela White |date=2000-03-03 |title=WAAKE-UP! student group posts demands at U. Colorado |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-21 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25241456.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200402/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25241456.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===March 2000===\nMarch 2, 2000, and again on March 15, 2000, WAAKE-UP! presented Chancellor Richard Byyny with a series of demands to ensure ethical apparel licensing was practiced by the University of Colorado. Byyny responded that he would consider adopting them but needed time, more community input, and expressed some specific concerns. Byyny questioned whether one of WAAKE-UP!'s demands, [[equal pay for women]] making [[University of Colorado system|University of Colorado]] apparel, was a [[human right]] or a [[cultural norm]]. According to the [[United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] it is not a cultural norm, Article 23, Section 2 states: \"Everyone, without any discrimination, has the right to equal pay for equal work.\"<ref name=\"POSTSDEMANDS\"/><ref name=\"CODAILY03172000\">{{cite news|author=Pamela White|title=Opinion: Byyny fails CU at WAAKE-UP! talks: Spirit of Norlin dead at CU|date=2000-03-17|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020308001325/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/17|archivedate=2002-03-08}}</ref><ref name=\"MEASURES\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |title=U. Colorado chancellor, students debate anti-sweatshop measures |date=2000-03-16 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25493515.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200506/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25493515.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nMarch 19, 2000, WAAKE-UP! members protested outside of the [[Abercrombie & Fitch]] store on the [[Pearl Street Mall]] in [[Boulder, Colorado]], a few blocks away from the CU-Boulder campus. WAAKE-UP! claimed Abercrombie & Fitch laborers were exploited and worked in [[sweatshop]] conditions.<ref name=\"CODAILY03202000\">{{cite news|title=Colorado Daily Front Page|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/20|newspaper=Colorado Daily|date=2000-03-20|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020308001325/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/20|archivedate=2002-03-08}}</ref>\n\nMarch 21, 2000, CU-Boulder professor [[Ira Chernus]] announced that he had written a resolution in support of WAAKE-UP!'s demands and that it would be voted on during the next Boulder Faculty Assembly. It included creating a Code of Conduct for Ethical Apparel Licensing as well as an Investment Board of Ethics which would be monitored by an Internal Advisory Board for compliance with the Code of Conduct.<ref name=\"CODAILY03222000\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=CU profs may support Code: BFA to consider sweatshop resolution|date=2000-03-17|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]}}</ref> This was in addition to resolutions passed by the Assembly on March 13, 2000, calling for WAAKE-UP!, Byyny, and Vice Chancellor Ronald Stump to continue a good-faith discussion on University of Colorado apparel licensing.<ref name=\"BEER2000A\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/MOTRES/xr1-0300.html |title=BFAX-R-1-0300: Facilitation |accessdate=2010-01-03 |author=Francis A. Beer |author2=Sierra Swearingen |author3=Britt Cartrite |date=2000-03-13 |archivedate=2010-01-03 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUlQw1Z9?url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/MOTRES/xr1-0300.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> The resolutions were forwarded to the Chancellor's office on March 14, 2000.<ref name=\"BEER2000B\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/MOTRES/index.html |title=BFA Motions and Resolutions |accessdate=2010-01-02 |author=Francis A. Beer |author2=Sierra Swearingen |author3=Britt Cartrite |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUlXiCd3?url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/MOTRES/index.html |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"BEER2000C\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/EXCOM/XMINARCH/XARCH00/031300.html |title=BFA Executive Committee Minutes |accessdate=2010-01-03 |author=Francis A. Beer |author2=Sierra Swearingen |author3=Britt Cartrite |date=2000-03-13 |archivedate=2000-09-19 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000919212421/http://www.colorado.edu/FacultyGovernance/EXCOM/XMINARCH/XARCH00/031300.html |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===April 2000===\nApril 4, 2000, WAAKE-UP! held a mock trial outside the University Memorial Center by the Dalton Trumbo Fountain with the \"Sweatshop King\", a {{convert|10|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} street theater puppet. University of Colorado police officers, Detective Tim DeLaria and Lt. Michelle Irving monitored the demonstration and took photographs of those participating. Both officers belonged to the Investigations and Community Service Unit of the [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]] Police Department.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000A\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=\"Sweatshop King\" reigns: Cops keep eye on WAAKE-UP! rally, students demand \"no sweat\"|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/5%20sweatr|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-05|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/5%20sweatr|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 5, 2000, WAAKE-UP! demanded that the University of Colorado join the [[Worker Rights Consortium]] by the end of the day on April 6, 2000. Meeting this deadline would have allowed representatives from the University to attend a [[Worker Rights Consortium]] meeting taking place in New York City on April 7, 2000.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000B\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Sweatshop issue gaining momentum: WAAKE-UP! gives CU deadline to join WRC|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/6|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-06|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/6|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 6, 2000, the Boulder Faculty Assembly voted in favor of a resolution supporting WAAKE-UP!'s demands, though it didn't specifically include the requirement that the University of Colorado should join the [[Worker Rights Consortium]]. The resolution was passed on a voice vote with 30 faculty members in attendance, the vast majority voting in favor of it.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000C\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=BFA demands \"no sweat\"|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/7%20daily%20bfa|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-07|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/7%20daily%20bfa|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref> The Assembly claimed that the [[United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights]] served as a basis for the proposed Code of Conduct. Byyny created an ad hoc group of ten [[University of Colorado Boulder|CU-Boulder]] faculty, staff, and students to investigate WAAKE-UP!'s proposal. Byyny's ad hoc group's first meeting was behind closed doors, against Colorado's [[Open Meeting Law]]<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000C 2\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Habitat for humanity|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-11|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref> WAAKE-UP! was invited to attend the first meeting, but boycotted it in protest. A WAAKE-UP! member was present at all subsequent meetings.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000D\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=WAAKE-UP! will attend: But students are critical of CU administration's \"task group\" meeting|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-11|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nThe Boulder Faculty Assembly had organized three community forums in an effort to get the community input Byyny requested. Byyny never attended any of the forums organized by the Assembly. University of Colorado Vice Chancellor Paul Tabolt, however, attended one of the forums and raised a few questions, but left without giving forum attendees a chance to respond to them.<ref name=\"LANGELAND2000C\"/> Tabolt stated [[collective bargaining]] is not a right (an opinion not supported by the [[United Nations Universal Declaration of Human Rights]]) and that he believed it was fair to pay workers less than what they need to live.<ref>{{cite news|title=Opinion: CU showing its true colors|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/10%20opinion|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-10|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/10%20opinion|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 7, 2000, the University of Colorado Student Union unanimously supported WAAKE-UP!'s demand that the University join the [[Worker Rights Consortium]], passing on a vote of 13\u20130. However, this failed to produce any action from the Office of the Chancellor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Student reps back WRC: Note campus support growing for anti-sweatshop measures; Byyny's task force to meet today|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/10%20ucsu|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-10|accessdate=2007-09-18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/10%20ucsu|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nIn the meantime WAAKE-UP! was busy circulating a petition among students demanding that the University of Colorado join the Worker Rights Consortium (gathering over 2000 signatures) and on April 10, 2000, and built a [[shantytown]] in the Norlin Quadrangle on the CU-Boulder campus to draw attention to their campaign and gain visibility during the [[Conference on World Affairs]]. In reference to the conference, WAAKE-UP! members named the shantytown the \"Conference on World Despairs.\" WAAKE-UP! initially created the shantytown without the University's permission, but later obtained \"temporary structure\" permits after it was established. The construction of the shantytown started just hours before the [[Conference on World Affairs]]' opening procession through the Norlin Quadrangle. WAAKE-UP! said the shantytown was meant to symbolize the poor living conditions of sweatshop workers. WAAKE-UP!'s shantytown was reminiscent of a previous one constructed in 1988 outside the Dalton Trumbo Fountain to protest the University of Colorado's investment in the South African [[apartheid]] regime.<ref name=\"HABITAT\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Habitat for humanity|date=2000-04-11|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|accessdate=2007-09-21|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"POPPEN2000\">{{cite news|author=Julie Poppen|title=Students demand CU join consortium: Protesters want CU to be sure sweatshops don't make university-licensed apparel|newspaper=[[Daily Camera]]|date=2000-04-11|accessdate=2007-09-21|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20camera|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20camera|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"STILLSTANDS\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |date=2000-04-12 |title=Anti-sweatshop still stands at U. Colorado despite threats |publisher=University Wire |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25798656.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200412/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-25798656.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nWAAKE-UP! members stayed at the [[shantytown]] in shifts during the day and night. During the day they held teach-ins, distributed fliers, and explained the purpose of the shantytown to passersby. Among other topics, WAAKE-UP! members discussed [[Gary Barnett]]'s threats to suspend players covering up [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] logos on their uniforms. Community members and local businesses supported them by supplying food and water.<ref name=\"STILLSTANDS\"/><ref name=\"CAMP\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Camp still stands: Threat of removal doesn't deter activists|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-12|accessdate=2007-09-21|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/12%20daily|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/12%20daily|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"SWOOSH\">{{cite news|author=Ted Dawson and Terje Langeland |title=Colorado football players punished for covering up Nike 'swoosh' |date=2000-04-26 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26204539.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200516/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26204539.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref> At 3 a.m. on April 13, 2000, approximately ten people came by the shantytown and set off fireworks, threw water balloons and distributed flyers that read \"kegs not contraversy (sic).\" WAAKE-UP! members sleeping at the [[shantytown]] said they appreciated the [[nonviolent]] protest methods used by the \"anti-protest protesters.\"<ref name=\"SHANTYTOWN\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Shantytown's future uncertain|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|accessdate=2007-09-21|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14%20shanty|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\nApril 15, 2000 WAAKE-UP! members staying at the shantytown abandoned it due to heavy snow, but later returned.\nApril 17, 2000 more than 150 people attended a rally at WAAKE-UP!'s shantytown focusing on high school education and in solidarity with protests the previous day in [[Washington D.C.]] against the [[International Monetary Fund]] and [[World Bank]].<ref name=\"SNOWFALL\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Snowfall only temporary setback for shantytown|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|date=2000-04-17|accessdate=2007-09-21|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/17%20shanty|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/17%20shanty|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\nApril 13, 2000, WAAKE-UP! began meeting with the ad hoc committee formed by Chancellor Byyny. Though both sides claimed progress was being made, the University administration favored joining the [[Fair Labor Association]] over the [[Worker Rights Consortium]]. WAAKE-UP! were critical of the Fair Labor Association as much of its funding came from organizations it monitored creating a potential [[conflict of interest]].<ref name=\"PROGRESS\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Progress made on students' demands: WAAKE-UP! meets with CU on code of conduct|date=2000-04-14|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"TASKFORCE\">{{cite news|title=Task force discusses sweatshop labor|date=2000-04-14|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Daily Camera]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14%20camera|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/14%20camera|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 17, 2000, the ad hoc group put together by Byyny recommended a one-year conditional membership in the Worker Rights Consortium, though it still needed to be approved by a larger ad hoc committee, appointed by the Chancellor, and the Chancellor himself. The committee also recommended they monitor the [[Fair Labor Association]] during that year to decide if it would be worth joining. Additionally, the committee raised some questions as to how the Code of Conduct would apply to contracts [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] had with the CU-Boulder athletics department, which operated somewhat autonomously.<ref name=\"GROUPAPPROVES\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Group approves WRC: CU subcommittee endorses joining consortium for one-year trial, but move still needs Byyny's approval|date=2000-04-18|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/18|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/18|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref><ref name=\"ADAMS2000\">{{cite news|author=Emma Adams|title=No proposals from CU labor panel|date=2000-04-18|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Daily Camera]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/18%20camera|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/18%20camera|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nBy April 19, 2000 the larger ad hoc committee said it was putting the finishing touches on the Code of Conduct and were getting ready to send it to Byyny to review.<ref name=\"ONEAUTOGRAPH\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=One autograph away: CU's membership in sweatshop watchdog group now hinges on chancellor's signature|date=2000-04-19|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/19|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/19|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref> WAAKE-UP! pressured Byyny to sign it as soon as he possibly could.<ref name=\"NEXTWEEK\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Students press Byynt on WRC: Chancellor unlikely to sign agreement until next week|date=2000-04-20|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/20|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 25, 2000, Chancellor Byyny announced that he would not sign the [[anti-sweatshop]] policy approved by the ad hoc committees. Instead, Byyny made some changes to the existing policy using the committee's recommendations as guidelines.<ref name=\"WHITE2000\">{{cite news|author=Pamela White|title=Byyny ought to resign|date=2000-04-27|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20pamela|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20pamela|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nApril 26, 2000, [[Ralph Nader]] visited the CU-Boulder campus. Nader endorsed WAAKE-UP!'s demands and condemned Byyny's decision not to join the Worker Rights Consortium. Nader speculated that the University's decision might be influenced by an announcement [[Phil Knight]] had recently made, stating that he would retract a thirty million dollar donation to the [[University of Oregon]] after they joined the [[Worker Rights Consortium]].<ref name=\"NADER\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Nader backs WAAKE-UP!|date=2000-04-27|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20nader|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20nader|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nWAAKE-UP! met with Byyny the same day. Byyny gave few specifics about his decision not to follow the committee's recommendations. A WAAKE-UP! member had brought a water gun to the meeting, and showed it to the police officers present. Later in the meeting officer Tim DeLaria attempted to grab the water gun out of the activist's hand, causing it to squirt two other officers. DeLaria attempted to arrest the activist for this, though Police Lt. John Kish reversed DeLaria's decision and let the water-gun carrying activist off with a warning. Professor Ira Chernus had protested the unnecessary show of force during this and previous meetings.<ref name=\"HEAT\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland|title=Chancellor takes heat|date=2000-04-27|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20byyny|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/27%20byyny|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\n===May 2000===\nMay 3, 2000, Byyny signed a revised version of the university apparel licensing policy recommended by the executive committee. The revisions were made in a closed door meeting, and public input was not sought on the changes. The revised version required licensees to comply with labor laws and regulations of their governments, and prohibited discrimination, harassment, child labor, [[Unfree labour|forced labor]] and [[Penal labour|prison labor]].<ref name=\"REALCHANGE\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |title=U. Colorado signs apparel policy, activists promise to fight for 'real change' |date=2000-03-04 |publisher=University Wire |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26399077.html |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200432/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26399077.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref> WAAKE-UP! members were disappointed with vague language used in revision and weakened stance on [[women's rights]] and maximum hours allowed in a [[workweek]].<ref name=\"VAGUE\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |title=Anti-sweatshop activists call proposed U. Colorado code too 'vague' |date=2000-05-03 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26374850.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200922/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-26374850.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\nMay 4, 2000, in response to Byyny's rejection of the committee's licensing recommendations, WAAKE-UP! and Boulder [[Biotic Baking Brigade]] member, Sara Toombs (a.k.a. Agent Moon Pie), [[Pieing|pied]] Chancellor Byyny while he was giving a speech on the CU-Boulder campus.<ref name=\"BBB2001\">{{cite news|url=http://bioticbakingbrigade.org/communique011301.html |title=Just dessets: Sweet confection targeted CU policy on sweatshop labor |accessdate=2010-01-03 |author=Michael A. de Yoanna |date=January 2001 |newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]] |archivedate=2003-04-11 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030411190638/http://bioticbakingbrigade.org/communique011301.html |url-status=dead }}</ref> Toombs was later tried for [[assault]]. Byyny claimed he incurred numerous [[dry cleaning]] bills and that his cheek was slightly bruised as a result of the pieing. Toombs testified at the trial that she baked the organic blueberry pie herself, and that she used her training in [[nonviolent resistance]] techniques as well as the benefit of practice with friends to \"squoosh\" the pie in Byyny's face without harming him. The jury found that she was not guilty of assault but did find her guilty of [[harassment]] and [[Mischief|criminal mischief]]. Toombs was sentenced to six months of unsupervised probation, thirty hours of [[community service]], and was ordered to write Byyny a letter of apology. The verdict was considered a victory by Toombs, her attorneys, and her supporters.<ref name=\"BBB2001\"/>\n\nBefore the trial WAAKE-UP! members staged a \"sui-pied\", a demonstration where they hit themselves in the face with pies to show how harmless it was, outside the Boulder County Justice Center.<ref name=\"BBB2001\"/>\n\n===September 2000===\nSeptember 18, 2000, the University of Colorado confirmed suspicions it had joined the [[Fair Labor Association]] on May 3, 2000. WAAKE-UP! members had only learned of the decision from a discussion with a FLA representative, and were upset that they were not consulted about or informed of the decision.<ref name=\"HOYA2000\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thehoya.com/news/092200/news9.htm |title=Students Perceive Move to DLA as 'Betrayal' |accessdate=2007-09-19 |date=2000-09-22 |publisher=[[The Hoya]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929091853/http://www.thehoya.com/news/092200/news9.htm |archivedate=2007-09-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"FLABETRAYAL\">{{cite news|author=Terje Langeland |title=U. Colorado joins Fair Labor Association; student activists view decision as 'betrayal' |date=2000-09-20 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-32310150.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200847/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-32310150.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref> Following the news, WAAKE-UP! members said they would continue the campaign making three demands on the University: (1) to adopt a strong licensing policy that will eliminate the possibility of doing business with companies that use sweatshop labor, (2) form an internal monitoring board within the University of Colorado that will evaluate whether companies comply with the licensing policy and to investigate and research possible violations, and (3) to join the Worker Rights Consortium (WRC) as an external monitoring agency that will investigate conditions in the factories in which apparel is made. Although it was not in the three demands, WAAKE-UP! also asked that the University relinquish its membership in the [[Fair Labor Association]].<ref name=\"WADLINGE\">{{cite web|url=http://ucsu.colorado.edu/~wadlinge/actnow.html|author=Nina Wadlinger|title=ACTION|accessdate=2007-09-19|date=April 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010428120525/http://ucsu.colorado.edu/~wadlinge/actnow.html|archivedate=2001-04-28}}</ref>\n\n===Continued organizing and victory===\nNovember 15, 2001 former WAAKE-UP! organizer Scott Silber returned to CU-Boulder to give a talk titled ''American Jihad Inc.: Corporate Crusades for the Free Market Faith'' about corporate influence in the post-September 11 world.<ref name=\"WEEKLY2001\">{{cite news|url=http://www.boulderweekly.com/archive/111501/newsspin.html|author=Editorial Staff|title=Scott Silber WAAKEs up CU: Sweat shop activist returns|date=2001-11-15|publisher=[[Boulder Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051122202527/http://www.boulderweekly.com/archive/111501/newsspin.html|archivedate=2005-11-22}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2004 to 2006 the student groups 180 degrees at the 11th hour, CASA (Coalition Against Sweatshop Apparel), and WWJC (World Workers Justice Committee) organized on the [[University of Colorado Boulder|CU-Boulder]] campus, again trying to get the University to join the [[Worker Rights Consortium]], this time petitioning Chancellor Phil Distefano.<ref name=\"WEEKLY2005\">{{cite news|url=http://www.boulderweekly.com/archive/031705/coverstory.html|author=Pamela White|title=The triumphant return of crachers: A pissed-off corporate-crime-fighting chicken comes back to CU to end sweatshop abuses|date=2005-03-17|publisher=[[Boulder Weekly]]|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051122221510/http://www.boulderweekly.com/archive/031705/coverstory.html|archivedate=2005-11-22}}</ref>\n\nMay 5, 2005, the groups held a hunger strike inside Distefano's office, until it was announced that the University would begin the affiliation process. CASA members again went on hunger strike for fifteen days from April 12 to April 27, 2006 until the University accepted the Designated Supplier Program proposed by the United Students Against Sweatshops.<ref name=\"RMR\">{{cite news|url=http://rockymountainresister.org/?q=node/10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071009174927/http://rockymountainresister.org/?q=node%2F10|archivedate=2007-10-09|title=24-HR. Hunger Strike, Occupation Ends 6-Year CU Sweatshop Fight|date=2005-05-07|publisher=The Rocky Mountain Resister|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Other causes and campaigns==\n=== Career fair demonstration ===\nWAAKE-UP! members had requested a table at career fairs held on the CU-Boulder campus to inform students about the behavior of corporations trying to recruit them, but had been denied by CU-Boulder administration. In response, on January 31, 2000, WAAKE-UP! held a demonstration during a career fair, accompanied by [[TV Nation]]'s Crackers the Corporate Crime-Fighting Chicken, carrying a banner that read \"Students are NOT products, Teachers are NOT tools, The University is NOT a factory!\"<ref name=\"GEORGEANNEDAILY\">{{cite news|url=http://www.stp.georgiasouthern.edu/George-Anne/arc5/spr00/0131nws.html |author=TMS Campus |title=National News Brief: Students protest at U. of Colo. |date=2000-01-31 |publisher=[[The George-Anne Daily]] |accessdate=2010-01-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060909091236/http://www.stp.georgiasouthern.edu/George-Anne/arc5/spr00/0131nws.html |archivedate=2006-09-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"CAREERFAIR\">{{cite news|author=Amanda Hill |title=U. Colorado group protests career fair |date=2000-01-26 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-24764377.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200557/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-24764377.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Die-in to support the U'wa===\nMarch 14, 2000, WAAKE-UP! members staged a [[die-in]] in front of the World Trade Center buildings in [[Denver, Colorado]] to raise awareness about the [[U'wa people|U'wa]]'s struggle against the [[Occidental Petroleum Corporation]]. There were approximate 20 police officers at the protest who dragged the limp protesters away from the scene, at one point dragging a protester's head into a [[street gutter]]. One of the protesters was taken in to custody without being read his [[Miranda Rights]].<ref name=\"HALFHOUR\">{{cite news|author=Leo Griep-Ruiz|title=Opinion: A half hour in downtown Denver|date=2000-03-21|accessdate=2007-09-21|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/20|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020308001325/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/march2k.html#3/20|archivedate=2002-03-08}}</ref>\n\n===A16 solidarity march===\nOn April 15, 2000 WAAKE-UP! organized a march of more than 400 people in Boulder in solidarity with protests of the [[World Bank]] and [[International Monetary Fund]] in [[Washington D.C.]]. The protests were a continuation of those at the [[WTO Ministerial Conference of 1999 protest activity|Ministerial Conference of 1999]] in [[Seattle, Washington]].<ref name=\"INDYMEDIA\">{{cite web|url=http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/850 |title=A15 \u2013 Boulder, CO, Solidarity March |date=2000-04-16 |author=Tammi Laninga |publisher=[[Washington, D.C.|DC]] [[Independent Media Center|Indymedia]] |archivedate=2010-01-03 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUmIkxS8?url=http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/850 |url-status=dead }}</ref> On April 9, 2000, The ''[[Daily Camera]]'' published an article by Ira Chernus in support of the march supporting the protest. Speakers at the protest included Cecilia Zarate-Laun and David Pellow.<ref name=\"LOCALA15\">{{cite news|author =Amanda Hill|title=Local A15 events slated|date=2000-04-11|accessdate=2007-09-27|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20a15|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/11%20a15|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref> The protest was non-violent and there was no hostile contact with the police during it.<ref name=\"MIRRORED\">{{cite news|author =Amanda Hill|title=Protest in Washington D.C. mirrored in Boulder|date=2000-04-17|accessdate=2007-09-27|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/17%20a15daily|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040116070056/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/april2k.html#4/17%20a15daily|archivedate=2004-01-16}}</ref>\n\nSome WAAKE-UP! members, however, went to the April 16 protest in Washington D.C., and came prepared to treat protesters who might be injured. They brought medical supplies and treated people who had been [[pepper spray]]ed.<ref name=\"PLAINSMAN2000\">{{cite news|url=http://www.auburn.edu/student_info/plainsman/archives/042000/042000nprotest.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050507092543/http://www.auburn.edu/student_info/plainsman/archives/042000/042000nprotest.html|archivedate=2005-05-07|title=\"This is what democracy looks like.\" : Protests Erupt in Washington, D.C.|date=2000-04-20|author=Matt Comer|publisher=[[The Auburn Plainsman]]}}</ref>\n\n===Flatirons Crossing protest===\nAugust 11, 2000, WAAKE-UP! members protested the opening of the Flatirons Crossing mall in [[Broomfield, Colorado]]. WAAKE-UP! believed the mall promoted [[consumerism]] and contributed to [[urban sprawl]].<ref name=\"CAMPUSPRESS\">{{cite news|url=http://newmedia.colorado.edu/press/stories/pages/110.html |title=FlatIron Crossing takes shopping to the extreme |date=2000-09-20 |publisher=[[The Campus Press]] |author=Hanh Tran |archivedate=2001-03-03 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010303165340/http://newmedia.colorado.edu/press/stories/pages/110.html |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===S26 Solidarity March===\nSeptember 25, 2000, WAAKE-UP! members and other activists marched on [[Pearl Street Mall]] in [[Boulder, Colorado]]. The action was in solidarity with protests against the [[International Monetary Fund]] and [[World Bank]] in [[Prague]]. Protesters urged passersby at stores on the Pearl Street Mall such as [[Gap (clothing retailer)|GAP]], [[Banana Republic (clothing retailer)|Banana Republic]], [[Abercrombie & Fitch]], [[Starbucks]], and [[Borders Group|Borders Bookstore]] (under construction at the time) to support local business, chanting \"Take your crap back to the Gap\" and \"Human need, not corporate greed.\" This was a smaller protest compared to one following it in [[Denver, Colorado]] on September 26, 2000.<ref name=\"YOANNA20000925\">{{cite news|url=http://www.colorado.edu/AmStudies/lewis/2010/gap.htm |title=Boulderites unite with Prague protesters: Denver demonstration slated for Tuesday |date=2000-09-25 |newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]] |author=Michael A. de Yoanna |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUr1A3YP?url=http://www.colorado.edu/AmStudies/lewis/2010/gap.htm |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"PARKER\">{{cite news|title=Views mixed on local vs. outside-owned businesses|date=2000-09-25|newspaper=[[Colorado Daily]]|author=Lisa Parker|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/s2k.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040119102934/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/s2k.html|archivedate=2004-01-19}}</ref>\n\n===Buy Nothing Day===\nNovember 23, 2001, WAAKE-UP! members supported the [[Buy Nothing Day]] protests in [[Boulder, Colorado]], organized by CU-Boulder professor Kayann Short, who focused it on how [[consumerism]] affects women.<ref name=\"BND-LIST\">{{cite mailing list|url=http://www.ddh.nl/pipermail/bnd-list/2001/000050.html |title=Why Shop? Week in Colorado |date=2001-11-17 |accessdate=2007-09-19 |mailinglist=Bnd-list |last=Short |first=Kayann |archivedate=2007-10-20 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020073527/http://www.ddh.nl/pipermail/bnd-list/2001/000050.html |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"ANTICONSUMERISM\">{{cite news|author=Fred Baerkircher |title=U. Colorado instructor launches anti-consumerism campaign |date=2001-11-15 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-48239447.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516201751/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-48239447.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===The People's Summit on Globalization===\nWAAKE-UP! supported the [[People's Summit]] on Globalization, a conference discussing how [[globalization]] affects people around the world. The conference focused specifically on institutions such as the [[World Bank]], [[International Monetary Fund]], and the [[World Trade Organization]]. The conference was held March 8\u201311, 2001, and featured speakers such as [[Paul Hawken]], Chol Soon Rhie, Danny Kennedy, [[Kevin Danaher (activist)|Kevin Danaher]], Ignacio Ibarra, Njoki Njoroge Njehu, Raquel Sancho, [[Amy Goodman]], Julie Davids, Carlos Zorrilla, Michael Morrill, Orrin Williams, [[Ward Churchill]], Evelyn Hu-DeHart, Irungu Houghton, Jason Wallach, and William Begay.<ref name=\"PEOPLESUMMIT\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/StudentGroups/summit/ |title=The People's Summit on Globalization and Concurrent Events : \"A conference to educate, empower, and united people striving for justice in the face of corporate globalization\" |date=2001-03-08 |author=The Coalition for Economic Justice |archivedate=2010-01-03 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUmhfpe5?url=http://www.colorado.edu/StudentGroups/summit/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===The Rocky Mountain Rebels===\n'''The Rocky Mountain Rebels''' were a group of [[Radical cheerleading|Radical Cheerleaders]] in WAAKE-UP!. They were present at nearly every WAAKE-UP! demonstration cheering on the protesters.<ref name=\"BECKEREJ\">{{cite web|url=http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~beckerej/Home.html|author=Emily Becker|title=Radical Cheerleaders|accessdate=2007-09-19|year=2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010725092749/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~beckerej/Home.html|archivedate=2001-07-25}}</ref><ref name=\"RADICALRUSH\">{{cite news|author=Lisa Parker |title=U. Colorado Radical Rush week kicks off with film |date=2000-09-13 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-31823277.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200648/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-31823277.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===Radical Rush===\nAs an alternative to [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity and sorority]] rushes, WAAKE-UP! members held a \"Radical Rush\" at the beginning of each semester in an attempt to get incoming students acquainted with all of the radical student organizations on campus.<ref name=\"RADICALRUSH\"/><ref name=\"RADICALRUSHSITE\">{{cite web|url=http://www.colorado.edu/studentgroups/radicalrush/|title=Radical Rush|accessdate=2007-09-19|year=2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010911041255/http://www.colorado.edu/studentgroups/radicalrush/|archivedate=2001-09-11}}</ref><ref name=\"RADICALRUSH2001\">{{cite news|author=Jessika Fruchter |title=Alternative rush kicks off at U. Colorado |date=2001-09-05 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-46686422.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516201327/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-46686422.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref> The Radical Rush tradition continued after WAAKE-UP! was defunct.<ref name=\"RADICALRUSH2002\">{{cite news|author=Jenny Atchley |title='Radical Rush' week exposes U. Colorado students to activist groups |date=2002-09-03 |publisher=University Wire |accessdate=2007-09-22 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-55877917.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110516200947/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-55877917.html |archivedate=May 16, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n===This Is What Democracy Looks Like===\nNovember 30, 2000, WAAKE-UP! co-sponsored showings of the film ''This Is What Democracy Looks Like'' along with End Sanctions Now!, the Rocky Mountain Independent Media Center, AMP, Art & Revolution, [[Free Speech TV]] and [[KGNU]].<ref name=\"LOOKSLIKE1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisdemocracy.org/n30.html|title=THIS IS WHAT DEMOCRACY LOOKS LIKE|accessdate=2007-09-19|date=November 2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051215090901/http://www.thisisdemocracy.org/n30.html|archivedate=2005-12-15}}</ref><ref name=\"LOOKSLIKE2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thisisdemocracy.org/7_n30list.html|title=THIS IS WHAT DEMOCRACY LOOKS LIKE|accessdate=2007-09-19|date=November 2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061230091833/http://www.thisisdemocracy.org/7_n30list.html|archivedate=2006-12-30}}</ref>\n\n===Unity 2000===\nWAAKE-UP! endorsed Unity 2000, a group of concerned citizens and activists who protested at the [[Republican National Convention]] in [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]] on July 30, 2000.<ref name=\"ABOLITION\">{{cite mailing list|url=http://www.xmission.com/pub/lists/abolition-usa/archive/v01.n300 |title=Should political parties be able to endorse Unity 2000? |date=2000-05-10 |accessdate=2007-09-19 |mailinglist=abolition-usa-digest |last=Morrill |first=Michael |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUmotpzR?url=http://www.xmission.com/pub/lists/abolition-usa/archive/v01.n300 |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"GENDERRADIO\">{{cite episode|title=GenderTalk|series=2000 Programs|url=http://www.gendertalk.com/radio/programs/251/gt266.shtml|credits=Hosted by Nancy Nangeroni and Gordene O. MacKenzie. Featuring Daviko Marcel (transman and director of Boston's Transgender Education Network, and partner [name removed by request], on ground breaking research on health care needs for trans persons) and Michael Morrill (organizer of the upcoming \"Unity 2000 March\" in Philadelphia during the Republican National Convention)|station=WMBR|location=[[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]|airdate=2000-07-10|number=266|archivedate=2015-09-10|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910035033/http://www.gendertalk.com/radio/programs/251/gt266.shtml}}</ref>\n\n==Presence in the Denver Police spy files==\nThe Colorado [[ACLU]] was able to obtain files collected by the FBI's [[Joint Terrorism Task Force]] while working with local law enforcement in [[Denver, Colorado]] as a result of the Denver Police Spy File litigation. The files show that emails were intercepted from WAAKE-UP!'s email list, specifically about a protest planned for the Aspen Institutes's Summit on Globalization and the Human Condition in July 2000. Tim DeLaria of the CU-Boulder police department intercepted the email and forwarded it to George Kennedy in the Denver Police Department's Intelligence Unit. Kennedy wrote back to Tim DeLaria saying he would forward the email to Tom Fisher of the FBI Joint Terrorism Task Force to contact someone in [[Aspen, Colorado]].<ref name=\"SPYFILESX\">{{cite web|url=http://www.coloradoaclu.org/spyfiles/fbifiles.htm |author=ACLU of Colorado |title=ACLU of Colorado: Spy Files |accessdate=2007-09-19 |date=2006-02-24 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUkeulc8?url=http://www.aclu-co.org/spyfiles/fbifiles.htm |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn addition to the exchange about the Aspen Institutes's Summit on Globalization, it also includes an exchange between Tim DeLaria and the Denver Police Department about a march organized by WAAKE-UP! in support of the [[U'wa people|U'wa]].<ref name=\"DELARIA2000\">{{cite mailing list|url=http://www.siliconashes.net/~talbert/emails.pdf |title=Fw: MARCH FOR THE U'wa (fwd) |date=2000-10-06 |accessdate=2010-01-02 |mailinglist=waake-up |last=Delaria |first=Tim |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUn1tJ0M?url=http://www.siliconashes.net/~talbert/emails.pdf |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The WAAKE-UP! email list was one of 24 lists mentioned in a [[Freedom of Information Act (United States)|FOIA]] request by the Colorado ACLU in relation to the Denver Police Spy files case.<ref name=\"SILVERSTEIN2004\">{{cite journal|title=Re: Request under Freedom of Information Act and Privacy Act |date=2004-12-02 |last=Silverstein |first=Mark |url=https://www.aclu.org/FilesPDFs/foia_co.pdf |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5mUq2f9Sw?url=http://www.aclu.org/FilesPDFs/foia_co.pdf |archivedate=2010-01-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nLinda Gorman of the [[Independence Institute]] wrote two articles decrying WAAKE-UP!.<ref name=\"GORMAN2000A\">{{cite web|title=Linda Gorman|publisher=Independence Institute |date=2000-05-18|url=http://www.i2i.org/main/author.php?author_id=80|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061003124227/http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=288|archivedate=2006-10-03}}</ref> Gorman claimed that policies advocated by WAAKE-UP! would put the working poor making [[University of Colorado Boulder|University of Colorado]] apparel out of work. Gorman was also very critical of Sara Toombs' choice of fillings for the pie baked to [[Pieing|pie]] Chancellor Byyny; stating that at the time of year when the pie was baked [[blueberries]] were out of season and may have been imported by a corporation exploiting its workers south of the United States border. Gorman suggested Toombs should have made a [[rhubarb]] pie, as rhubarb was in season at the time.<ref name=\"GORMAN2000B\">{{cite web|author=Linda Gorman |title=Against Everything, For What? |publisher=Independence Institute |date=2000-05-03 |accessdate=2007-09-21 |url=http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=284 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928021517/http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=284 |archivedate=2007-09-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"GORMAN2000C\">{{cite web|author=Linda Gorman |title=WAAKE-UP! and Feel Better\u2014Throw the Poor Our of Work |publisher=Independence Institute |date=2000-05-18 |accessdate=2007-09-21 |url=http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=288 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061003124227/http://www.i2i.org/main/article.php?article_id=288 |archivedate=2006-10-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20010420170521/http://ucsub.colorado.edu/~amnesty/doitjust.html WAAKE-UP!'s home page] (archive.org)\n* [https://archive.is/20130415060558/http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/2535 A Video Documentary About WAAKE-UP! by Andrew Dieringer of the Activist Media Project] (DC Indymedia)\n* [https://archive.is/20130415010029/http://dc.indymedia.org/newswire/display/1479 A Video Documentary on WAAKE-UP!'s A16 Solidarity March] (DC Indymedia)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20010819074557/http://ucsu.colorado.edu/~wadlinge/news.html Archive of WAAKE-UP!'s news coverage] (archive.org)\n* [http://www.mail-archive.com/waake-up@lists.colorado.edu/ WAAKE-UP!'s Email List Archives]\n* [http://www.colorado.edu/studentgroups/18011/ 180*11's home page] (colorado.edu)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090114045548/http://www.culaborsolidarity.org/ the Coalition Against Sweatshop Abuse's home page] (archive.org)\n\n[[Category:Anti-globalization protests]]\n[[Category:Anti-globalization organizations]]\n[[Category:Environmental organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 1998]]\n[[Category:2001 disestablishments in Colorado]]\n[[Category:Student political organizations]]\n", "name_user": "NASCARfan0548", "label": "safe", "comment": "Addingshort description: \"Former student and community coalition\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WAAKE-UP!"}
{"title_page": "Heather Henson", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Heather Henson\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| alma_mater         = [[Rhode Island School of Design]]\n| occupation         = Producer, puppeteer\n| years_active       = 1971\u2013present\n| birth_name         = Heather Beth Henson\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1970|12|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (State)|New York]], U.S.\n| relatives          = [[Lisa Henson]] <small>(sister)</small><br/>[[Cheryl Henson]] <small>(sister)</small><br/>[[Brian Henson]] <small>(brother)</small><br/>[[John Henson (puppeteer)|John Henson]] <small>(brother, deceased)</small>\n| parents            = [[Jim Henson]]<br>[[Jane Henson]]\n| boards             = [[Jim Henson Foundation]], [[The Jim Henson Company]], [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center]]\n}}\n\n'''Heather Beth Henson''' (born December 19, 1970 in [[New York City]]) is a contemporary puppet artist. She serves on [[The Jim Henson Company]], The Jim Henson Legacy, and the [[Jim Henson Foundation]] Boards of Directors. She is also a Trustee of the [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center]] in Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Trustees|url=http://www.theoneill.org/about-us/trustees/|publisher=The Eugene O'Neill Theater Center|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHeather Henson was born in [[New York City]], the youngest child of [[Jim Henson|Jim]] (1936\u20131990) and [[Jane Henson]] (1934\u20132013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qctimes.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/beyond-the-muppets-jim-henson-s-daughter-creates-a-new/article_5674e2a1-9696-5290-bebc-41b72f0d5687.html|title=Beyond the Muppets: Jim Henson's daughter creates a new generation of puppets|last=Burke|first=David|publisher=Quad City Times|date=23 January 2009|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> She has four siblings: [[Lisa Henson]] (born 1960), [[Cheryl Henson]] (born 1961), [[Brian Henson]] (born 1963), and [[John Henson (puppeteer)|John Henson]] (1965\u20132014).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nHenson is a graduate of the [[George School]]<ref>https://www.georgeschool.org/heather-henson-89-hosts-student-puppetry-workshops/</ref> and the [[Rhode Island School of Design]], and attended the [[California Institute of the Arts]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.henson.com/the-henson-family.php|title=The Henson Family|publisher=Henson.com|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> Her on-screen appearances include the ''Number Three Ball Film'' and ''[[The Muppets Take Manhattan]]'', ''[[The Storyteller (TV series)|The Storyteller]]'' episode \"Hans My Hedgehog,\" the role of Prince Kermit in ''[[The Frog Prince (Muppets)|The Frog Prince]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.henson.com/jimsredbook/page/111/|title=Jim Henson's Red Book|publisher=Henson.com|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> as well as [[Frank Oz]]'s film [[Little Shop of Horrors (1986 film)|Little Shop of Horrors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/68624/11-bloodthirsty-facts-about-little-shop-horrors|title=11 Bloodthirsty Facts About Little Shop of Horrors|last=Mancini|first=Mark|publisher=Mentalfloss|date=17 September 2015|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHeather is the owner of [[IBEX Puppetry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harbourfrontcentre.com/whatson/today.cfm?id=6617&festival_id=182|title=Heather Henson Presents|publisher=Harbor Front Center|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> which is an entertainment company dedicated to promoting the art of [[puppetry]] in all of its various mediums, including stage, cinema and gallery exhibitions. IBEX projects include ''Handmade Puppet Dreams'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puppetfestival.ca/project/handmade-puppet-dreams/|title=HANDMADE PUPPET DREAMS VOL VII|publisher=Festival of Animated Objects|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> The Orlando Puppet Festival,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orlandoweekly.com/orlando/performing-arts-orlando-puppet-festival/Content?oid=2256227|title=Performing Arts: Orlando Puppet Festival|last=Shepherd|first=Lindy T|publisher=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|date=21 October 2009|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> The Puppet Slam Network<ref>{{cite web|url=http://windhamarts.org/event/2016-uconn-fall-puppet-slam/|title=Performance Calendar|publisher=Windham Arts|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> and environmental spectacles including \"Panther and Crane,\" a drama about preserving the Florida ecosystem in modern times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marching.com/spotlight/heather-henson-panther-crane/|title=Henson blends winter guard with puppetry in Panther & Crane|last=Martinson|first=Ken T|publisher=Marching.com|date=12 September 2008|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ibexpuppetry.com Ibex Puppetry Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|0378210}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henson, Heather}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:American puppeteers]]\n[[Category:California Institute of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Henson family (show business)]]\n[[Category:Jim Henson]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:The Jim Henson Company people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Heather Henson\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| caption            = \n| alma_mater         = [[Rhode Island School of Design]]\n| occupation         = Producer, puppeteer\n| years_active       = 1971\u2013present\n| birth_name         = Heather Beth Henson\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1970|12|19|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], [[New York (State)|New York]], U.S.\n| relatives          = [[Lisa Henson]] <small>(sister)</small><br/>[[Cheryl Henson]] <small>(sister)</small><br/>[[Brian Henson]] <small>(brother)</small><br/>[[John Henson (puppeteer)|John Henson]] <small>(brother, deceased)</small>\n| parents            = [[Jim Henson]]<br>[[Jane Henson]]\n| boards             = [[Jim Henson Foundation]], [[The Jim Henson Company]], [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center]]\n}}\n\n'''Heather Beth Henson''' (born December 19, 1970 in [[New York City]]) is a contemporary puppet artist. She serves on [[The Jim Henson Company]], The Jim Henson Legacy, and the [[Jim Henson Foundation]] Boards of Directors. She is also a Trustee of the [[Eugene O'Neill Theater Center]] in Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|title=Board of Trustees|url=http://www.theoneill.org/about-us/trustees/|publisher=The Eugene O'Neill Theater Center|accessdate=10 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nHeather Henson was born in [[New York City]], the youngest child of [[Jim Henson|Jim]] (1936\u20131990) and [[Jane Henson]] (1934\u20132013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://qctimes.com/entertainment/arts-and-theatre/beyond-the-muppets-jim-henson-s-daughter-creates-a-new/article_5674e2a1-9696-5290-bebc-41b72f0d5687.html|title=Beyond the Muppets: Jim Henson's daughter creates a new generation of puppets|last=Burke|first=David|publisher=Quad City Times|date=23 January 2009|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> She has four siblings: [[Lisa Henson]] (born 1960), [[Cheryl Henson]] (born 1961), [[Brian Henson]] (born 1963), and [[John Henson (puppeteer)|John Henson]] (1965\u20132014).<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Career ==\nShe is a graduate of the [[George School]]<ref>https://www.georgeschool.org/heather-henson-89-hosts-student-puppetry-workshops/</ref> and the [[Rhode Island School of Design]], and attended the [[California Institute of the Arts]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.henson.com/the-henson-family.php|title=The Henson Family|publisher=Henson.com|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> Her on-screen appearances include the ''Number Three Ball Film'' and ''[[The Muppets Take Manhattan]]'', ''[[The Storyteller (TV series)|The Storyteller]]'' episode \"Hans My Hedgehog,\" the role of Prince Kermit in ''[[The Frog Prince (Muppets)|The Frog Prince]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.henson.com/jimsredbook/page/111/|title=Jim Henson's Red Book|publisher=Henson.com|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> as well as [[Frank Oz]]'s film [[Little Shop of Horrors (1986 film)|Little Shop of Horrors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/68624/11-bloodthirsty-facts-about-little-shop-horrors|title=11 Bloodthirsty Facts About Little Shop of Horrors|last=Mancini|first=Mark|publisher=Mentalfloss|date=17 September 2015|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nHeather is the owner of [[IBEX Puppetry]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.harbourfrontcentre.com/whatson/today.cfm?id=6617&festival_id=182|title=Heather Henson Presents|publisher=Harbor Front Center|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> which is an entertainment company dedicated to promoting the art of [[puppetry]] in all of its various mediums, including stage, cinema and gallery exhibitions. IBEX projects include ''Handmade Puppet Dreams'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.puppetfestival.ca/project/handmade-puppet-dreams/|title=HANDMADE PUPPET DREAMS VOL VII|publisher=Festival of Animated Objects|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> The Orlando Puppet Festival,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://orlandoweekly.com/orlando/performing-arts-orlando-puppet-festival/Content?oid=2256227|title=Performing Arts: Orlando Puppet Festival|last=Shepherd|first=Lindy T|publisher=[[Orlando Sentinel]]|date=21 October 2009|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> The Puppet Slam Network<ref>{{cite web|url=http://windhamarts.org/event/2016-uconn-fall-puppet-slam/|title=Performance Calendar|publisher=Windham Arts|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref> and environmental spectacles including \"Panther and Crane,\" a drama about preserving the Florida ecosystem in modern times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marching.com/spotlight/heather-henson-panther-crane/|title=Henson blends winter guard with puppetry in Panther & Crane|last=Martinson|first=Ken T|publisher=Marching.com|date=12 September 2008|accessdate=9 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.ibexpuppetry.com Ibex Puppetry Official website]\n* {{IMDb name|0378210}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Henson, Heather}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:American puppeteers]]\n[[Category:California Institute of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Henson family (show business)]]\n[[Category:Jim Henson]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Rhode Island School of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:The Jim Henson Company people]]\n", "name_user": "Morganfitzp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heather_Henson"}
